{"title_page": "Saw VI", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Saw VI\n| image          = Saw VI Poster.jpg\n| alt            = Gears and machinery form the shape of a VI. The title of the film is seen near the bottom of the poster.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patrick Melton]]\n* [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]]\n* [[Mark Rolston]]\n* [[Peter Outerbridge]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing        = Andrew Coutts\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|10|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 90:10--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-vi-3 | title=''SAW VI'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 8, 2009 | accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United States<br/>Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $11 million<!--Source is in the filming section. -->\n| gross          = $68.2 million<!--Source is in the box office section. -->\n}}\n'''''Saw VI''''' is a 2009 [[horror film]] directed by [[Kevin Greutert]] (in his feature directorial debut) from a screenplay by [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]]. It is the sixth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Tobin Bell]], [[Costas Mandylor]], [[Betsy Russell]], [[Mark Rolston]], [[Peter Outerbridge]], and [[Shawnee Smith]].\n\n''Saw VI'' continues the franchise's focus on the posthumous effects of the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]] and the progression of his successor, [[Mark Hoffman]]. In this film, Hoffman sets a series of traps for an insurance executive, [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]], and his employees. Meanwhile, the FBI trails [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]], now suspected of being Jigsaw's last accomplice, and Hoffman is drawn into motion to protect his secret identity.\n\nGreutert served as editor for all the previous ''Saw'' films before making his directorial debut with ''Saw VI''. Melton and Dunstan, the writers for both ''[[Saw IV]]'' and ''[[Saw V]]'', returned to write the screenplay and [[Charlie Clouser]], who provided the score for all previous ''Saw'' films, composed the [[Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Score|score]]. Filming took place in [[Toronto]] from March to May 2009 with a budget of $11 million.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on October 23, 2009, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. In Spain it was the first film to receive a [[Motion picture content rating system#Spain|Pel\u00edcula X]] rating for violence (a rating usually reserved for [[pornographic film]]s); the rating restricted screenings to eight select theaters in that country. It was released almost a year later on October 8, 2010 in Spain with an \"18\" rating, after the producers had the offensive content edited out, according to the rating board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2010/08/04/spain_drops_xrating_on_saw_vi|title=Spain Drops X-Rating On 'Saw VI'|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate= May 18, 2015}}</ref> With gross receipts of $14 million in its opening weekend, ''Saw VI'' placed second to ''[[Paranormal Activity]]''{{'s}} $21 million. ''Saw VI'' went on to gross over $68 million worldwide, the lowest-grossing ''Saw'' film to date, but still a financial success compared to its small budget. Reviews were mixed, with some criticizing the acting and others praising Greutert's directing, improvement over the last few installments and the film's contribution to the [[Healthcare reform debate in the United States|debate on healthcare reform in the United States]]. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw 3D]]'', was released in 2010.\n\n==Plot==\nTwo [[Predatory lending|predatory lenders]] wake up in a room with a caged-in scale, wearing head harnesses with screws aimed at their temples, and the one who sets more flesh weight on their scale will survive. The overweight Eddie cuts fat from his torso, but Simone chops off her arm, and Eddie is killed when the timer expires. Meanwhile, Detective Mark Hoffman exits the glass coffin to safety and sees Agent Peter Strahm\u2019s corpse; he also notices that Strahm's right hand was unharmed. As he reviews Eddie\u2019s and Simone\u2019s game footage, he is called over by FBI Agent Dan Erickson, who found Strahm's fingerprints at the scene. Also present is Lindsey Perez, whose survival was covered up by Erickson for her protection. They learn from Dr. Adam Heffner, the coroner who performed the autopsies for all of the Jigsaw victims so far, that the knife used to cut the jigsaw piece from Eddie's flesh was only used once before, on Seth Baxter. The agents intend to find Seth Baxter's audio tape to prove Strahm's involvement.\n\nWhile at the hospital to meet with Simone, Hoffman is met by reporter Pamela Jenkins, who claims to have found something at the meatpacking plant, but he dismisses her. He later meets with Jill Tuck at her clinic, and tells her that he is taking control of the games. Jill gives him five envelopes from the box left to her in John Kramer's will, each containing photos of people to be tested. After he leaves, a flashback reveals that John brought Amanda Young to Jill, who had deemed her a lost cause, as proof that his methods work. A later flashback, as Jill delivers a package from the box to the hospital, shows that Jill met with John at the [[Saw IV|Gideon Meatpacking Plant]] before his death, where he gave her the box's key and his promise that she would be protected when the games ended.\n\nWilliam Easton, an insurance executive for Umbrella Health, meets with Debbie, the company's attorney, about Harold Abbott, who succumbed to heart disease after his coverage request was denied due to an application discrepancy. Hoffman abducts Easton from his office that night and brings him to an abandoned [[zoo]], where he and his janitor, Hank, awaken in [[vise]]s designed to tighten around their torsos each time they breathe into [[oxygen mask]]s strapped to their faces. John himself appears in a videotape and informs William that he has one hour to complete four tests and remove the bombs strapped to his limbs, or he will never see his family again. Hank, a heavy smoker, is unable to hold his breath, and is killed by the vise. William's other tests force him to choose which of his workers to save from various traps, including a [[hanging]] room, a [[Steambath|steam room]], and a [[carousel]] trap. Flashbacks show that John met William at the opening of Jill's clinic, and took issue with his formula for only deeming policyholders worthy of coverage. After his cancer was diagnosed, John's coverage request for an experimental Norwegian treatment was rejected by William.\n\nThe game is viewed by a woman named Tara and her son Brent from a cage below the observation room, which contains a tank of [[hydrofluoric acid]] and a switch marked \"Live\" and \"Die\". Pamela awakens in another cage on the other side of the room. During the game, Hoffman is called away by Erickson and Perez, who found the Seth Baxter audio tape and are having it unscrambled by an offsite technician. They inform him that abnormalities were found in Strahm's fingerprints, and Erickson eventually reveals their knowledge of Strahm's death. When his voice is unscrambled from the tape, Hoffman kills everyone in the room, with Perez mockingly telling him that everyone already knows of his involvement before she dies. He then plants fingerprints using Strahm's severed hand, before dowsing fuel on the room and setting it on fire to destroy the evidence.\n\nHe returns to the observation room and finds [[Saw III|the letter that he wrote to Amanda]] in which he had used his knowledge of her role in Jill's miscarriage to blackmail her into killing Dr. Lynn Denlon. The letter was found by Pamela and given to Jill, who uses it to ambush Hoffman as William reaches the end of his path with one second left, finding himself between the cages. It is revealed that Pamela is his sister, while Tara and Brent are Harold's family. Tara is informed by a videotape from John that she can either kill William or free him using the switch; when she is unable to make a decision, Brent angrily shifts the switch to \"Die\", causing a bed of needles to swing down and inject hydrofluoric acid into William's body, killing him as Brent, Tara, and Pamela watch in horror. Jill restrains Hoffman, and locks a new Reverse Bear Trap to his head. She shows him the sixth envelope from John's will, which contains his photo, and leaves him with 45 seconds, but no key. Hoffman escapes by breaking his hand to free his wrist restraints, and jams the trap in window bars as it activates. He then pulls his head free, ripping open his cheek in the process and screams in agony.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Mark Rolston]] as [[List of Saw characters#Dan Erickson|Agent Dan Erickson]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* [[Peter Outerbridge]] as [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Agent Lindsey Perez]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* Samantha Lemole as [[List of Saw characters#Pamela Jenkins|Pamela Jenkins]]\n* [[Tanedra Howard]] as [[List of Saw characters#Simone|Simone]]\n* Marty Moreau as [[List of Saw characters#Eddie|Eddie]]\n* Shawn Ahmed as [[List of Saw characters#Addy and Allen|Allen]]\n* Janelle Hutchison as [[List of Saw characters#Addy and Allen|Addy]]\n* [[Gerry Mendicino]] as [[List of Saw characters#Hank|Hank]]\n* [[Caroline Cave]] as [[List of Saw characters#Debbie|Debbie]]\n* [[George Newbern]] as [[List of Saw characters#Harold Abbott|Harold Abbott]]\n* [[Shauna MacDonald]] as [[List of Saw characters#Brent and Tara Abbott|Tara Abbott]]\n* [[Devon Bostick]] as [[List of Saw characters#Brent and Tara Abbott|Brent Abbott]]\n* [[Darius McCrary]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Dave]]\n* Shawn Mathieson as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Josh]]\n* [[Melanie Scrofano]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Gena]]\n* [[Karen Cliche]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Shelby]]\n* [[James Gilbert (actor)|James Gilbert]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Aaron]]\n* Larissa Gomes as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Emily]]\n* Billy Otis as [[List of Saw characters#Cecil Adams|Cecil Adams]]\n* James Van Patten as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]]\n* [[Mpho Koaho]] as [[List of Saw characters#Timothy Young|Timothy Young]]\n* Ginger Busch as [[List of Saw characters#Sachi|Sachi]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Agent Peter Strahm]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\nOn {{nowrap|May 14, 2008}}, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Kevin Greutert]], the editor of the first five films in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]], would make his directorial debut with ''Saw VI''.<ref name=\"Kevin Greutert To Direct Saw VI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/12258 |title='Saw VI' To Be Directed By Kevin Greutert |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=May 14, 2008 |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVYisV3N?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/12258 |archivedate=September 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Newcomer to the series, Andrew Coutts replaced him as [[film editor|editor]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |title='Saw VI' Director Having a 'Mind-Numbingly Complex' Experience |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=June 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVYKw9sH?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |archivedate=September 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw VI'' marked David Armstrong's last time to serve as [[cinematographer]] of the series.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\">{{cite web|title=B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew of 'Saw VI', New Traps Revealed! |url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16277 |last=Pereira |first=Mike |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=May 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mavzfr?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16277 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] again served as producers, with [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], creators of the series, executive producing. [[Charlie Clouser]] was brought back to compose the score.<ref name=\"convo with filmmakers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17736 |title='Trilogy My Ass': A Conversation with the Filmmakers and Cast of 'Saw VI' |last=Eggertsen |first=Chris |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=October 16, 2009 |accessdate=November 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3lnWewN?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17736 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]], writers of ''[[Saw IV]]'' and ''[[Saw V]]'', returned to write the sixth installment.<ref name=\"Saw 6-Sequel Plans & Rumors\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: We Interview 'Saw VI' Director Kevin Greutert! |url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13793_exclusive_we_interview_saw_vi_director.html |last=Walsingham |first=Eric |last2=DiPietro |first2=Gabrielle |last3=McCabework |first3=Joseph |work=[[Fearnet]] |date=November 17, 2008 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mM6d6w?url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13793_exclusive_we_interview_saw_vi_director.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |title=Horror Nights '09: 'Saw VI' Co-Writers/Director Talk |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 4, 2009 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mS5rra?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Melton said that the film had good pacing and a resolution for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/32714/sdcc-09-what-expect-saw-vi |title=SDCC 09: What to Expect from Saw VI |author=MattFini |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline|CraveOnline Media]] |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 25, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mWzzXL?url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/32714/sdcc-09-what-expect-saw-vi |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Greutert commented that ''Saw VI'' would have some finality to it, something he always wanted to see in the series.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> During the early planning stage for the script it was suggested that Mandylor's character, Detective Hoffman, should take on the [[American Mafia|mafia]], but the idea was quickly dismissed as not \"feeling ''Saw'' enough\".<ref name=\"shock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=12372 |title=EXCL: Saw VI's Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton |last=Rotten |first=Ryan |work=ShockTilYouDrop |publisher=CraveOnline Media |date=October 20, 2009 |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ryAuXzf7?url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=12372 |archivedate=August 14, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>   Greutert said in a [[Demon FM]] interview that [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] told him a week before filming, that ''Saw VI'' would be post-converted into [[3D film|3D]]. Greutert was upset by this, since the film he envisioned was a 2D film, aesthetically. The plans were later abandoned due to time restraints.<ref>{{cite video |url=http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node/1417 |title=Demon FM Meets....Kevin Greutert (Saw 3D) |medium=[[Demon FM]] podcast |people=[[Kevin Greutert]] and Matt Horn |date=September 15, 2010 |accessdate=September 16, 2010 |time=2:40\u20133:10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022059/http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node%2F1417 |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\nOn July 26, 2007, before ''[[Saw IV]]'' was released, [[CraveOnline]]'s horror website ShockTilYouDrop.com announced that [[Costas Mandylor]] would sign-on to appear as [[Mark Hoffman]] in ''[[Saw V]]'' and ''Saw VI''.<ref name=\"Costas Return\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=889 |title=Actor Signs For More Saws |last=Rotten |first=Ryan |work=ShockTilYouDrop |publisher=CraveOnline Media |date=July 26, 2007 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mfgsIZ?url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=889 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mandylor commented on his character: \"Hoffman is sort of torn of becoming a mad man or becoming a guy that's more composed, coming from a pure place like Jigsaw. That's my character's dilemma; does he go fucking crazy or follow the rules of the boss?\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> Greutert said in an interview with Bloody Disgusting that ''Saw VI'' would have the most characters of any ''Saw'' film to date but reassured the writers would stay true to previous storylines to prevent any \"violations of logic and chronology\".<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> A TV reality show called ''[[Scream Queens (2008 TV series)|Scream Queens]]'' aired in 2008 on [[VH1]], in which 10 unknown actresses competed for a \"breakout\" role in ''Saw VI''. Unknown actress [[Tanedra Howard]] won the role. [[Lionsgate]] made a public statement ensuring her a leading role in the film but did not elaborate further on her character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horror.about.com/b/2008/12/09/tanedra-wins-scream-queens.htm |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |last=Harris |first=Mark] |title=Tanedra Wins Scream Queens |date=December 21, 2008 |accessdate=December 21, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mlJGtI?url=http://horror.about.com/b/2008/12/09/tanedra-wins-scream-queens.htm |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2009, it was confirmed that [[Shawnee Smith]] would return as [[Amanda Young]]. Newly filmed \"flashback\" scenes would be created instead of using [[Stock footage|archive footage]] from previous entries, as had been done in the films since her character's death in ''[[Saw III]]''.<ref name=\"smith returns\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8992 |title='Saw IV' Wraps, Shawnee Update, JIGSAW! |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |last=Miska |first=Brad |date=May 31, 2007 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3gOu4EG?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8992 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |title=Shawnee Smith: \"I Can't Watch Horror Movies\" |work=[[New York Post]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |date=July 13, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/614M45DUi?url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |archivedate=August 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On April 19 it was announced that James Van Patten would return as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]], a character featured in the opening scene of the fourth installment performing the autopsy on [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]].<ref name=\"Patten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15932 |title=New Confirmed Saw VI Casting |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=April 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mp1r7L?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15932 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Peter Outerbridge]] was cast as a new character, [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William]], and [[Tobin Bell]], [[Betsy Russell]], and [[Mark Rolston]] returned as their characters John Kramer, [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]], and [[List of Saw characters#Dan Erickson|Special Agent Erickson]], respectively.<ref name=\"Saw VI Plot\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/977/977615p1.html |title=Saw VI Plot Details Revealed |last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=News Corporation |date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mvVj4z?url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/977/977615p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Russell commented about her character: \"You find out a little more about if Jill is good or evil. Pretty much you'll know.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/>   Greutert wanted to bring [[Cary Elwes]]'s character [[List of Saw characters#Dr. Gordon|Dr. Gordon]] back but Elwes was not available. He was later cast in ''[[Saw 3D]]'', though the storyline is very different than the one Greutert had for him in ''Saw VI''.<ref>{{cite video|url=http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node/1417|title=Demon FM Meets....Kevin Greutert (Saw 3D)|medium=Demon FM podcast|people=Kevin Greutert and Matt Horn|date=September 15, 2010|accessdate=September 16, 2010|time=30:20\u201331:00|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022059/http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node%2F1417|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and trap designs===\n[[File:SawVI Carousel Room.JPG|thumb|left|Concept art of the \"carousel room\" trap. Since the actors were constantly spinning, they were given [[Antiemetic|anti-nausea]] medication to prevent [[motion sickness]].<ref>{{cite video |people=Tony Lanni (production designer) |date=2010 |title=The Traps of Saw VI |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] |accessdate=October 9, 2010 |time=6:50\u20137:00}}</ref>]]\nWith a budget of $11 million, ''Saw VI'' began [[principal photography]] on March 30, 2009 and wrapped on May 13, 2009.<ref name=\"smith returns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15663 |title=Updated: Shawnee Smith Returns In 'Saw VI' |last=Miska |first=Brad] |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=March 21, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3lwsYgR?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15663 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/10/movie-projector-saw-and-paranormal-do-battle-as-amelia-looks-anemic.html |title=Movie projector: 'Saw' and 'Paranormal' do battle as 'Amelia' looks anemic |last=Fritz |first=Ben |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3m50Le8?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/10/movie-projector-saw-and-paranormal-do-battle-as-amelia-looks-anemic.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=465 |title=Another Final Day (filming) |publisher=[[Kevin Greutert]] |work=kevingreutert.com |date=May 16, 2009 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3hOhCQz?url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=465 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film was shot at Toronto's [[Cinespace Film Studios]].<ref>{{harv|Alexander|2009|p=40}}</ref>  Greutert said that the victims in traps would be more one-on-one with the trap and would be more personal to them. This was compared to ''Saw IV'' and ''Saw V'', which most of the traps were set in big rooms and involved several people at one time.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/>\n\nArmstrong told [[Bloody Disgusting]] reviewer Mike Pereira that he thinks \"visually\" ''Saw VI'' might be his favorite, saying \"We're kind of pulling back a little bit in the color palette. It's going to be more suggestive and not so vibrant, in your face like ''III'' and ''IV''. It's more neutral and shows natural flesh tones. On ''Saw V'', I pulled back a little bit and on this one, I pulled back even more.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> He commented that the \"steam room\" trap was the \"best looking\" of them all.  He went on to say, \"It's big and expensive. It's got furnaces, fires and steam. It's multi-leveled. The most complex ''Saw''. We had techno cranes flying through. It was pretty amazing.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> Commenting on the \"carousel room\" trap Armstrong said: \"It's very carnival, playground-like. It's just nasty. [There are] spinning red lights in there. It's really overwhelming to walk in and look at because everything is spinning.\" Greutert said in an issue of the horror magazine ''[[Fangoria]]'' that the \"carousel room\" was, to date, the \"longest trap scene ever\". He admitted that originally they had ten actors riding the carousel, but it was ultimately scaled down to six, to \"tie in to the [film's] title\".<ref>{{harv|Alexander|2009|p=41}}</ref> [[Post-production]] services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw6/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=Saw VI Production Notes|publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]|format=[[DOC (computing)|.DOC]] file 3.23MB download|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{See also|Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Score}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n|caption     ={{deletable image-caption|Wednesday, 13 November 2019|PROD}}\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 20, 2009\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[metalcore]], [[Deathcore]]\n| length     = 75:38\n| label      = [[Trustkill Records|Trustkill]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Saw V Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n| next_title = [[Saw 3D#Music|Saw 3D Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n''Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' includes music by the bands [[Every Time I Die]], [[Chimaira]], [[Suicide Silence]], [[Nitzer Ebb]], [[Mushroomhead]], and [[Lacuna Coil]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=48267 |title=Saw VI Soundtrack Final Lineup and Tracklisting Revealed |publisher=Metalundergrounds.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJRJhZk?url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=48267 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The soundtrack includes 18 tracks separated by three parts, each with six songs and includes three bonus tracks. It was released on October 20, 2009 through [[Trustkill Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustkill.com/webstore/music.php?id=978 |title=Various Artists \"Saw VI Soundtrack\" |publisher=[[Trustkill Records]] |accessdate=July 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJNY4sO?url=http://www.trustkill.com/webstore/music.php?id=978 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> James Christopher Monger of [[AllMusic]] praised the use of [[hard rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] music, something that had been missing since ''Saw IV''. He said in his review that \"It's a fitting marriage, as hard rock and heavy metal are the sonic suitors to horror and torture porn films and video games\". He particularly liked the songs by Hatebreed (\"In Ashes They Shall Reap\"), Converge (\"Dark Horse\"), My My Misfire (\"The Sinatra\"), and Kittie (\"Cut Throat\"), calling the songs the \"most ferocious moments this time around\".<ref name=\"AllmusicReviewScore\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=saw-vi-soundtrack-r1663952/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Saw VI (Soundtrack) Review|last=Christopher Monger|first=James|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Chances\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 23:37\n\n| title1 = [[Hatebreed (album)|In Ashes They Shall Reap]]\n| extra1 = [[Hatebreed]]\n| writer1 = Chris Beattie,<br />Matt Byrne,<br />[[Jamey Jasta]],<br />Sean Martin\n| length1 = 3:20\n\n| title2 = [[Shallow Life|The Last Goodbye]]\n| extra2 = [[Lacuna Coil]]\n| writer2 = Don Gilmore,<br />[[Lacuna Coil]]\n| length2 = 4:15\n\n| title3 = [[Lividity (album)|Reckless Abandon]]\n| writer3= [[It Dies Today]],<br />[[Jason Wood (musician)|Jason Wood]]\n| extra3 = It Dies Today\n| length3 = 3:56\n\n| title4 = Your Soul Is Mine\n| writer4= [[Mushroomhead]]\n| extra4 = Mushroomhead\n| length4 = 4:50\n\n| title5 = [[The Infection|Warpath]]\n| writer5= [[Rob Arnold]],<br />[[Matt DeVries]],<br />[[Andols Herrick]],<br />[[Mark Hunter (musician)|Mark Hunter]],<br />[[Jim LaMarca]],<br />[[Chris Spicuzza]]\n| extra5 = [[Chimaira]]\n| length5 = 4:18\n\n| title6 = [[This Is Danko Jones|Code of the Road]]\n| writer6 = John Calabrese,<br />Dan Cornelius,<br />[[Danko Jones]]\n| extra6 = Danko Jones\n| length6 = 2:58\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Lessons\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 19:19\n\n| title7 = [[Genocide (song)|Genocide]] \n| note7 = ''Saw VI'' Remix\n| writer7= Christopher Garza,<br />Mark Heylmun,<br />Alexandro Lopez,<br />Mitchell Lucker\n| extra7 = [[Suicide Silence]]\n| length7 = 3:01\n\n| title8 = [[Sleepwalking (Memphis May Fire album)|Ghost in the Mirror]]\n| writer8 = Kellen McGregor,<br />[[Memphis May Fire]],<br />Matt Mullins\n| extra8 = [[Memphis May Fire]]\n| length8 = 3:53\n\n| title9 = The Countdown Begins\n| writer9 = William Bean,<br />Brian Kemsley,<br />Ryan O'Connor,<br />Tim O'Connor,<br />Erik Perkins\n| extra9 = [[Outbreak (band)|Outbreak]]\n| length9 = 1:48\n\n| title10 = [[Still I Rise (song)|Still I Rise]]\n| note10 = ''Saw VI'' Remix\n| writer10 = [[Jonathan Donais]],<br />[[Brian Fair]],<br />[[Paul Romanko]]\n| extra10 = [[Shadows Fall]]\n| length10 = 3:27\n\n| title11 = [[Dead Again (Type O Negative album)|Dead Again]]\n| writer11= [[Peter Steele]]\n| extra11 = [[Type O Negative]]\n| length11 = 4:16\n\n| title12 = [[Axe to Fall|Dark Horse]]\n| writer12 = [[Kurt Ballou]],<br />[[Jacob Bannon]],<br />[[Ben Koller]],<br />Nate Newman\n| extra12 = [[Converge (band)|Converge]]\n| length12 = 2:55\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Choices\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 20:58\n\n| title13 = [[In the Black|Cut Throat]]\n| writer13 = [[Mercedes Lander]],<br />[[Morgan Lander]],<br />[[Tara McLeod]],<br />[[Ivy Vujic]]\n| extra13 = [[Kittie]]\n| length13 = 2:56\n\n| title14 = Never Known\n| writer14 = [[Bon Harris]],<br />Douglas McCarthy\n| extra14 = [[Nitzer Ebb]]\n| length14 = 4:04\n| title15 = [[New Junk Aesthetic|Roman Holiday]]\n| writer15 = [[Jordan Buckley]],<br />[[Keith Buckley]],<br />[[Josh Newton]],<br />Mike Novak,<br />[[Andy Williams]]\n| extra15 = [[Every Time I Die]]\n| length15 = 2:51\n\n| title16 = The Sinatra\n| writer16 = My My Misfire\n| extra16 = My My Misfire\n| length16 = 3:20\n\n| title17 = Lethal Injection\n| writer17= [[The Flood (band)|The Flood]]\n| extra17 = The Flood\n| length17 = 3:48\n\n| title18 = More Than a Sin\n| writer18 = Jimmy Craig,<br />[[James Grant (musician)|James Grant]]\n| extra18 = James Brothers\n| length18 = 3:59\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = Bonus Digital Tracks\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 11:29\n\n| title19 = [[Back in Blood (The 69 Eyes album)|We Own the Night]]\n| extra19 = [[The 69 Eyes]]\n| length19 = 3:57\n\n| title20 = Watch Us Burn\n| extra20 = Ventana\n| length20 = 4:00\n\n| title21 = [[Apologies Are for the Weak|Forgive & Forget]]\n| extra21 = [[Miss May I]]\n| length21 = 3:32\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Saw VI'' was released on {{nowrap|October 22, 2009}} in Australia and New Zealand, a day earlier than the Canada, United States, and United Kingdom release. Most of the film's stars attended the Lionsgate annual \"[[red carpet]]\" event for the film at [[TCL Chinese Theatre|Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17809 |title=Red Carpet Premiere: 'Saw VI' |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3n7K0Hs?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17809 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave the film an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R rating]] without much content having to be edited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=480 |title=Saw VI Gets R Rating |work=kevingreutert.com |publisher=Kevin Greutert |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3iu5aKN?url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=480 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Spain, the film was rated with a [[Motion picture content rating system#Spain|Pel\u00edcula X]] rating for extreme violence, and [[List of banned films|restricted]] screenings to only eight [[Adult movie theater|adult theaters]] in that region. [[Buena Vista (brand)|Buena Vista]], the film's foreign distributor, appealed the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spain-saw-vi-x-rating-90366 |title=Spain gives 'Saw VI' an X rating |last=Rolfe |first=Pamela |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQANBXT?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spain-saw-vi-x-rating-90366 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> After producers cut several of the \"most violent scenes\" to obtain a \"not under 18\" rating, it was released in Spain on October 8, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/saw-vi-finally-secures-release-in-spain_1156379 |title=Saw Vi Finally Secures Release In Spain |publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]] |date=August 3, 2010 |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQ2KMwo?url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/saw-vi-finally-secures-release-in-spain_1156379 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe DVD and [[Blu-ray]] were released in three editions on January 26, 2010: an \"R-rated Theatrical Full Screen Edition\", an \"Unrated Director's Cut Widescreen Edition\", and an \"Unrated Director's cut Blu-ray\", as well as a [[Digital distribution|digital download]].<ref name=\"home media\">{{cite web|url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/105/1052747p1.html |title=SAW VI Sees a Release Date; \"2-Movie\" DVD and Blu-ray sets will include the original film |last=White |first=Cindy |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=December 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3oT0zIt?url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/105/1052747p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The release includes an additional scene after the credits roll, featurettes about Jigsaw, the traps, and the [[Halloween Horror Nights]] \"Saw: Game Over\" maze.<ref name=\"home media\"/> Music videos by [[Memphis May Fire]], [[Hatebreed]], Mushroomhead, and Suicide Silence were included with all editions.<ref name=\"home media\"/> The Director's Cut included two [[Audio commentary|commentary tracks]], one with director Kevin Greutert and writers Patrick Melton and Marcus Dunstan, and the other featuring producer Mark Burg and executive producers Peter Block and Jason Constantine.<ref name=\"DVD review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34849/saw-vi-dvd-and-blu-ray-art-and-details |title=Saw VI DVD and Blu-ray Art and Details |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |last=Barton |first=Steve |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=January 27, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQSV25w?url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34849/saw-vi-dvd-and-blu-ray-art-and-details |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> During its initial release, all three editions came in a \"2-Movie Set\", which was bundled with [[Saw (2004 film)|the first film]] with the original bonus features from the initial release.<ref name=\"home media\"/> The film is now sold by itself without the original ''Saw''. According to The Numbers.com, which only counts DVD sales in the United States, ''Saw VI'' placed number three its first week on the DVD sales chart, selling 220,107 units ($2,766,088) in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2010/20100131.php |title=US DVD Sales Chart for Week Ending Jan 31, 2010 |date=January 31, 2010 |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJYnKs2?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2010/20100131.php |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In comparison, ''[[Saw V]]'' sold 515,095 units ($11,326,939) its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2009/20090125.php |title=US DVD Sales Chart for Week Ending Jan 25, 2009 |date=January 25, 2010 |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJVAjf0?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2009/20090125.php |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the first three weeks ''Saw VI'' sold 443,710 units for $7,587,396.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2009/SAW6-DVD.php|title=Movie Saw VI \u2013 DVD Sales|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=February 14, 2010|accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw VI'' opened in 3,036 theaters on 4,000 screens<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2621&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Paranormal' Rages, 'Saw' Dulls|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=October 26, 2009|accessdate=November 9, 2010}}</ref> and earned $6.9 million on its opening day, in second place behind ''[[Paranormal Activity]]'' which grossed $7.5 million that day during its second weekend of wide release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/daily/chart/?sortdate=2009-10-23&p=.htm | title=Daily Box Office for Friday, October 23, 2009 | work=Box Office Mojo | date=October 23, 2009 | accessdate=November 24, 2009}}</ref>  It grossed $14.1 million its opening weekend,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2009&wknd=43&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 23\u201325, 2009 | date=October 25, 2009 | accessdate=November 24, 2009}}</ref> which is the lowest of all the ''Saw'' films.<ref name=\"saw.vs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?view=weekend&id=sawvs.htm | title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw' | work=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> It remained at number two behind ''Paranormal Activity'' which was playing on only 64% as many screens as ''Saw VI'', but made 67% more money.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4569 | title=Weekend Estimates: Paranormal Activity Knocks Saw from its Throne | work= The Numbers | publisher=Nash Information Services | date=October 25, 2009 | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1932154,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |title=Box-Office Bloodbath: Paranormal Slays Saw VI |last=Corliss |first=Richard |date=October 26, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1AkR3b?url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1932154,00.html |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Halloween weekend, it moved down to number six and made $5.2 million, a 63% decrease in ticket sales from the previous weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=44&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 30 \u2013 November 1, 2009 | date=October 30, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> By its third weekend it declined in sales by 61% and was removed from 945 theaters. It fell into 11th place with $2 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2009&wknd=45&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 6\u20138, 2009 | date=November 8, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> By its fourth weekend, ticket sales declined by 78% and the film was pulled from 1,314 theaters; it made $449,512.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=46&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 13\u201315, 2009 | date=November 15, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> On its fifth and final weekend it made $91,875, an 80% decrease, and it was pulled from an additional 599 theaters. It was being shown in 178 theaters by the end of its run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=47&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 20\u201322, 2009 | date=November 22, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> The film closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|November 24, 2009}}, after only 35 days.<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw6.htm|title=Saw VI (2009)|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Saw VI'' began its international run in tenth place with $4.7 million on 946 screens in 11 markets. It opened in the [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] in second place behind ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'', grossing $2.6 million on 375 screens. In [[Cinema of Australia|Australia]], it opened at fourth place with earnings of $846,000 on 164 screens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4581 |title=International Details \u2013 An Ugly Milestone |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1F8Pd9?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4581 |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In its second week it came in eighth place with $4.4 million on 1,229 screens in 20 markets for a total of $11.8 million. The film opened in third place in [[Cinema of Russia|Russia]] with $1.1 million on 273 screens while it fell to fourth place in the United Kingdom with $1.5 million on 381 screens over the weekend for a total of $6.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4595 |title=International Details \u2013 Not Taking Any Chances |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=November 7, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1I1tdz?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4595 |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw VI'' was released in [[Cinema of Spain|Spain]] on {{nowrap|October 8, 2010}} and grossed $1.2 million on its opening weekend in 211 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secure.boxofficemojo.com/intl/spain/?yr=2010&wk=41&p=.htm|title=Spain Box Office, October 8\u201310, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|date=October 10, 2010|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> The film has come to gross $27.6 million in the [[Cinema of the United States|United States]] and [[Cinema of Canada|Canada]], and $40.5 million in other markets, for a worldwide total of $68.2 million; making it the lowest-grossing film of the series.<ref name=\"saw.vs\"/><ref name=\"bom\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)  \n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n!colspan=\"3\"  align=\"center\" | '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''United States/Canada'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other markets'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 23, 2009\n|align=\"center\" | $11,000,000\n|$27,693,292\n|$40,540,337\n|$68,233,629\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response {{anchor|Critics}}===\n''Saw VI'' was not screened in advance for critics.<ref name=\"SA\">{{cite web|url=http://bandsawselect.com |title=Audience becomes the final piece of band saw in puzzle for 'Saw 3D' |last=Johnson |first=Robert |work=[[San Antonio Express]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=October 28, 2010 |accessdate=October 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105011200/http://bandsawselect.com/ |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref> The film received mixed reviews from film critics, and garnered the \nsecond best critical reception out of the series, after ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' (2004). [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 39% of 72 critics have given the film a positive review, with an average rating of 4.3 out of 10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"It won't earn the franchise many new fans, but ''Saw VI'' is a surprising step up for what has become an intricately grisly annual tradition.\"<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/| title=Saw VI (2009) | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango Media]]| accessdate = March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a weighted average rating of 30 out of 100, based on 12 reviews, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews| title=Saw VI Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate= March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade moviegoers gave the film was a \"C\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/26/business/fi-ct-boxoffice26/2|title='Paranormal Activity' cuts off 'Saw VI' at the box office|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 26, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024120152/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/26/business/fi-ct-boxoffice26/2 |archivedate=October 24, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Tobin Bell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|Although [[Tobin Bell]]'s character was killed in ''[[Saw III]]'', his Jigsaw persona sustains a crucial part in every sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2010/07/23/2010-07-23_final_cut_saw_3d_to_end_the_horror_franchise_for_good.html |title=Final cut: 'Saw 3D' to end the horror franchise for good |last=Benigno |first=Anthony |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]] |date=July 23, 2010 |accessdate=September 7, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jV4V23t?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-07-23/entertainment/27070673_1_usa-today-full-circle-serial-killer |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said that \"''Saw VI'' is the thinnest, draggiest, and most tediously preachy of the ''Saw'' films. It's the first one that's more or less consumed by backstory\u2014which is to say, it's one of those hollow franchise placeholders in which far too many fragments from the previous sequels keep popping up in flashbacks.\" He said, \"If your goal is to do a quick study for a round of ''Saw'' [[Trivial Pursuit]], then this may be the movie for you. If you're looking to be jolted into fear or queasy laughter, skip this sequel and hope that the producers get their sick act together next time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20315066,00.html |author=Gleiberman, Owen |title=Saw VI Review (2009) |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=October 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nUcWjW?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20315066,00.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live |author-link=Owen Gleiberman }}</ref> Rob Nelson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote, \"Squeezing another pint of blood from its [[Splatter film#Torture porn|torture-porn]] corpus, Lionsgate slays again with ''Saw VI'', a film so frighteningly familiar it could well be called 'Saw It Already'. At least the requisite moralism is more playful than pious in this edition\", but added, \"Presumably owing to director Kevin Greutert's work as editor of all five previous ''Saw'' pics, the film's juggling of chronology is the franchise's best....\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442 |last=Nelson |first=Rob |title=Saw VI Movie Review |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nfI0IX?url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442.html?categoryid=3478&cs=1 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Christopher Monfette of [[IGN|IGN Movies]] rated ''Saw VI'' three out of five and wrote that \"while ''Saw VI'' certainly offers a redemption for the series and the promise of a coming power struggle for Jigsaw's legacy, ''Saw \u2166'' will no doubt mark the time to either shake things up or watch this franchise get the ax\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/103/1038167p1.html |title=Saw VI Review at IGN |last=Monfette |first=Christopher |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nq7AAS?url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/103/1038167p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said, \"If this is torture porn, it's as if it was designed to be enjoyed by [[Michael Moore]].\"  He closed his review saying, \"As usual, what gives the film whatever interest it has -- beyond satisfying the rapacious appetites of gore aficionados -- is the moral element attached to the various [[Rube Goldberg]]-style set pieces. Here, it's exemplified by a well-staged sequence in which a man must choose who lives or dies during a particularly lethal variation of musical chairs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699 |title=Saw VI \u2013 Film Review |last=Scheck |first=Frank |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQpk10a?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Roger Moore of ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave the film two out of five stars. He said the script \"has a more lyrical bent, and a more satiric bite, than any of the other ''Saw'' sequels\" and called the acting \"perfunctory on most fronts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/orl-movie-review-saw-vi,0,5498571.story |title=Movie review: Saw VI -- 2 out of 5 stars |last=Moore |first=Roger |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss5g3eh0?url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/orl-movie-review-saw-vi,0,5498571.story |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Robert Abele of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a negative review, writing \"But, really, do reformers and victims of callous health insurers really want a guy with a penchant for elaborately constructed death panels of his own to be their advocate? Elsewhere, the usual critiques apply: terrible acting, zero suspense, laughable logic and the promise of another one next year. How can we get this policy canceled?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calendarlive.com/movies/reviews/cl-et-saw23-2009oct24,0,7768845.story |last=Abele |first=Robert |title='Saw VI' takes a stab at healthcare reform |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company |date=October 24, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091104063148/http://www.calendarlive.com/movies/reviews/cl-et-saw23-2009oct24%2C0%2C7768845.story |archivedate=November 4, 2009 }}</ref> Chris Hewitt of the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' gave the film a negative review. He was displeased that the film offered nothing new saying, \"The first three ''Saw'' movies had some intriguing ideas and an unusual way of presenting them, but the three most recent films have barely bothered to come up with anything fresh.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hewitt|first=Chris|date=October 24, 2009 |title=Saw It All Before \u2013 'Saw VI' Offers Nothing New|journal=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |location=[[Minnesota]]|volume= |page=C1}}</ref>  [[Kim Newman]] of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' gave the film three out of five, stating \"''Saw VI'' gets back to ''Saw'' basics in gripping, gruesome manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136589 |title=Review of Saw VI |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=October 25, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o1Itnw?url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136589 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Wesley Morris]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' gave the film a two and half out of four stars saying, \"Who knew that the franchise's creators would eventually find a plot twist that made sense? Who knew they'd realize that Tobin Bell's righteous killer had current-events value? Given our cable-news climate, it's not beyond imagining that John Kramer could have his own populist TV show: 'Jigsaw's Death Panel'?\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://articles.boston.com/2009-10-26/ae/29261477_1_sequels-health-insurance-horror |title=It's a horror sequel and a health-care initiative |page=7 |last=Morris |first=Wesley |authorlink=Wesley Morris |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=October 26, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss4gVK4z?url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2009/10/26/new_saw_sequel_is_a_horror_flick_and_a_health_care_initiative/ |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Blake French of [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC Filmcritic]] gave the film three and a half out of five, writing, \"Director Kevin Greutert hasn't helmed a lot of films in the past, but he did edit all of the previous ''Saw''s. As it turns out, his mastered craft lends well to directing. He spins a taut, tight, concise web of terror and surprise. The best entry in the series since ''Saw II.''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcritic.com/reviews/2009/saw-vi/ |title=Saw VI Movie Review |last=French |first=Blake |work=[[Filmcritic.com|AMC Filmcritic]] |publisher=[[Rainbow Media]] |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o4H7ap?url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/Saw-VI |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brad Miska of [[Bloody Disgusting]] gave the film seven out of ten and wrote \"''Saw VI'' is faithful to the franchise and the twist/finale are 100% satisfying. ''Saw'' fans will walk out of the theater with their fists in the air with the feeling that they've reclaimed their beloved franchise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/film/1831/review |title=Saw VI Movie Reviews |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=October 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o8mdc4?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/film/1831/review |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' gave the film one and half out of five stars, saying \"Enshrouding the whole gooey mess in the already blood-spattered surgical garb of the ongoing health care debate is a crafty move on the screenwriters' part, but once you get past that pseudo-ironic touch, this Saw is no more or less disturbing than any other in the series\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2009-10-30/saw-vi/ |title=Saw VI |last=Sovlov |first=Marc |work=[[Austin Chronicle]] |publisher=Austin Chronicle Corp |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss4jDsoM?url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid:896634\\\\ |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* [http://bandsawexpert.net/ Top 8 band saw] ( November 2015)\n* {{cite journal|last=Alexander|first=Chris|authorlink=Chris Alexander (editor)|title=Saw VI: Audiences Sick|journal=[[Fangoria]]|issn=0164-2111|number=288|date=November 2009|pages=38\u201343|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|1233227|Saw VI}}\n*{{metacritic film|saw-vi|Saw VI}}\n*{{mojo title|saw6|Saw VI}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|saw_VI|Saw VI}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Kevin Greutert}}\n{{Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 6}}\n[[Category:Saw films|6]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2009 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kevin Greutert]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:2009 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Saw VI\n| image          = Saw VI Poster.jpg\n| alt            = Gears and machinery form the shape of a VI. The title of the film is seen near the bottom of the poster.\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patrick Melton]]\n* [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]]\n* [[Mark Rolston]]\n* [[Peter Outerbridge]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing        = Andrew Coutts\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2009|10|23|United States}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 90:10--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-vi-3 | title=''SAW VI'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 8, 2009 | accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United States<br/>Canada\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $11 million<!--Source is in the filming section. -->\n| gross          = $68.2 million<!--Source is in the box office section. -->\n}}\n'''''Saw VI''''' is a 2009 [[horror film]] directed by [[Kevin Greutert]] (in his feature directorial debut) from a screenplay by [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]]. It is the sixth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Tobin Bell]], [[Costas Mandylor]], [[Betsy Russell]], [[Mark Rolston]], [[Peter Outerbridge]], and [[Shawnee Smith]].\n\n''Saw VI'' continues the franchise's focus on the posthumous effects of the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]] and the progression of his successor, [[Mark Hoffman]]. In this film, Hoffman sets a series of traps for an insurance executive, [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]], and his employees. Meanwhile, the FBI trails [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]], now suspected of being Jigsaw's last accomplice, and Hoffman is drawn into motion to protect his secret identity.\n\nGreutert served as editor for all the previous ''Saw'' films before making his directorial debut with ''Saw VI''. Melton and Dunstan, the writers for both ''[[Saw IV]]'' and ''[[Saw V]]'', returned to write the screenplay and [[Charlie Clouser]], who provided the score for all previous ''Saw'' films, composed the [[Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Score|score]]. Filming took place in [[Toronto]] from March to May 2009 with a budget of $11 million.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on October 23, 2009, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. In Spain it was the first film to receive a [[Motion picture content rating system#Spain|Pel\u00edcula X]] rating for violence (a rating usually reserved for [[pornographic film]]s); the rating restricted screenings to eight select theaters in that country. It was released almost a year later on October 8, 2010 in Spain with an \"18\" rating, after the producers had the offensive content edited out, according to the rating board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starpulse.com/news/index.php/2010/08/04/spain_drops_xrating_on_saw_vi|title=Spain Drops X-Rating On 'Saw VI'|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate= May 18, 2015}}</ref> With gross receipts of $14 million in its opening weekend, ''Saw VI'' placed second to ''[[Paranormal Activity]]''{{'s}} $21 million. ''Saw VI'' went on to gross over $68 million worldwide, the lowest-grossing ''Saw'' film to date, but still a financial success compared to its small budget. Reviews were mixed, with some criticizing the acting and others praising Greutert's directing, improvement over the last few installments and the film's contribution to the [[Healthcare reform debate in the United States|debate on healthcare reform in the United States]]. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw 3D]]'', was released in 2010.\n\n==Plot==\nTwo [[Predatory lending|predatory lenders]] wake up in a room with a caged-in scale, wearing head harnesses with screws aimed at their temples, and the one who sets more flesh weight on their scale will survive. The overweight Eddie cuts fat from his torso, but Simone chops off her arm, and Eddie is killed when the timer expires. Meanwhile, Detective Mark Hoffman exits the glass coffin to safety and sees Agent Peter Strahm\u2019s corpse; he also notices that Strahm's right hand was unharmed. As he reviews Eddie\u2019s and Simone\u2019s game footage, he is called over by FBI Agent Dan Erickson, who found Strahm's fingerprints at the scene. Also present is Lindsey Perez, whose survival was covered up by Erickson for her protection. They learn from Dr. Adam Heffner, the coroner who performed the autopsies for all of the Jigsaw victims so far, that the knife used to cut the jigsaw piece from Eddie's flesh was only used once before, on Seth Baxter. The agents intend to find Seth Baxter's audio tape to prove Strahm's involvement.\n\nWhile at the hospital to meet with Simone, Hoffman is met by reporter Pamela Jenkins, who claims to have found something at the meatpacking plant, but he dismisses her. He later meets with Jill Tuck at her clinic, and tells her that he is taking control of the games. Jill gives him five envelopes from the box left to her in John Kramer's will, each containing photos of people to be tested. After he leaves, a flashback reveals that John brought Amanda Young to Jill, who had deemed her a lost cause, as proof that his methods work. A later flashback, as Jill delivers a package from the box to the hospital, shows that Jill met with John at the [[Saw IV|Gideon Meatpacking Plant]] before his death, where he gave her the box's key and his promise that she would be protected when the games ended.\n\nWilliam Easton, an insurance executive for Umbrella Health, meets with Debbie, the company's attorney, about Harold Abbott, who succumbed to heart disease after his coverage request was denied due to an application discrepancy. Hoffman abducts Easton from his office that night and brings him to an abandoned [[zoo]], where he and his janitor, Hank, awaken in [[vise]]s designed to tighten around their torsos each time they breathe into [[oxygen mask]]s strapped to their faces. John himself appears in a videotape and informs William that he has one hour to complete four tests and remove the bombs strapped to his limbs, or he will never see his family again. Hank, a heavy smoker, is unable to hold his breath, and is killed by the vise. William's other tests force him to choose which of his workers to save from various traps, including a [[hanging]] room, a [[Steambath|steam room]], and a [[carousel]] trap. Flashbacks show that John met William at the opening of Jill's clinic, and took issue with his formula for only deeming policyholders worthy of coverage. After his cancer was diagnosed, John's coverage request for an experimental Norwegian treatment was rejected by William.\n\nThe game is viewed by a woman named Tara and her son Brent from a cage below the observation room, which contains a tank of [[hydrofluoric acid]] and a switch marked \"Live\" and \"Die\". Pamela awakens in another cage on the other side of the room. During the game, Hoffman is called away by Erickson and Perez, who found the Seth Baxter audio tape and are having it unscrambled by an offsite technician. They inform him that abnormalities were found in Strahm's fingerprints, and Erickson eventually reveals their knowledge of Strahm's death. When his voice is unscrambled from the tape, Hoffman kills everyone in the room, with Perez mockingly telling him that everyone already knows of his involvement before she dies. He then plants fingerprints using Strahm's severed hand, before dowsing fuel on the room and setting it on fire to destroy the evidence.\n\nHe returns to the observation room and finds [[Saw III|the letter that he wrote to Amanda]] in which he had used his knowledge of her role in Jill's miscarriage to blackmail her into killing Dr. Lynn Denlon. The letter was found by Pamela and given to Jill, who uses it to ambush Hoffman as William reaches the end of his path with one second left, finding himself between the cages. It is revealed that Pamela is his sister, while Tara and Brent are Harold's family. Tara is informed by a videotape from John that she can either kill William or free him using the switch; when she is unable to make a decision, Brent angrily shifts the switch to \"Die\", causing a bed of needles to swing down and inject hydrofluoric acid into William's body, killing him as Brent, Tara, and Pamela watch in horror. Jill restrains Hoffman, and locks a new Reverse Bear Trap to his head. She shows him the sixth envelope from John's will, which contains his photo, and leaves him with 45 seconds, but no key. Hoffman escapes by breaking his hand to free his wrist restraints, and jams the trap in window bars as it activates. He then pulls his head free, ripping open his cheek in the process and screams in agony.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Mark Rolston]] as [[List of Saw characters#Dan Erickson|Agent Dan Erickson]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* [[Peter Outerbridge]] as [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William Easton]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Agent Lindsey Perez]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* Samantha Lemole as [[List of Saw characters#Pamela Jenkins|Pamela Jenkins]]\n* [[Tanedra Howard]] as [[List of Saw characters#Simone|Simone]]\n* Marty Moreau as [[List of Saw characters#Eddie|Eddie]]\n* Shawn Ahmed as [[List of Saw characters#Addy and Allen|Allen]]\n* Janelle Hutchison as [[List of Saw characters#Addy and Allen|Addy]]\n* [[Gerry Mendicino]] as [[List of Saw characters#Hank|Hank]]\n* [[Caroline Cave]] as [[List of Saw characters#Debbie|Debbie]]\n* [[George Newbern]] as [[List of Saw characters#Harold Abbott|Harold Abbott]]\n* [[Shauna MacDonald]] as [[List of Saw characters#Brent and Tara Abbott|Tara Abbott]]\n* [[Devon Bostick]] as [[List of Saw characters#Brent and Tara Abbott|Brent Abbott]]\n* [[Darius McCrary]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Dave]]\n* Shawn Mathieson as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Josh]]\n* [[Melanie Scrofano]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Gena]]\n* [[Karen Cliche]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Shelby]]\n* [[James Gilbert (actor)|James Gilbert]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Aaron]]\n* Larissa Gomes as [[List of Saw characters#Carousel Room Victims|Emily]]\n* Billy Otis as [[List of Saw characters#Cecil Adams|Cecil Adams]]\n* James Van Patten as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]]\n* [[Mpho Koaho]] as [[List of Saw characters#Timothy Young|Timothy Young]]\n* Ginger Busch as [[List of Saw characters#Sachi|Sachi]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Agent Peter Strahm]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\nOn {{nowrap|May 14, 2008}}, [[Bloody Disgusting]] reported that [[Kevin Greutert]], the editor of the first five films in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]], would make his directorial debut with ''Saw VI''.<ref name=\"Kevin Greutert To Direct Saw VI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/12258 |title='Saw VI' To Be Directed By Kevin Greutert |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=May 14, 2008 |accessdate=May 20, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVYisV3N?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/12258 |archivedate=September 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Newcomer to the series, Andrew Coutts replaced him as [[film editor|editor]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |title='Saw VI' Director Having a 'Mind-Numbingly Complex' Experience |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=June 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVYKw9sH?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |archivedate=September 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw VI'' marked David Armstrong's last time to serve as [[cinematographer]] of the series.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\">{{cite web|title=B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew of 'Saw VI', New Traps Revealed! |url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16277 |last=Pereira |first=Mike |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=May 21, 2009 |accessdate=May 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mavzfr?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/16277 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] again served as producers, with [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], creators of the series, executive producing. [[Charlie Clouser]] was brought back to compose the score.<ref name=\"convo with filmmakers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17736 |title='Trilogy My Ass': A Conversation with the Filmmakers and Cast of 'Saw VI' |last=Eggertsen |first=Chris |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=October 16, 2009 |accessdate=November 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3lnWewN?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17736 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]], writers of ''[[Saw IV]]'' and ''[[Saw V]]'', returned to write the sixth installment.<ref name=\"Saw 6-Sequel Plans & Rumors\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: We Interview 'Saw VI' Director Kevin Greutert! |url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13793_exclusive_we_interview_saw_vi_director.html |last=Walsingham |first=Eric |last2=DiPietro |first2=Gabrielle |last3=McCabework |first3=Joseph |work=[[Fearnet]] |date=November 17, 2008 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mM6d6w?url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13793_exclusive_we_interview_saw_vi_director.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |title=Horror Nights '09: 'Saw VI' Co-Writers/Director Talk |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 4, 2009 |accessdate=October 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mS5rra?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17580 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Melton said that the film had good pacing and a resolution for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/32714/sdcc-09-what-expect-saw-vi |title=SDCC 09: What to Expect from Saw VI |author=MattFini |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline|CraveOnline Media]] |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 25, 2009|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mWzzXL?url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/32714/sdcc-09-what-expect-saw-vi |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Greutert commented that ''Saw VI'' would have some finality to it, something he always wanted to see in the series.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> During the early planning stage for the script it was suggested that Mandylor's character, Detective Hoffman, should take on the [[American Mafia|mafia]], but the idea was quickly dismissed as not \"feeling ''Saw'' enough\".<ref name=\"shock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=12372 |title=EXCL: Saw VI's Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton |last=Rotten |first=Ryan |work=ShockTilYouDrop |publisher=CraveOnline Media |date=October 20, 2009 |accessdate=August 14, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ryAuXzf7?url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/interviewsnews.php?id=12372 |archivedate=August 14, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>   Greutert said in a [[Demon FM]] interview that [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] told him a week before filming, that ''Saw VI'' would be post-converted into [[3D film|3D]]. Greutert was upset by this, since the film he envisioned was a 2D film, aesthetically. The plans were later abandoned due to time restraints.<ref>{{cite video |url=http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node/1417 |title=Demon FM Meets....Kevin Greutert (Saw 3D) |medium=[[Demon FM]] podcast |people=[[Kevin Greutert]] and Matt Horn |date=September 15, 2010 |accessdate=September 16, 2010 |time=2:40\u20133:10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022059/http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node%2F1417 |archive-date=July 16, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\nOn July 26, 2007, before ''[[Saw IV]]'' was released, [[CraveOnline]]'s horror website ShockTilYouDrop.com announced that [[Costas Mandylor]] would sign-on to appear as [[Mark Hoffman]] in ''[[Saw V]]'' and ''Saw VI''.<ref name=\"Costas Return\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=889 |title=Actor Signs For More Saws |last=Rotten |first=Ryan |work=ShockTilYouDrop |publisher=CraveOnline Media |date=July 26, 2007 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mfgsIZ?url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=889 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mandylor commented on his character: \"Hoffman is sort of torn of becoming a mad man or becoming a guy that's more composed, coming from a pure place like Jigsaw. That's my character's dilemma; does he go fucking crazy or follow the rules of the boss?\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> Greutert said in an interview with Bloody Disgusting that ''Saw VI'' would have the most characters of any ''Saw'' film to date but reassured the writers would stay true to previous storylines to prevent any \"violations of logic and chronology\".<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> A TV reality show called ''[[Scream Queens (2008 TV series)|Scream Queens]]'' aired in 2008 on [[VH1]], in which 10 unknown actresses competed for a \"breakout\" role in ''Saw VI''. Unknown actress [[Tanedra Howard]] won the role. [[Lionsgate]] made a public statement ensuring her a leading role in the film but did not elaborate further on her character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://horror.about.com/b/2008/12/09/tanedra-wins-scream-queens.htm |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |last=Harris |first=Mark] |title=Tanedra Wins Scream Queens |date=December 21, 2008 |accessdate=December 21, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mlJGtI?url=http://horror.about.com/b/2008/12/09/tanedra-wins-scream-queens.htm |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2009, it was confirmed that [[Shawnee Smith]] would return as [[Amanda Young]]. Newly filmed \"flashback\" scenes would be created instead of using [[Stock footage|archive footage]] from previous entries, as had been done in the films since her character's death in ''[[Saw III]]''.<ref name=\"smith returns\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8992 |title='Saw IV' Wraps, Shawnee Update, JIGSAW! |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |last=Miska |first=Brad |date=May 31, 2007 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3gOu4EG?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8992 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |title=Shawnee Smith: \"I Can't Watch Horror Movies\" |work=[[New York Post]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |date=July 13, 2009 |accessdate=January 25, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/614M45DUi?url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |archivedate=August 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On April 19 it was announced that James Van Patten would return as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]], a character featured in the opening scene of the fourth installment performing the autopsy on [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]].<ref name=\"Patten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15932 |title=New Confirmed Saw VI Casting |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=April 19, 2009 |accessdate=April 21, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mp1r7L?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15932 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Peter Outerbridge]] was cast as a new character, [[List of Saw characters#William Easton|William]], and [[Tobin Bell]], [[Betsy Russell]], and [[Mark Rolston]] returned as their characters John Kramer, [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]], and [[List of Saw characters#Dan Erickson|Special Agent Erickson]], respectively.<ref name=\"Saw VI Plot\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/977/977615p1.html |title=Saw VI Plot Details Revealed |last=Vejvoda |first=Jim |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=News Corporation |date=April 29, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3mvVj4z?url=http://uk.movies.ign.com/articles/977/977615p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Russell commented about her character: \"You find out a little more about if Jill is good or evil. Pretty much you'll know.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/>   Greutert wanted to bring [[Cary Elwes]]'s character [[List of Saw characters#Dr. Gordon|Dr. Gordon]] back but Elwes was not available. He was later cast in ''[[Saw 3D]]'', though the storyline is very different than the one Greutert had for him in ''Saw VI''.<ref>{{cite video|url=http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node/1417|title=Demon FM Meets....Kevin Greutert (Saw 3D)|medium=Demon FM podcast|people=Kevin Greutert and Matt Horn|date=September 15, 2010|accessdate=September 16, 2010|time=30:20\u201331:00|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716022059/http://www.demonfm.co.uk/?q=node%2F1417|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and trap designs===\n[[File:SawVI Carousel Room.JPG|thumb|left|Concept art of the \"carousel room\" trap. Since the actors were constantly spinning, they were given [[Antiemetic|anti-nausea]] medication to prevent [[motion sickness]].<ref>{{cite video |people=Tony Lanni (production designer) |date=2010 |title=The Traps of Saw VI |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] |accessdate=October 9, 2010 |time=6:50\u20137:00}}</ref>]]\nWith a budget of $11 million, ''Saw VI'' began [[principal photography]] on March 30, 2009 and wrapped on May 13, 2009.<ref name=\"smith returns\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15663 |title=Updated: Shawnee Smith Returns In 'Saw VI' |last=Miska |first=Brad] |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=March 21, 2009 |accessdate=March 24, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3lwsYgR?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/15663 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/10/movie-projector-saw-and-paranormal-do-battle-as-amelia-looks-anemic.html |title=Movie projector: 'Saw' and 'Paranormal' do battle as 'Amelia' looks anemic |last=Fritz |first=Ben |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=November 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3m50Le8?url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2009/10/movie-projector-saw-and-paranormal-do-battle-as-amelia-looks-anemic.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=465 |title=Another Final Day (filming) |publisher=[[Kevin Greutert]] |work=kevingreutert.com |date=May 16, 2009 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3hOhCQz?url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=465 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film was shot at Toronto's [[Cinespace Film Studios]].<ref>{{harv|Alexander|2009|p=40}}</ref>  Greutert said that the victims in traps would be more one-on-one with the trap and would be more personal to them. This was compared to ''Saw IV'' and ''Saw V'', which most of the traps were set in big rooms and involved several people at one time.<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/>\n\nArmstrong told [[Bloody Disgusting]] reviewer Mike Pereira that he thinks \"visually\" ''Saw VI'' might be his favorite, saying \"We're kind of pulling back a little bit in the color palette. It's going to be more suggestive and not so vibrant, in your face like ''III'' and ''IV''. It's more neutral and shows natural flesh tones. On ''Saw V'', I pulled back a little bit and on this one, I pulled back even more.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> He commented that the \"steam room\" trap was the \"best looking\" of them all.  He went on to say, \"It's big and expensive. It's got furnaces, fires and steam. It's multi-leveled. The most complex ''Saw''. We had techno cranes flying through. It was pretty amazing.\"<ref name=\"B-D Chats With the Cast and Crew\"/> Commenting on the \"carousel room\" trap Armstrong said: \"It's very carnival, playground-like. It's just nasty. [There are] spinning red lights in there. It's really overwhelming to walk in and look at because everything is spinning.\" Greutert said in an issue of the horror magazine ''[[Fangoria]]'' that the \"carousel room\" was, to date, the \"longest trap scene ever\". He admitted that originally they had ten actors riding the carousel, but it was ultimately scaled down to six, to \"tie in to the [film's] title\".<ref>{{harv|Alexander|2009|p=41}}</ref> [[Post-production]] services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw6/docs/pro_notes.doc|title=Saw VI Production Notes|publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]|format=[[DOC (computing)|.DOC]] file 3.23MB download|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{See also|Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Score}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n|caption     ={{deletable image-caption|Wednesday, 13 November 2019|PROD}}\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 20, 2009\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[metalcore]], [[Deathcore]]\n| length     = 75:38\n| label      = [[Trustkill Records|Trustkill]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Saw V Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 2008\n| next_title = [[Saw 3D#Music|Saw 3D Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n''Saw VI: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' includes music by the bands [[Every Time I Die]], [[Chimaira]], [[Suicide Silence]], [[Nitzer Ebb]], [[Mushroomhead]], and [[Lacuna Coil]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=48267 |title=Saw VI Soundtrack Final Lineup and Tracklisting Revealed |publisher=Metalundergrounds.com |date=September 14, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJRJhZk?url=http://www.metalunderground.com/news/details.cfm?newsid=48267 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The soundtrack includes 18 tracks separated by three parts, each with six songs and includes three bonus tracks. It was released on October 20, 2009 through [[Trustkill Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trustkill.com/webstore/music.php?id=978 |title=Various Artists \"Saw VI Soundtrack\" |publisher=[[Trustkill Records]] |accessdate=July 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJNY4sO?url=http://www.trustkill.com/webstore/music.php?id=978 |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> James Christopher Monger of [[AllMusic]] praised the use of [[hard rock]] and [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] music, something that had been missing since ''Saw IV''. He said in his review that \"It's a fitting marriage, as hard rock and heavy metal are the sonic suitors to horror and torture porn films and video games\". He particularly liked the songs by Hatebreed (\"In Ashes They Shall Reap\"), Converge (\"Dark Horse\"), My My Misfire (\"The Sinatra\"), and Kittie (\"Cut Throat\"), calling the songs the \"most ferocious moments this time around\".<ref name=\"AllmusicReviewScore\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=saw-vi-soundtrack-r1663952/review|pure_url=yes}}|title=Saw VI (Soundtrack) Review|last=Christopher Monger|first=James|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\n;Track listing\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Chances\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 23:37\n\n| title1 = [[Hatebreed (album)|In Ashes They Shall Reap]]\n| extra1 = [[Hatebreed]]\n| writer1 = Chris Beattie,<br />Matt Byrne,<br />[[Jamey Jasta]],<br />Sean Martin\n| length1 = 3:20\n\n| title2 = [[Shallow Life|The Last Goodbye]]\n| extra2 = [[Lacuna Coil]]\n| writer2 = Don Gilmore,<br />[[Lacuna Coil]]\n| length2 = 4:15\n\n| title3 = [[Lividity (album)|Reckless Abandon]]\n| writer3= [[It Dies Today]],<br />[[Jason Wood (musician)|Jason Wood]]\n| extra3 = It Dies Today\n| length3 = 3:56\n\n| title4 = Your Soul Is Mine\n| writer4= [[Mushroomhead]]\n| extra4 = Mushroomhead\n| length4 = 4:50\n\n| title5 = [[The Infection|Warpath]]\n| writer5= [[Rob Arnold]],<br />[[Matt DeVries]],<br />[[Andols Herrick]],<br />[[Mark Hunter (musician)|Mark Hunter]],<br />[[Jim LaMarca]],<br />[[Chris Spicuzza]]\n| extra5 = [[Chimaira]]\n| length5 = 4:18\n\n| title6 = [[This Is Danko Jones|Code of the Road]]\n| writer6 = John Calabrese,<br />Dan Cornelius,<br />[[Danko Jones]]\n| extra6 = Danko Jones\n| length6 = 2:58\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Lessons\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 19:19\n\n| title7 = [[Genocide (song)|Genocide]] \n| note7 = ''Saw VI'' Remix\n| writer7= Christopher Garza,<br />Mark Heylmun,<br />Alexandro Lopez,<br />Mitchell Lucker\n| extra7 = [[Suicide Silence]]\n| length7 = 3:01\n\n| title8 = [[Sleepwalking (Memphis May Fire album)|Ghost in the Mirror]]\n| writer8 = Kellen McGregor,<br />[[Memphis May Fire]],<br />Matt Mullins\n| extra8 = [[Memphis May Fire]]\n| length8 = 3:53\n\n| title9 = The Countdown Begins\n| writer9 = William Bean,<br />Brian Kemsley,<br />Ryan O'Connor,<br />Tim O'Connor,<br />Erik Perkins\n| extra9 = [[Outbreak (band)|Outbreak]]\n| length9 = 1:48\n\n| title10 = [[Still I Rise (song)|Still I Rise]]\n| note10 = ''Saw VI'' Remix\n| writer10 = [[Jonathan Donais]],<br />[[Brian Fair]],<br />[[Paul Romanko]]\n| extra10 = [[Shadows Fall]]\n| length10 = 3:27\n\n| title11 = [[Dead Again (Type O Negative album)|Dead Again]]\n| writer11= [[Peter Steele]]\n| extra11 = [[Type O Negative]]\n| length11 = 4:16\n\n| title12 = [[Axe to Fall|Dark Horse]]\n| writer12 = [[Kurt Ballou]],<br />[[Jacob Bannon]],<br />[[Ben Koller]],<br />Nate Newman\n| extra12 = [[Converge (band)|Converge]]\n| length12 = 2:55\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = 6 Choices\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 20:58\n\n| title13 = [[In the Black|Cut Throat]]\n| writer13 = [[Mercedes Lander]],<br />[[Morgan Lander]],<br />[[Tara McLeod]],<br />[[Ivy Vujic]]\n| extra13 = [[Kittie]]\n| length13 = 2:56\n\n| title14 = Never Known\n| writer14 = [[Bon Harris]],<br />Douglas McCarthy\n| extra14 = [[Nitzer Ebb]]\n| length14 = 4:04\n| title15 = [[New Junk Aesthetic|Roman Holiday]]\n| writer15 = [[Jordan Buckley]],<br />[[Keith Buckley]],<br />[[Josh Newton]],<br />Mike Novak,<br />[[Andy Williams]]\n| extra15 = [[Every Time I Die]]\n| length15 = 2:51\n\n| title16 = The Sinatra\n| writer16 = My My Misfire\n| extra16 = My My Misfire\n| length16 = 3:20\n\n| title17 = Lethal Injection\n| writer17= [[The Flood (band)|The Flood]]\n| extra17 = The Flood\n| length17 = 3:48\n\n| title18 = More Than a Sin\n| writer18 = Jimmy Craig,<br />[[James Grant (musician)|James Grant]]\n| extra18 = James Brothers\n| length18 = 3:59\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline = Bonus Digital Tracks\n| extra_column = Artist\n|total_length = 11:29\n\n| title19 = [[Back in Blood (The 69 Eyes album)|We Own the Night]]\n| extra19 = [[The 69 Eyes]]\n| length19 = 3:57\n\n| title20 = Watch Us Burn\n| extra20 = Ventana\n| length20 = 4:00\n\n| title21 = [[Apologies Are for the Weak|Forgive & Forget]]\n| extra21 = [[Miss May I]]\n| length21 = 3:32\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Saw VI'' was released on {{nowrap|October 22, 2009}} in Australia and New Zealand, a day earlier than the Canada, United States, and United Kingdom release. Most of the film's stars attended the Lionsgate annual \"[[red carpet]]\" event for the film at [[TCL Chinese Theatre|Grauman's Chinese Theatre]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17809 |title=Red Carpet Premiere: 'Saw VI' |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3n7K0Hs?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/17809 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The [[Motion Picture Association of America]] gave the film an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R rating]] without much content having to be edited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=480 |title=Saw VI Gets R Rating |work=kevingreutert.com |publisher=Kevin Greutert |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3iu5aKN?url=http://www.kevingreutert.com/?p=480 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Spain, the film was rated with a [[Motion picture content rating system#Spain|Pel\u00edcula X]] rating for extreme violence, and [[List of banned films|restricted]] screenings to only eight [[Adult movie theater|adult theaters]] in that region. [[Buena Vista (brand)|Buena Vista]], the film's foreign distributor, appealed the decision.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spain-saw-vi-x-rating-90366 |title=Spain gives 'Saw VI' an X rating |last=Rolfe |first=Pamela |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 22, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQANBXT?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/spain-saw-vi-x-rating-90366 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> After producers cut several of the \"most violent scenes\" to obtain a \"not under 18\" rating, it was released in Spain on October 8, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/saw-vi-finally-secures-release-in-spain_1156379 |title=Saw Vi Finally Secures Release In Spain |publisher=[[Contactmusic.com]] |date=August 3, 2010 |accessdate=August 4, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQ2KMwo?url=http://www.contactmusic.com/news/saw-vi-finally-secures-release-in-spain_1156379 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe DVD and [[Blu-ray]] were released in three editions on January 26, 2010: an \"R-rated Theatrical Full Screen Edition\", an \"Unrated Director's Cut Widescreen Edition\", and an \"Unrated Director's cut Blu-ray\", as well as a [[Digital distribution|digital download]].<ref name=\"home media\">{{cite web|url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/105/1052747p1.html |title=SAW VI Sees a Release Date; \"2-Movie\" DVD and Blu-ray sets will include the original film |last=White |first=Cindy |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=December 11, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3oT0zIt?url=http://dvd.ign.com/articles/105/1052747p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The release includes an additional scene after the credits roll, featurettes about Jigsaw, the traps, and the [[Halloween Horror Nights]] \"Saw: Game Over\" maze.<ref name=\"home media\"/> Music videos by [[Memphis May Fire]], [[Hatebreed]], Mushroomhead, and Suicide Silence were included with all editions.<ref name=\"home media\"/> The Director's Cut included two [[Audio commentary|commentary tracks]], one with director Kevin Greutert and writers Patrick Melton and Marcus Dunstan, and the other featuring producer Mark Burg and executive producers Peter Block and Jason Constantine.<ref name=\"DVD review\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34849/saw-vi-dvd-and-blu-ray-art-and-details |title=Saw VI DVD and Blu-ray Art and Details |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |last=Barton |first=Steve |date=December 7, 2009 |accessdate=January 27, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQSV25w?url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/34849/saw-vi-dvd-and-blu-ray-art-and-details |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> During its initial release, all three editions came in a \"2-Movie Set\", which was bundled with [[Saw (2004 film)|the first film]] with the original bonus features from the initial release.<ref name=\"home media\"/> The film is now sold by itself without the original ''Saw''. According to The Numbers.com, which only counts DVD sales in the United States, ''Saw VI'' placed number three its first week on the DVD sales chart, selling 220,107 units ($2,766,088) in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2010/20100131.php |title=US DVD Sales Chart for Week Ending Jan 31, 2010 |date=January 31, 2010 |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJYnKs2?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2010/20100131.php |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In comparison, ''[[Saw V]]'' sold 515,095 units ($11,326,939) its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2009/20090125.php |title=US DVD Sales Chart for Week Ending Jan 25, 2009 |date=January 25, 2010 |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |accessdate=February 24, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rVJVAjf0?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/dvd/charts/weekly/2009/20090125.php |archivedate=July 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the first three weeks ''Saw VI'' sold 443,710 units for $7,587,396.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2009/SAW6-DVD.php|title=Movie Saw VI \u2013 DVD Sales|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=February 14, 2010|accessdate=April 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw VI'' opened in 3,036 theaters on 4,000 screens<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2621&p=.htm|title=Weekend Report: 'Paranormal' Rages, 'Saw' Dulls|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=October 26, 2009|accessdate=November 9, 2010}}</ref> and earned $6.9 million on its opening day, in second place behind ''[[Paranormal Activity]]'' which grossed $7.5 million that day during its second weekend of wide release.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/daily/chart/?sortdate=2009-10-23&p=.htm | title=Daily Box Office for Friday, October 23, 2009 | work=Box Office Mojo | date=October 23, 2009 | accessdate=November 24, 2009}}</ref>  It grossed $14.1 million its opening weekend,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2009&wknd=43&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 23\u201325, 2009 | date=October 25, 2009 | accessdate=November 24, 2009}}</ref> which is the lowest of all the ''Saw'' films.<ref name=\"saw.vs\">{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?view=weekend&id=sawvs.htm | title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw' | work=Box Office Mojo | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref> It remained at number two behind ''Paranormal Activity'' which was playing on only 64% as many screens as ''Saw VI'', but made 67% more money.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4569 | title=Weekend Estimates: Paranormal Activity Knocks Saw from its Throne | work= The Numbers | publisher=Nash Information Services | date=October 25, 2009 | accessdate=January 25, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1932154,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |title=Box-Office Bloodbath: Paranormal Slays Saw VI |last=Corliss |first=Richard |date=October 26, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1AkR3b?url=http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1932154,00.html |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn Halloween weekend, it moved down to number six and made $5.2 million, a 63% decrease in ticket sales from the previous weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=44&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 30 \u2013 November 1, 2009 | date=October 30, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> By its third weekend it declined in sales by 61% and was removed from 945 theaters. It fell into 11th place with $2 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2009&wknd=45&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 6\u20138, 2009 | date=November 8, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> By its fourth weekend, ticket sales declined by 78% and the film was pulled from 1,314 theaters; it made $449,512.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=46&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 13\u201315, 2009 | date=November 15, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> On its fifth and final weekend it made $91,875, an 80% decrease, and it was pulled from an additional 599 theaters. It was being shown in 178 theaters by the end of its run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?view=&yr=2009&wknd=47&p=.htm | work=Box Office Mojo |title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 20\u201322, 2009 | date=November 22, 2009 | accessdate=January 26, 2010}}</ref> The film closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|November 24, 2009}}, after only 35 days.<ref name=\"bom\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw6.htm|title=Saw VI (2009)|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=November 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Saw VI'' began its international run in tenth place with $4.7 million on 946 screens in 11 markets. It opened in the [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] in second place behind ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'', grossing $2.6 million on 375 screens. In [[Cinema of Australia|Australia]], it opened at fourth place with earnings of $846,000 on 164 screens.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4581 |title=International Details \u2013 An Ugly Milestone |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1F8Pd9?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4581 |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> In its second week it came in eighth place with $4.4 million on 1,229 screens in 20 markets for a total of $11.8 million. The film opened in third place in [[Cinema of Russia|Russia]] with $1.1 million on 273 screens while it fell to fourth place in the United Kingdom with $1.5 million on 381 screens over the weekend for a total of $6.1 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4595 |title=International Details \u2013 Not Taking Any Chances |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=November 7, 2009 |accessdate=January 26, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nG1I1tdz?url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=4595 |archivedate=February 3, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw VI'' was released in [[Cinema of Spain|Spain]] on {{nowrap|October 8, 2010}} and grossed $1.2 million on its opening weekend in 211 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://secure.boxofficemojo.com/intl/spain/?yr=2010&wk=41&p=.htm|title=Spain Box Office, October 8\u201310, 2010|work=Box Office Mojo|date=October 10, 2010|accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> The film has come to gross $27.6 million in the [[Cinema of the United States|United States]] and [[Cinema of Canada|Canada]], and $40.5 million in other markets, for a worldwide total of $68.2 million; making it the lowest-grossing film of the series.<ref name=\"saw.vs\"/><ref name=\"bom\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)  \n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n!colspan=\"3\"  align=\"center\" | '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"bom\"/>\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''United States/Canada'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other markets'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 23, 2009\n|align=\"center\" | $11,000,000\n|$27,693,292\n|$40,540,337\n|$68,233,629\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response {{anchor|Critics}}===\n''Saw VI'' was not screened in advance for critics.<ref name=\"SA\">{{cite web|url=http://bandsawselect.com |title=Audience becomes the final piece of band saw in puzzle for 'Saw 3D' |last=Johnson |first=Robert |work=[[San Antonio Express]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=October 28, 2010 |accessdate=October 30, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141105011200/http://bandsawselect.com/ |archivedate=November 5, 2014 }}</ref> The film received mixed reviews from film critics, and garnered the \nsecond best critical reception out of the series, after ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' (2004). [[Review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 39% of 72 critics have given the film a positive review, with an average rating of 4.3 out of 10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"It won't earn the franchise many new fans, but ''Saw VI'' is a surprising step up for what has become an intricately grisly annual tradition.\"<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/| title=Saw VI (2009) | work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango Media]]| accessdate = March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gives the film a weighted average rating of 30 out of 100, based on 12 reviews, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews| title=Saw VI Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate= March 15, 2018}}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade moviegoers gave the film was a \"C\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/26/business/fi-ct-boxoffice26/2|title='Paranormal Activity' cuts off 'Saw VI' at the box office|last=Fritz|first=Ben|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 26, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2010 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024120152/http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/26/business/fi-ct-boxoffice26/2 |archivedate=October 24, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Tobin Bell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|Although [[Tobin Bell]]'s character was killed in ''[[Saw III]]'', his Jigsaw persona sustains a crucial part in every sequel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/2010/07/23/2010-07-23_final_cut_saw_3d_to_end_the_horror_franchise_for_good.html |title=Final cut: 'Saw 3D' to end the horror franchise for good |last=Benigno |first=Anthony |work=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]] |publisher=[[Mortimer Zuckerman]] |date=July 23, 2010 |accessdate=September 7, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jV4V23t?url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-07-23/entertainment/27070673_1_usa-today-full-circle-serial-killer |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n\n[[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said that \"''Saw VI'' is the thinnest, draggiest, and most tediously preachy of the ''Saw'' films. It's the first one that's more or less consumed by backstory\u2014which is to say, it's one of those hollow franchise placeholders in which far too many fragments from the previous sequels keep popping up in flashbacks.\" He said, \"If your goal is to do a quick study for a round of ''Saw'' [[Trivial Pursuit]], then this may be the movie for you. If you're looking to be jolted into fear or queasy laughter, skip this sequel and hope that the producers get their sick act together next time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20315066,00.html |author=Gleiberman, Owen |title=Saw VI Review (2009) |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=October 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nUcWjW?url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20315066,00.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live |author-link=Owen Gleiberman }}</ref> Rob Nelson of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote, \"Squeezing another pint of blood from its [[Splatter film#Torture porn|torture-porn]] corpus, Lionsgate slays again with ''Saw VI'', a film so frighteningly familiar it could well be called 'Saw It Already'. At least the requisite moralism is more playful than pious in this edition\", but added, \"Presumably owing to director Kevin Greutert's work as editor of all five previous ''Saw'' pics, the film's juggling of chronology is the franchise's best....\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442 |last=Nelson |first=Rob |title=Saw VI Movie Review |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nfI0IX?url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442.html?categoryid=3478&cs=1 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Christopher Monfette of [[IGN|IGN Movies]] rated ''Saw VI'' three out of five and wrote that \"while ''Saw VI'' certainly offers a redemption for the series and the promise of a coming power struggle for Jigsaw's legacy, ''Saw \u2166'' will no doubt mark the time to either shake things up or watch this franchise get the ax\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/103/1038167p1.html |title=Saw VI Review at IGN |last=Monfette |first=Christopher |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nq7AAS?url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/103/1038167p1.html |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nFrank Scheck of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said, \"If this is torture porn, it's as if it was designed to be enjoyed by [[Michael Moore]].\"  He closed his review saying, \"As usual, what gives the film whatever interest it has -- beyond satisfying the rapacious appetites of gore aficionados -- is the moral element attached to the various [[Rube Goldberg]]-style set pieces. Here, it's exemplified by a well-staged sequence in which a man must choose who lives or dies during a particularly lethal variation of musical chairs.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699 |title=Saw VI \u2013 Film Review |last=Scheck |first=Frank |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=September 15, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQpk10a?url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699 |archivedate=September 16, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Roger Moore of ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave the film two out of five stars. He said the script \"has a more lyrical bent, and a more satiric bite, than any of the other ''Saw'' sequels\" and called the acting \"perfunctory on most fronts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/orl-movie-review-saw-vi,0,5498571.story |title=Movie review: Saw VI -- 2 out of 5 stars |last=Moore |first=Roger |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 23, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss5g3eh0?url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/orl-movie-review-saw-vi,0,5498571.story |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Robert Abele of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a negative review, writing \"But, really, do reformers and victims of callous health insurers really want a guy with a penchant for elaborately constructed death panels of his own to be their advocate? Elsewhere, the usual critiques apply: terrible acting, zero suspense, laughable logic and the promise of another one next year. How can we get this policy canceled?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calendarlive.com/movies/reviews/cl-et-saw23-2009oct24,0,7768845.story |last=Abele |first=Robert |title='Saw VI' takes a stab at healthcare reform |work=Los Angeles Times |publisher=Tribune Company |date=October 24, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091104063148/http://www.calendarlive.com/movies/reviews/cl-et-saw23-2009oct24%2C0%2C7768845.story |archivedate=November 4, 2009 }}</ref> Chris Hewitt of the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' gave the film a negative review. He was displeased that the film offered nothing new saying, \"The first three ''Saw'' movies had some intriguing ideas and an unusual way of presenting them, but the three most recent films have barely bothered to come up with anything fresh.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hewitt|first=Chris|date=October 24, 2009 |title=Saw It All Before \u2013 'Saw VI' Offers Nothing New|journal=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |location=[[Minnesota]]|volume= |page=C1}}</ref>  [[Kim Newman]] of ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' gave the film three out of five, stating \"''Saw VI'' gets back to ''Saw'' basics in gripping, gruesome manner.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136589 |title=Review of Saw VI |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=October 25, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o1Itnw?url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=136589 |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Wesley Morris]] of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' gave the film a two and half out of four stars saying, \"Who knew that the franchise's creators would eventually find a plot twist that made sense? Who knew they'd realize that Tobin Bell's righteous killer had current-events value? Given our cable-news climate, it's not beyond imagining that John Kramer could have his own populist TV show: 'Jigsaw's Death Panel'?\".<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://articles.boston.com/2009-10-26/ae/29261477_1_sequels-health-insurance-horror |title=It's a horror sequel and a health-care initiative |page=7 |last=Morris |first=Wesley |authorlink=Wesley Morris |journal=[[The Boston Globe]] |publisher=The New York Times Company |date=October 26, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss4gVK4z?url=http://www.boston.com/ae/movies/articles/2009/10/26/new_saw_sequel_is_a_horror_flick_and_a_health_care_initiative/ |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Blake French of [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC Filmcritic]] gave the film three and a half out of five, writing, \"Director Kevin Greutert hasn't helmed a lot of films in the past, but he did edit all of the previous ''Saw''s. As it turns out, his mastered craft lends well to directing. He spins a taut, tight, concise web of terror and surprise. The best entry in the series since ''Saw II.''\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcritic.com/reviews/2009/saw-vi/ |title=Saw VI Movie Review |last=French |first=Blake |work=[[Filmcritic.com|AMC Filmcritic]] |publisher=[[Rainbow Media]] |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=December 8, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o4H7ap?url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/Saw-VI |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Brad Miska of [[Bloody Disgusting]] gave the film seven out of ten and wrote \"''Saw VI'' is faithful to the franchise and the twist/finale are 100% satisfying. ''Saw'' fans will walk out of the theater with their fists in the air with the feeling that they've reclaimed their beloved franchise.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/film/1831/review |title=Saw VI Movie Reviews |last=Miska |first=Brad |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=October 28, 2009 |accessdate=October 29, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3o8mdc4?url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/film/1831/review |archivedate=January 26, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Marc Savlov of ''[[The Austin Chronicle]]'' gave the film one and half out of five stars, saying \"Enshrouding the whole gooey mess in the already blood-spattered surgical garb of the ongoing health care debate is a crafty move on the screenwriters' part, but once you get past that pseudo-ironic touch, this Saw is no more or less disturbing than any other in the series\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/calendar/film/2009-10-30/saw-vi/ |title=Saw VI |last=Sovlov |first=Marc |work=[[Austin Chronicle]] |publisher=Austin Chronicle Corp |date=October 30, 2009 |accessdate=September 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ss4jDsoM?url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Calendar/Film?Film=oid:896634\\\\ |archivedate=September 19, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* [http://bandsawexpert.net/ Top 8 band saw] ( November 2015)\n* {{cite journal|last=Alexander|first=Chris|authorlink=Chris Alexander (editor)|title=Saw VI: Audiences Sick|journal=[[Fangoria]]|issn=0164-2111|number=288|date=November 2009|pages=38\u201343|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|1233227|Saw VI}}\n*{{metacritic film|saw-vi|Saw VI}}\n*{{mojo title|saw6|Saw VI}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|saw_VI|Saw VI}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Kevin Greutert}}\n{{Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 6}}\n[[Category:Saw films|6]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2009 films]]\n[[Category:2009 horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Kevin Greutert]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:2009 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:7ef6:9800:c5b7:fd1f:d7c:7635", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_VI"}
{"title_page": "Saw (2004 film)", "text_new": "{{about||the franchise|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film \n| name           = Saw\n| image          = Saw official poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Wan]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Gregg Hoffman]]|[[Oren Koules]]|[[Mark Burg]]}}\n| writer         = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| story          = {{ubl|James Wan|Leigh Whannell}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Saw (2003 film)|''Saw'']]|James Wan|Leigh Whannell}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|Leigh Whannell|[[Cary Elwes]]|[[Danny Glover]]|[[Monica Potter]]|[[Michael Emerson]]|[[Ken Leung]]|[[Tobin Bell]]}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing        = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lions Gate Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2004|01|19|[[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2004|10|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=Saw (2004)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw.htm|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $103.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Saw''''' is a 2004 American [[horror film]]<ref name=\"VarietyReview\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=12&ti=1,12&Search_Arg=Saw&Search_Code=TALL&CNT=25&PID=x8Cuc4HrUx9R--hShAp_UDaA4t&SEQ=20110817025227&SID=1 |title=Saw. Motion Picture |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |date=May 17, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6102VFlCf?url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=12&ti=1,12&Search_Arg=Saw&Search_Code=TALL&CNT=25&PID=x8Cuc4HrUx9R--hShAp_UDaA4t&SEQ=20110817025227&SID=1 |archivedate=August 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> directed by [[James Wan]] (in his feature directorial debut) and written by [[Leigh Whannell]] from a story by Wan and Whannell. It stars Whannell, [[Cary Elwes]], [[Danny Glover]], [[Monica Potter]], [[Michael Emerson]], [[Ken Leung]], and [[Tobin Bell]]. It is the first installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. In it, Whannell and Elwes portray two men who awake to find themselves chained in a large dilapidated bathroom, with one being ordered to kill the other or his family will die. The screenplay was written by Whannell, who co-created the story with Wan in their screenwriting debuts respectively.\n\nThe screenplay was written in 2001, but after failed attempts to get the script produced in Wan and Whannell's home country of Australia, they were urged to travel to Los Angeles. In order to help attract producers they shot a [[Low-budget film|low-budget]] short film [[Saw (2003 film)|of the same name]] from a scene out of the script. This proved successful in 2003 as producers from [[Evolution Entertainment]] were immediately attached and also formed a horror genre production label, [[Twisted Pictures]]. The film was given a small budget of $1.2 million and shot for 18 days.\n\n''Saw'' was first screened on January 19, 2004, before released in North America on October 29, 2004, by [[Lions Gate Films]]. Compared to its low budget, ''Saw'' performed very well at the box office, grossing more than $100 million worldwide and becoming, at the time, one of the most profitable horror films since ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996). The film was theatrically re-released, to select theatres, on October 31, 2014 to celebrate its tenth anniversary.<ref name=\"IGNAug2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/27/saw-returning-to-theaters-for-its-10th-anniversary|title=Saw returning to theatres for its 10th anniversary|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> A sequel, titled ''[[Saw II]]'', was released in 2005.\n\n==Plot==\nPhotographer Adam awakens in a dilapitated bathtub, with his ankle chained to a pipe. Across the room is [[Oncology|oncologist]] Dr Lawrence Gordon with a corpse between them holding a [[revolver]] and a [[microcassette]] recorder. Both men find a tape in their pockets, and Adam retrieves the recorder. Adam's tape urges him to escape, while Lawrence's tape tells him to kill Adam by six o'clock or his wife and daughter will be killed and he will be left to die. Adam finds a bag containing two [[hacksaw]]s inside the toilet, which they try to use to cut through their chains, but Adam's saw breaks. Lawrence realizes the saws are meant to be used on their feet, and identifies their captor as the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]], whom Lawrence knows of because he was once a suspect.\n\nFlashbacks reveal that Lawrence, while discussing the terminal brain cancer of a patient named John Kramer, was approached by Detectives [[David Tapp]] and [[List of Saw characters#Steven Sing|Steven Sing]], who found his penlight at the scene of one of Jigsaw's \"games\". Lawrence's alibi cleared him, but he agreed to view the testimony of [[heroin]] addict [[Amanda Young]], the only known survivor of one of Jigsaw's traps who believes the killer helped her.\n\nIn the present, Lawrence's wife Alison and daughter Diana are held captive at home as their captor watches Adam and Lawrence through a hidden camera. The house is simultaneously watched by Tapp, having been discharged from the police and becoming obsessed with the Jigsaw case, eventually finding Jigsaw's warehouse using the videotape from Amanda's game. There, he and Sing apprehended Jigsaw and saved a man from a drill trap. However, Jigsaw escaped after slashing Tapp's throat and Sing was killed by a shotgun trap. Convinced that Lawrence is Jigsaw, Tapp has continued to stalk him.\n\nIn the bathroom, Lawrence finds a box containing two cigarettes, a lighter, and a one-way cellphone, and recalls his abduction in a parking garage by a pig-masked figure. He and Adam stage Adam's death with a cigarette dipped in the corpse's poisoned blood, but the plan fails when Adam is electrically shocked through his ankle chain. Adam recalls his own abduction: in his photo development room when the power went out, he found [[Billy the Puppet|a puppet]] and was attacked by the same pig-masked figure. Alison calls Lawrence at gunpoint and tells him not to trust Adam, who admits that he was paid to take photos of Lawrence, many of which were in the bag containing the hacksaws. Adam reveals his knowledge of Lawrence's affair with one of his medical students, whom he had visited the night he was abducted; revealing why Lawrence is being \"tested\". After Adam describes the man who hired him, Lawrence realizes it was Tapp. Adam finds a photo he did not take, of a man staring out a window of Lawrence's house, whom Lawrence identifies as Zep, an orderly at his hospital. As the clock strikes six, Zep moves to kill Alison and Diana.\n\nAlison frees herself and fights Zep for his gun, after he calls Lawrence. The struggle attracts Tapp's attention, and he saves Alison and Diana and chases Zep to the sewers, where he is shot in the chest after a brief struggle. Lawrence, only aware of gunshots and screaming, is shocked and loses reach of the cellphone. In desperation, he saws off his foot and shoots Adam with the corpse's revolver. Zep enters the bathroom to kill Lawrence according to \"the rules\", but Adam, having survived, bludgeons Zep to death with the toilet tank lid. As Lawrence crawls out of the room, Adam searches Zep's body for a key and finds another tape, which reveals that Zep was another victim following rules to obtain an antidote for a slow-acting poison he was given. As the tape ends, the corpse rises and is revealed to be John Kramer, the real Jigsaw Killer. He reveals that the key to Adam's chain went down the bathtub drain when Adam first woke up. Horrified, Adam attempts to shoot John with Zep's gun, but John shocks him with a remote. John shuts off the lights, and yells \"Game Over\" before sealing the door and leaving a helpless Adam to die.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n[[File:Shawnee Smith gfdl.png|thumb|upright|It took one day for [[Shawnee Smith]]'s scenes to be shot, which Wan described as \"physically taxing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview130.htm |title=The Arrow Interviews James Wan |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323061516/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview130.htm |archivedate=March 23, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n{{div col}}\n* [[Cary Elwes]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lawrence Gordon|Dr. Lawrence \"Larry\" Gordon]]\n* [[Leigh Whannell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Stanheight|Adam Stanheight]]\n* [[Danny Glover]] as [[David Tapp]]\n* [[Monica Potter]] as [[List of Saw characters#Alison and Diana Gordon|Alison Gordon]]\n* [[Michael Emerson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Zep Hindle|Zep Hindle]]\n* [[Ken Leung]] as [[List of Saw characters#Steven Sing|Detective Steven Sing]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* Mike Butters as [[List of Saw characters#Paul Leahy|Paul]]\n* [[Paul Gutrecht]] as [[List of Saw characters#Mark Wilson|Mark]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Makenzie Vega]] as [[List of Saw characters#Alison and Diana Gordon|Diana Gordon]]\n* [[Ned Bellamy]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Ridenhour|Jeff Ridenhour]]\n* [[Alexandra Bokyun Chun]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carla Song|Carla]]\n* [[Oren Koules]] as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n* [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]] as Brett\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[File:James Wan and Leigh Whannell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|left|Wan (left) and Whannell (right).]]\nAfter finishing film school, Australian director [[James Wan]] and Australian writer [[Leigh Whannell]] wanted to write and fund a film.<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/ |title=Saw creators Leigh Whannell and James Wan |last=Tobias |first=Scott |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]] |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912091303/http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/ |archivedate=September 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The inspiration that they needed came after watching the low-budget independent film ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]''.  Another film that inspired them to finance the film themselves was [[Darren Aronofsky]]'s ''[[Pi (film)|Pi]]''.<ref name=\"FangoriaPg50\">{{cite journal|last=Walker|first=Sarah|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw Cuts Deep|issn=0164-2111|number=236|date=September 2004|pages=50}}</ref> The two thought the cheapest script to shoot would involve two actors in one room.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> Whannell said, \"So I actually think the restrictions we had on our bank accounts at the time, the fact that we wanted to keep the film contained, helped us come up with the ideas in the film.\"<ref name=\"IGNpg1\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p1.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |page=1 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107181331/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p1.html |archivedate=November 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> One idea was to have the entire film set with two actors stuck in an elevator and being shot in the point of view of security cameras.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" />\n\nWan pitched the idea to Whannell of two men chained to opposite sides of a bathroom with a dead body in the middle of the floor and they are trying to figure out why and how they are there. By the end of the film they realize the person lying on the floor is not dead and he is the reason they are locked in the room. Whannell initially did not give Wan the reaction he was looking for. He said, \"I'll never forget that day. I remember hanging up the phone and started just going over it in my head, and without any sort of long period of pondering, I opened my diary that I had at the time and wrote the word 'Saw'.\"<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> Before instantaneously writing the word \"Saw\" in a blood-red, dripping font, the two had not come up with a title. \"It was one of those moments that made me aware that some things just really are meant to be. Some things are just waiting there to be discovered\", Whannell said.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" />\n\nThe character of [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] did not come until months later, when Whannell was working at a job he was unhappy with and began having migraines. Convinced it was a [[brain tumor]],<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\" /> he went to a [[neurology|neurologist]] to have an [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] and while sitting nervously in the waiting room he thought, \"What if you were given the news that you had a tumor and you were going to die soon? How would you react to that?\"<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> He imagined the character Jigsaw having been given one or two years to live and combined that with the idea of Jigsaw putting others in a literal version of the situation, but only giving them a few minutes to choose their fate.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\nWan did not intend to make a \"[[Splatter film|torture porn]]\" film as the script only had one short segment of torture. He said the film \"played out like a mystery thriller\". It was not until the [[Saw (franchise)|sequel]]s that the plot focused more on torture scenes.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\n===Funding===\nWhannell and Wan initially had $30,000 to spend on the film, but as the script developed it was clear that more funds would be needed.<ref name=\"FangoriaPg50\" /> The script was optioned by a producer in [[Sydney]] for a year but the deal eventually fell through.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> After other failed attempts to get the script produced in Australia from 2001 to 2002,<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> literary agent Ken Greenblat read the script and suggested they travel to [[Los Angeles]], where their chances of finding an interested studio were greater.<ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/23/1100972389306.html |title=They came, Saw, conquered |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |date=November 24, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105200654/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/23/1100972389306.html |archivedate=November 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wan and Whannell initially refused, due to lack of traveling funds but the pair's agent, Stacey Testro, convinced them to go.<ref name=\"SMH\" />  In order to help studios take interest in the script, Whannell provided A$5,000 (US$5,000) to make a seven-minute short film based on the script's jaw trap scene, which they thought would prove most effective. Whannell played David, the man wearing the Reverse Bear Trap. Working at the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], Whannell and Wan knew cameramen who were willing to provide technical assistance for the short.<ref name=\"IGNpg2\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p2.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=2 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126003505/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p2.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Quote box|quote=I guess the term 'torture-porn' doesn't affect me one way or the other. I don't love the term, nor do I really hate it. For me, it's kind of hard to have any bad feelings about the term, because I guess torture-porn has given me a lot of good things, like being able to work in the film industry and work as a screenwriter. I guess I'm just thankful to be part of a film that made it, and anything after that is just a champagne problem.|source=\u2014Leigh Whannell (screenwriter) on his feelings of the film being labeled \"torture porn\".<ref name=\"AVClub\"/>|align=right|width=27%|style=padding:10px;}}\nWan shot the short with a [[16 mm film|16mm]] camera<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview131.htm |title=The Arrow Interviews Leigh Whannell |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101065652/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview131.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> in over two days and transferred the footage to DVDs to ship along with the script. Whannell wanted to play the lead character in the feature film. The short helped show that Wan and Whannell were a \"director-actor team\" rather than just wanting to sell the script. Wan said, \"Leigh and I just loved the project so much and we wanted a career in filmmaking so we stuck to our guns and said, 'Look, guys, if you want this project, we're coming on board \u2014 Leigh has to act in it and I have to direct it.\"<ref name=\"SMH\" />\n\nIn early 2003,<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/21/us-saw-idUSTRE49K00J20081021 |title=\"Saw\" horror franchise faces test with 5th movie |last=A. Fernandez |first=Jay |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=October 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023142633/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/21/us-saw-idUSTRE49K00J20081021 |archivedate=October 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  while in Los Angeles and before they met with producer [[Gregg Hoffman]], Hoffman's friend pulled him into his office and showed him the short. Hoffman said, \"About two or three minutes into it, my jaw hit the floor.\"<ref name=\"SawProdNotes\">{{cite web |url=http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw/docs/pro_notes.doc |title=Saw Production Notes |publisher=[[Lionsgate]] |year=2004 |format=1.18MB [[Doc (computing)|.DOC]] file download |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930182202/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw/docs/pro_notes.doc |archivedate=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He quickly showed the short and script to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] of [[Evolution Entertainment]].<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> They later formed [[Twisted Pictures]] as a horror genre production label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117918836 |title=Twisted, LG find way into 'Catacombs' |last=Harris |first=Dana |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=March 2, 2005 |accessdate=September 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120918202856/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117918836 |archivedate=September 18, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The producers read the screenplay that night and two days later offered Wan and Whannell [[Artistic control|creative control]] and 25% of the net profits.<ref name=\"Virginian\">{{cite news|title=As the ' Saw ' turns |last=Lidz|first=Franz|work=[[The Virginian-Pilot]]|publisher=[[Landmark Media Enterprises]]|location=[[Norfolk, Virginia]]|date=October 25, 2009}}</ref> Even though Wan and Whannell received \"better offers\" from studios like [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] and [[Gold Circle Films]], they were not willing to chance Wan's directing and Whannell acting in the lead role.<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> In order to finance the film, Hoffman, Burg, and Koules put up a second mortgage on their [[Highland Avenue (Los Angeles)|Highland Avenue]] headquarters.<ref name=\"Variety2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117898181 |title='Saw' comes, conquers |last=Fleming |first=Mike |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=January 11, 2004 |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130205092742/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117898181 |archivedate=February 5, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw'' was given a [[production budget]] of between $1 million and $1.2 million.{{#tag:ref|Sources for the budget figure vary. Some put the budget at $1 million,<ref name=\"TorontoStar\"/> $1.15 million<ref name=\"NYTimes2009\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html |title=Limbs Pile Up, and Money, Too |last=Lidz |first=Franz |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040501/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html |archivedate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and $1.2 million.<ref name=\"SMH\"/>  |group=note}}\n\n===Casting===\nCary Elwes was sent the short film on DVD and immediately became interested in the film. He read the script in one sitting and was drawn in by the \"uniqueness and originality\" of the story.<ref name=\"ElwesIGN\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p1.html|title=IGN Interviews Cary Elwes|last=Otto|first=Jeff|work=IGN|publisher=News Corporation|page=1|date=October 26, 2004|accessdate=August 18, 2011}}</ref> To prepare for his role as an [[Oncology|oncologist]], he met with a doctor at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]'s Department of [[Neurosurgery]].<ref name=\"ElwesIGN2\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p2.html |title=IGN Interviews Cary Elwes |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=2 |date=October 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126051813/http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p2.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nShawnee Smith, who is not a horror fan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |title=Shawnee Smith: \"I Can't Watch Horror Movies\" |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |work=[[New York Post]] |date=July 13, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128193200/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> initially refused the role, describing the script as \"horrific\". However, after watching the short, she agreed to the role, which was the part that Whannell portrayed in the short.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/interviews/glover-danny-smith-shawnee-saw |title=Glover, Danny & Smith, Shawnee (Saw) |last=Condit |first=Jon |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |date=December 2, 2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021152701/http://www.dreadcentral.com/interviews/glover-danny-smith-shawnee-saw |archivedate=October 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn taking the role of Jigsaw, Tobin Bell said, \"I did ''Saw'' because I thought it was a fascinating location for a film to be made. These guys locked in a room, to me, was fresh. I did not anticipate the ending when I read the script, so I was quite caught by surprise and it was clear to me that if the filmmakers shot the scene well, the audience would be caught by surprise as well. The film was worth doing for that moment alone.\"<ref name=\"SawRevisted\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/22185 |title=Special Feature: 'Saw Revisited: Jigsaw's Long Journey' |last=Albin |first=Andrea |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=October 26, 2010 |accessdate=September 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029202452/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/22185 |archivedate=October 29, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Filming and post-production===\nWith a shooting budget of $700,000,<ref name=\"AVClub\" /><ref name=\"Collider2011\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/james-wan-leigh-whannell-interview-insidious/83806/ |title=James Wan & Leigh Whannell Insidious Interview; The Saw Creators Also Discuss Their Untitled Sci-Fi Project, Nihtfall, and Recent Horror Remakes |last=Messer |first=Ron |publisher=Collider.com |date=April 4, 2011 |accessdate=April 4, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806131151/http://collider.com/james-wan-leigh-whannell-interview-insidious/83806/ |archivedate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw'' began [[principal photography]] on {{nowrap|September 22, 2003}}<ref name=\"Variety2004\" /> at Lacy Street Production Facility in Los Angeles<ref name=\"SawProdNotes\" /> for 18 days.<ref name=\"Collider2011\" /> The bathroom was the only set that had to be built.<ref name=\"TheArrowMG_GH_OK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview137.htm |title=The Arrow interviews Gregg Hoffman, Oren Koules & Mark Burg |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=JoBlo.com |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101054056/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview137.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Danny Glover]] completed his scenes in two days.<ref name=\"IGNpg3\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p3.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=3 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126090136/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p3.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the tight [[shooting schedule]], Wan could not afford to shoot more than a couple of [[take]]s per actor.<ref name=\"BDInterview1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/42 |title=Saw: Director James Wan & Writer/Star Leigh Whannell |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222220149/http://bloody-disgusting.com/interview/42 |archivedate=December 22, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"It was a really tough struggle for me. Every day, it was me fighting to get the shots I did not get. I had high aspirations, but there's only so much you can do. I wanted to make it in a very [[Hitchcockian]] style of filmmaking, but that style of filmmaking takes time to set up and so on\", Wan said about the very short shooting schedule.<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> He said the style instead ended up being \"more gritty and rough around the edges due to the lack of time and money that we had to shoot the movie with\" and it ultimately became the aesthetic of the film.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\nIn post-production, Wan found he did not have enough shots or takes to work with as he was basically shooting rehearsals. Having a lot of missing gaps in the final product, he and editor [[Kevin Greutert]] created shots to mend together during editing; such as making a shot look like a surveillance camera feed and using still photographs. \"We did a lot of things to fill in gaps throughout the film. Whatever we cut to newspaper clippings and stuff like that, or we cut to surveillance cameras, or we cut to [[Unit still photographer|still photography]] within the film, which now people say, 'Wow, that's such a cool experimental style of filmmaking', we really did that out of necessity to fill in gaps we did not get during the filming\", he explained.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|Hello Zepp}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 5, 2004\n| recorded   = 2004\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[electro-industrial]]\n| length     = 57:29\n| label      = [[Entertainment One Music|Koch]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Saw II#Soundtrack|Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n}}\nThe soundtrack was mainly composed by [[Charlie Clouser]], which took six weeks to complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.ign.com/articles/562/562509p3.html |title=Charlie Clouser Interview |author=Spence D. |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |page=3 |date=November 1, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319115742/http://music.ign.com/articles/562/562509p3.html |archivedate=March 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other songs were performed by [[Front Line Assembly]], [[Fear Factory]], [[Enemy (American band)|Enemy]], Pitbull Daycare and Psycho Pumps. [[Megadeth]]'s song \"Die Dead Enough\" was originally set to be featured in the film, but was not used for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25140 |title=MEGADETH: 'Die Dead Enough' Single To Be Featured In Upcoming Horror Film |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=July 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312232449/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25140 |archivedate=March 12, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25203 |title=Producer: MEGADETH's 'Die Dead Enough' Not Featured In 'Saw' Movie |publisher=Blabbermouth.net |date=July 28, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921223302/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25203 |archivedate=September 21, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack was released on {{nowrap|October 5, 2004}} by [[Entertainment One Music|Koch Records]]. Johnny Loftus of [[AllMusic]] gave it three out of five stars. He said that Clouser \"really nails it with his creaky, clammy score\" and that he \"understands that ''Saw''{{'s}} horror only works with a heady amount of camp, and he draws from industrial music in the same way\". He particularly liked, \"Cigarette\"; \"Hello, Adam\"; and \"F**k This S*!t\", commenting that they \"blend chilling sounds with harsh percussion and deep-wound keyboard stabs\".<ref name=\"AllMusicReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r710182|title=Saw (Original) Motion Picture Soundtrack|last= Loftus|first=Johnny|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline         = ''Saw Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n| extra_column = Artist\n| total_length = 57:29\n| title1 = Sturm\n| writer1         = [[Rhys Fulber]]<br />[[Bill Leeb]]\n| extra1 = [[Front Line Assembly]]\n| length1 = 6:07\n| title2 = Hello, Adam\n| writer2         = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| extra2 = Clouser\n| length2 = 3:57\n| title3 = Bite the Hand That Bleeds\n| writer3         =  [[Burton C. Bell]]<br />Fear Factory<br />[[Raymond Herrera]]<br />Olde Wolbers\n| extra3 = [[Fear Factory]]\n| length3 = 4:01\n| title4 = Last I Heard ... \n| writer4         = Clouser\n| extra4 = Clouser\n| length4 = 4:40\n| title5 = Action\n| writer5         = [[Jason Slater]]<br />[[Troy Van Leeuwen]]\n| extra5 = [[Enemy (American band)|Enemy]]\n| length5 = 3:43\n| title6 =  Reverse Beartrap\n| writer6         = Clouser\n| extra6 = Clouser\n| length6 = 4:47\n| title7 = You Make Me Feel So Dead\n| writer7         = Stephen Ladd Bishop<br />Charles Todd Conally<br />Don Van Stavern\n| extra7 = Pitbull Daycare\n| length7 =  3:49\n| title8 =  X Marks the Spot\n| writer8         = Clouser\n| extra8 = Clouser\n| length8 = 4:34\n| title9 = Wonderful World\n| writer9         = Flemming Norre Larsen<br />Jesper Schmidt\n| extra9 = Psycho Pumps\n| length9 = 5:00\n| title10 =  Cigarette\n| writer10         = Clouser\n| extra10 = Clouser\n| length10 = 3:07\n| title11 = We're Out of Time\n| writer11         = Clouser\n| extra11 = Clouser\n| length11 =  3:48\n| title12 = F**k This S*!t\n| writer12         = Clouser\n| extra12 = Clouser\n| length12 = 4:09\n| title13 = [[Hello Zepp]]\n| writer13         = Clouser\n| extra13 =  Clouser\n| length13 = 3:00\n| title14 =  Zepp Overture\n| writer14         = Clouser\n| extra14 = Clouser\n| length14 = 2:38\n}}\n\n==Release==\n[[Lions Gate Films]] picked up ''Saw''{{'s}} worldwide distribution rights at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] days before the film premiered on {{nowrap|January 19, 2004}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/lions_gate_gets_world_rights_to_sundance_midnight_film_saw/ |title=Lions Gate Gets World Rights To Sundance Midnight Film \"Saw\" |work=[[indieWire]] |date=January 13, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309222928/http://www.indiewire.com/article/lions_gate_gets_world_rights_to_sundance_midnight_film_saw |archivedate=March 9, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> There it played to a packed theater for three nights to a very positive reaction.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> It was the closing film at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on {{nowrap|September 18, 2004}}.<ref name=\"TorontoStar\">{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> Lions Gate initially planned to release the film [[direct-to-video]], but due to the positive reaction at Sundance, they chose to release it theatrically by Halloween.<ref name=\"Virginian\" /> It was released on {{nowrap|October 1, 2004}} in the United Kingdom, {{nowrap|October 29, 2004}} in the United States and {{nowrap|December 2, 2004}} in Australia. The film was originally rated [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|NC-17]] (No children under 17 permitted) by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for strong graphic violence, though after being re-edited, it was released with an [[Motion picture content rating system|R rating]].<ref name=\"TheArrowMG_GH_OK\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/28/news/wk-movies28\\ |title=An outsider mentality |last=Abele |first=Robert |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 28, 2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016080337/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/28/news/wk-movies28 |archivedate=October 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lions Gate held the inaugural \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] and collected 4,249 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive |publisher=[[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] |date=August 6, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106140610/http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |archivedate=November 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109034821/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Tenth anniversary re-release===\nOn October 31, 2014, in honor of the film's 10th anniversary, ''Saw'' was re-released to select theatres for one week.\n\nThe release earned only $650,051 in its opening weekend, and is the third lowest-grossing wide opening.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/worstopenings.htm?page=WRSTOPN20&p=.htm | title=Worst Openings at the Box Office for 2,000+ | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref> At the end of its run, the release had grossed $815,324, bringing the film's overall domestic gross to $56,000,369.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw10th.htm | title=Saw 10th Anniversary (2014) | work=Box Office Mojo | publisher=Internet Movie Database | date=November 6, 2014 | accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe theatrical version of the film was released on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] on {{nowrap|February 15, 2005}} in the United States. After its first week, it made {{nowrap|$9.4 million}} in DVD rentals and {{nowrap|$1.7 million}} in VHS rentals, making it the top rental of the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1117 |title=Seeing Saw |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=February 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613174753/http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1117 |archivedate=June 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> For the second week it remained as the number one DVD rental with {{nowrap|$6.8 million}}, for a {{nowrap|$16.27 million}} two-week total. It dropped to third place in VHS rentals with {{nowrap|$1.09 million}}, for a {{nowrap|$2.83 million}} two-week total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1137|title=Saw Remains on Top of Belated Rental Charts|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=March 5, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>  The film went on to sell more than $70 million worth of video and DVDs.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> A two-disc \"Uncut Edition\" was released on {{nowrap|October 18, 2005}} to tie in with the release of ''[[Saw II]]''. The short film, also entitled ''Saw'', was included on the DVD.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtown.com/moviedatabase/release-details/saw/dvd/16836 |title=Details and specifications for Saw (Special Edition, Uncut) on DVD |publisher=DVD Town |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807094922/http://www.dvdtown.com/moviedatabase/release-details/saw/dvd/16836 |archivedate=August 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film was subsequently included in a boxed set with all six sequels entitled ''Saw: The Complete Movie Collection'', which was released in September 2014 for the film's tenth anniversary.  The set contained the unrated editions of all seven films, though it lacked any of the special features from previous releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Saw-Complete-Movie-Collection-Blu-ray/dp/B00MFCPVO6/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1436562992&sr=8-1&keywords=saw+the+complete+movie+collection|title=Saw 1 - 7 Movie Collection|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=February 3, 2018|website=Amazon.com}}</ref>\n\n====''Full Disclosure Report''====\n''Full Disclosure Report'' is a 2005 [[mockumentary]], pseudo-documentary set in the ''[[Saw (franchise)|Saw]]'' franchise, taking place between the events of ''Saw'' and ''[[Saw II]]'', around one year after the beginning of the Jigsaw murders, following television host Rich Skidmore as he commentates on the murders and the police work in the yet-unresolved case. [[Donnie Wahlberg]] appears as Detective Eric Matthews, prior to his appearance in ''Saw II''.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw'' opened at #3 on [[Halloween]] weekend 2004 in 2,315 theaters and grossed {{nowrap|$18.2 million}}, behind ''[[Ray (film)|Ray]]'' ($20 million) and ''[[The Grudge]]'' ($21.8 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2004&wknd=44&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 29\u201331, 2004|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=November 1, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> According to Lionsgate's exit poll, 60% of the mostly male audience was under 25 years of age. ''Saw'' had also become Lions Gate's second best opening, after ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''{{'s}} {{nowrap|$23.9 million}} (2004).<ref name=\"BOMOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1540&p=.htm|title='Ray,' 'Saw' See Robust Bows|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 1, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend, an additional 152 theaters were added, bringing the theater count to 2,467. It dropped to number four, making $11 million, a 39% drop from the opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2004&wknd=45&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 5\u20137, 2004|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 8, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Saw'' opened in the United Kingdom to {{nowrap|$2.2 million}} in 301 theaters, grossing a {{nowrap|$12.3 million}} total in seven weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=UK&id=saw.htm|title=United Kingdom and Ireland and Malta Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 14, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Australia, it opened in 161 theaters with {{nowrap|$1.2 million}} and totaled out to {{nowrap|$3.1 million}} in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=AU&id=saw.htm|title=Australia Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=March 10, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Italy, the film opened on {{nowrap|January 14, 2005}} in 267 theaters to {{nowrap|$1.7 million}} and grossed {{nowrap|$6.4 million}} in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=IT&id=saw.htm|title=Italy Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=February 20, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Saw'' opened to {{nowrap|$1.5 million}} 187 theaters in France on {{nowrap|March 16, 2005}} and made {{nowrap|$3.1 million}} by the end of its four-week run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=FR&id=saw.htm|title=France and Algeria, Monaco, Morocco and Tunisia Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=April 12, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Saw'' came to gross {{nowrap|$55.1 million}} in the United States and Canada and {{nowrap|$47.9 million}} in other markets for a worldwide total of {{nowrap|$103 million}}.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> It is the second lowest-grossing film in the series after ''[[Saw VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' vs 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> At the time, it became the most profitable horror film after ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/61775/ |title=Splattered: An Interview with James Wan Talking torture, politics and not-so-sweet revenge |last=Foundas |first=Scott |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=August 30, 2011 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309195342/http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/61775/ |archivedate=March 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)\n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)\n! colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" | '''Box office gross'''<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''North America'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other territories'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 29, 2004\n|align=\"center\" |$1,200,000\n|$55,185,045\n|$47,911,300\n|$103,096,345\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nCritical reception to ''Saw'' was mixed. On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 49% based on 184 reviews, with an average rating of 5.53/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''Saw'' ensnares audiences with a deceptively clever plot and a myriad of memorable, nasty set pieces, but its lofty ambitions are undercut by a nihilistic streak that feels more mean than profound.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/| title=''Saw'' (2004)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = June 29, 2019}}</ref> Metacritic gave the film a score of 46 out of 100, based on 32 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw| title= Saw Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = October 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDennis Harvey of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a negative review after its Sundance premiere. He called it a \"crude concoction sewn together from the severed parts of prior horror/serial killer pics\".  He called the screenplay \"convoluted\", criticizing the use of \"flashbacks within flashbacks\" and [[red herring]]s. He described the film as being \"too hyperbolic to be genuinely disturbing\".<ref name=\"VarietyReview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117922951.html |title=Sundance Review |last=Harvey |first=Dennis |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=January 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008033538/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117922951/ |archivedate=October 8, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carla Meyer of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film a positive review saying the film \"combined B-movie acting with a twisted mind-set and visual tricks designed to camouflage cheap effects\" and that it was \"terrifying at some moments and insinuatingly creepy at many others\". She called the killing scenes \"amazingly evocative for such a low-budget movie\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/10/29/DDGRB9HIGS1.DTL |title=Cheap Thrills Sharpen Grisly 'Saw' |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=October 29, 2004 |first=Carla |last=Meyer |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629045222/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/10/29/DDGRB9HIGS1.DTL&type=movies |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'s}} [[Kim Newman]] gave the film four out of five stars. He said ''Saw'' is styled like early [[David Fincher]] films and \"boasts an intricate structure \u2014 complex flashbacks-within-flashbacks explain how the characters have come to this crisis \u2014 and a satisfying mystery to go with its ghastly claustrophobia.\" He ended his review saying, \"As good an all-out, non-camp horror movie as we've had lately.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10234 |title=Saw |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=April 1, 2006 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113224054/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10234 |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B minus, calling it \"derivative and messy and too nonsensical for its own good\".  He described Jigsaw's intent as \"to show you the serial killer lurking inside yourself\". Gleiberman criticized Elwes' performance by saying, \"[Elwes] ought to be featured in a seminar on the perils of [[overacting]].\"<ref name=\"EWReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,734839,00.html |title=Saw Review |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |authorlink=Owen Gleiberman |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105124526/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,734839,00.html |archivedate=January 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Daniel M. Kimmel]] of the ''[[Telegram & Gazette]]'' called it \"one of the most loathsome films this critic has seen in more than 20 years on the job\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Many will wish they'd never seen 'Saw'|last=M. Kimmel|first=Daniel|authorlink=Daniel M. Kimmel|work=[[Telegram & Gazette]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=October 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]''{{'s}} [[Stephen Holden]] gave a mixed review saying the film \"does a better-than-average job of conveying the panic and helplessness of men terrorized by a sadist in a degrading environment, but it is still not especially scary. What sets its demon apart from run-of-the-mill movie serial killers is his impulse to humiliate and torture his victims and justify it with some twisted morality.\" He said the film is \"seriously undermined by the half-baked, formulaic detective story in which the horror is framed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2004/10/29/movies/29saw.html |title=A Gore Fest, With Overtones of Iraq and TV |last=Holden |first=Stephen |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=October 29, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710144903/http://movies.nytimes.com/2004/10/29/movies/29saw.html |archivedate=July 10, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carina Chocano of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' also gave the film a mixed review saying, \"''Saw'' is so full of twists it ends up getting snarled. For all of his flashy engineering and inventive torture scenarios, the Jigsaw Killer comes across as an amateur. [[Hannibal Lecter]] would have him for lunch.\" She said the film \"carelessly underscores its own shaky narrative at every turn with its mid-budget hokiness\". She also noted that Elwes and Whannell had trouble keeping an American accent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/29/entertainment/et-saw29 |title='Saw' would work better if sharpened |last=Chocano |first=Carina |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 29, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016080331/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/29/entertainment/et-saw29 |archivedate=October 16, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another mixed review came from [[Roger Ebert]], who gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and lamented the gimmicks and plot contrivances but nonetheless described ''Saw'' as \"well made and acted, and does what it does about as well as it could be expected to\".<ref>[[Roger Ebert]] (2004) \"[http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/saw-2004 Saw]\", accessed 10 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Comparisons to ''Seven'' (1995)===\nWhen asked if the 1995 thriller film ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]'' was an inspiration to ''Saw'', Whannell said \"For me as the writer, definitely. I mean, ''Seven'' is just a very well constructed film, and if you're writing a thriller, it can't hurt to study it. In terms of the story though, James and I never really felt ''Seven'' was that close to our film. I guess if you stand back, you have two detectives chasing a psychopath, who uses vile methods to teach people lessons, and those points echo ''Seven''. What we always liked about ''Saw'', though, was the fact that the story is told from the point of view of two of the psychopath's victims, instead of the police chasing after him, as you so often see.\"<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\" /> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Owen Gleiberman compared the plot to ''Seven'' saying, \"In a blatant imitation of ''Seven'', ''Saw'' features a lunatic sadist whose ghoulish crimes are meant, in each case, to mirror the sins of his victims. The twist here is that the psycho doesn't do the killing.\"<ref name=\"EWReview\" /> Richard J. Leskosky of [[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area|Champaign-Urbana]]'s ''The News-Gazette'' said \"''Saw'' wants to be taken as another ''Seven''. Though it features perverse gross-out scenes and a villain with a superficially pedantic motive behind his crimes (his victims, if they survive, have learned to appreciate life more), it lacks the finesse and polish of the David Fincher film.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Improbable ' Saw ' surprises, but still not worth a see |last=J. Leskosky|first=Richard|work=The News-Gazette|location=[[Champaign-Urbana Metropolitan Area|Champaign-Urbana]], [[Illinois|IL]]|date=November 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n[[Bloody Disgusting]] ranked the film tenth in its list of the Top 20 Horror Films of the Decade, with the article calling ''Saw'' \"perhaps the most influential horror film of the decade, which kick-started a franchise. ... In light of its measly $1.2 million price tag the film's quality relative to bigger-budget horror films is striking. It also takes itself seriously, which came as a breath of fresh air following the trend of wimpy tongue-in-cheek horror that had dominated the multiplexes post-''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]''. More than anything, this twisted morality tale is a film made by horror fans, for horror fans; it's gory, it's depraved, and best of all it introduced a new horror icon in Jigsaw.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18425 |title=00's Retrospect: Bloody Disgusting's Top 20 Films of the Decade ... Part 3 |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=December 17, 2009 |accessdate=January 3, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810151317/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18425 |archivedate=August 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' listed the film number 14 on their Top 100 list that defined the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6501160/Top-100-movies-defining-the-noughties-00s-in-film.html |title=The films that defined the noughties |last=Gritten |first=David |last2=Robey |first2=Tim |last3=Sandhu |first3=Sukhdev |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825145737/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6501160/Top-100-movies-defining-the-noughties-00s-in-film.html |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Brussels International Fantastic Film Festival]]\n| Pegasus Audience Award\n|rowspan=2| [[James Wan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Fantasporto]]\n| International Fantasy Film Award- Best Film\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Trailer Awards]]\n| Best Horror\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Festival international du film fantastique de G\u00e9rardmer]]\n| Special Jury Prize\n|rowspan=2| James Wan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Youth Jury Grand Prize\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Frightened Performance\n| [[Cary Elwes]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]]\n| Audience Award- Best Feature\n| James Wan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| Outstanding DVD Extras (Uncut Edition)\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Release|Best DVD Special Edition Release]]\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]]\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Scream Scene\n| [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Thriller\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=note/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0387564|Saw}}\n* {{metacritic film|saw|Saw}}\n* {{mojo title|saw|Saw}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|saw|Saw}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{James Wan}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw (Film)}}\n[[Category:Saw films|1]]\n[[Category:2004 films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2004 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:Features based on short films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by James Wan]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by James Wan]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:2004 directorial debut films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the franchise|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film \n| name           = Saw\n| image          = Saw official poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Wan]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Gregg Hoffman]]|[[Oren Koules]]|[[Mark Burg]]}}\n| writer         = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| story          = {{ubl|James Wan|Leigh Whannell}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|[[Saw (2003 film)|''Saw'']]|James Wan|Leigh Whannell}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|Leigh Whannell|[[Cary Elwes]]|[[Danny Glover]]|[[Monica Potter]]|[[Michael Emerson]]|[[Ken Leung]]|[[Tobin Bell]]}}\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing        = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lions Gate Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2004|01|19|[[Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]|2004|10|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 103 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $1.2 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=Saw (2004)|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw.htm|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n| gross          = $103.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n\n'''''Saw''''' is a 2004 American [[horror film]]<ref name=\"VarietyReview\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=12&ti=1,12&Search_Arg=Saw&Search_Code=TALL&CNT=25&PID=x8Cuc4HrUx9R--hShAp_UDaA4t&SEQ=20110817025227&SID=1 |title=Saw. Motion Picture |publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]] |date=May 17, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6102VFlCf?url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?v1=12&ti=1,12&Search_Arg=Saw&Search_Code=TALL&CNT=25&PID=x8Cuc4HrUx9R--hShAp_UDaA4t&SEQ=20110817025227&SID=1 |archivedate=August 17, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> directed by [[James Wan]] (in his feature directorial debut) and written by [[Leigh Whannell]] from a story by Wan and Whannell. It stars Whannell, [[Cary Elwes]], [[Danny Glover]], [[Monica Potter]], [[Michael Emerson]], [[Ken Leung]], and [[Tobin Bell]]. It is the first installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. In it, Whannell and Elwes portray two men who awake to find themselves chained in a large dilapidated bathroom, with one being ordered to kill the other or his family will die. The screenplay was written by Whannell, who co-created the story with Wan in their screenwriting debuts respectively.\n\nThe screenplay was written in 2001, but after failed attempts to get the script produced in Wan and Whannell's home country of Australia, they were urged to travel to Los Angeles. In order to help attract producers they shot a [[Low-budget film|low-budget]] short film [[Saw (2003 film)|of the same name]] from a scene out of the script. This proved successful in 2003 as producers from [[Evolution Entertainment]] were immediately attached and also formed a horror genre production label, [[Twisted Pictures]]. The film was given a small budget of $1.2 million and shot for 18 days.\n\n''Saw'' was first screened on January 19, 2004, before released in North America on October 29, 2004, by [[Lions Gate Films]]. Compared to its low budget, ''Saw'' performed very well at the box office, grossing more than $100 million worldwide and becoming, at the time, one of the most profitable horror films since ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996). The film was theatrically re-released, to select theatres, on October 31, 2014 to celebrate its tenth anniversary.<ref name=\"IGNAug2014\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/27/saw-returning-to-theaters-for-its-10th-anniversary|title=Saw returning to theatres for its 10th anniversary|last=Vejvoda|first=Jim|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=August 28, 2014|accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> A sequel, titled ''[[Saw II]]'', was released in 2005.\n\n==Plot==\nPhotographer Adam awakens in a dilapitated bathtub, with his ankle chained to a pipe. Across the room is [[Oncology|oncologist]] Dr Lawrence Gordon with a corpse between them holding a [[revolver]] and a [[microcassette]] recorder. Both men find a tape in their pockets, and Adam retrieves the recorder. Adam's tape urges him to escape, while Lawrence's tape tells him to kill Adam by six o'clock or his wife and daughter will be killed and he will be left to die. Adam finds a bag containing two [[hacksaw]]s inside the toilet, which they try to use to cut through their chains, but Adam's saw breaks. Lawrence realizes the saws are meant to be used on their feet, and identifies their captor as the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]], whom Lawrence knows of because he was once a suspect.\n\nFlashbacks reveal that Lawrence, while discussing the terminal brain cancer of a patient named John Kramer, was approached by Detectives [[David Tapp]] and [[List of Saw characters#Steven Sing|Steven Sing]], who found his penlight at the scene of one of Jigsaw's \"games\". Lawrence's alibi cleared him, but he agreed to view the testimony of [[heroin]] addict [[Amanda Young]], the only known survivor of one of Jigsaw's traps who believes the killer helped her.\n\nIn the present, Lawrence's wife Alison and daughter Diana are held captive at home as their captor watches Adam and Lawrence through a hidden camera. The house is simultaneously watched by Tapp, having been discharged from the police and becoming obsessed with the Jigsaw case, eventually finding Jigsaw's warehouse using the videotape from Amanda's game. There, he and Sing apprehended Jigsaw and saved a man from a drill trap. However, Jigsaw escaped after slashing Tapp's throat and Sing was killed by a shotgun trap. Convinced that Lawrence is Jigsaw, Tapp has continued to stalk him.\n\nIn the bathroom, Lawrence finds a box containing two cigarettes, a lighter, and a one-way cellphone, and recalls his abduction in a parking garage by a pig-masked figure. He and Adam stage Adam's death with a cigarette dipped in the corpse's poisoned blood, but the plan fails when Adam is electrically shocked through his ankle chain. Adam recalls his own abduction: in his photo development room when the power went out, he found [[Billy the Puppet|a puppet]] and was attacked by the same pig-masked figure. Alison calls Lawrence at gunpoint and tells him not to trust Adam, who admits that he was paid to take photos of Lawrence, many of which were in the bag containing the hacksaws. Adam reveals his knowledge of Lawrence's affair with one of his medical students, whom he had visited the night he was abducted; revealing why Lawrence is being \"tested\". After Adam describes the man who hired him, Lawrence realizes it was Tapp. Adam finds a photo he did not take, of a man staring out a window of Lawrence's house, whom Lawrence identifies as Zep, an orderly at his hospital. As the clock strikes six, Zep moves to kill Alison and Diana.\n\nAlison frees herself and fights Zep for his gun, after he calls Lawrence. The struggle attracts Tapp's attention, and he saves Alison and Diana and chases Zep to the sewers, where he is shot in the chest after a brief struggle. Lawrence, only aware of gunshots and screaming, is shocked and loses reach of the cellphone. In desperation, he saws off his foot and shoots Adam with the corpse's revolver. Zep enters the bathroom to kill Lawrence according to \"the rules\", but Adam, having survived, bludgeons Zep to death with the toilet tank lid. As Lawrence crawls out of the room, Adam searches Zep's body for a key and finds another tape, which reveals that Zep was another victim following rules to obtain an antidote for a slow-acting poison he was given. As the tape ends, the corpse rises and is revealed to be John Kramer, the real Jigsaw Killer. He reveals that the key to Adam's chain went down the bathtub drain when Adam first woke up. Horrified, Adam attempts to shoot John with Zep's gun, but John shocks him with a remote. John shuts off the lights, and yells \"Game Over\" before sealing the door and leaving a helpless Adam to die.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n[[File:Shawnee Smith gfdl.png|thumb|upright|It took one day for [[Shawnee Smith]]'s scenes to be shot, which Wan described as \"physically taxing\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview130.htm |title=The Arrow Interviews James Wan |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323061516/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview130.htm |archivedate=March 23, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]\n{{div col}}\n* [[Cary Elwes]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lawrence Gordon|Dr. Lawrence \"Larry\" Gordon]]\n* [[Leigh Whannell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Stanheight|Adam Stanheight]]\n* [[Danny Glover]] as [[David Tapp]]\n* [[Monica Potter]] as [[List of Saw characters#Alison and Diana Gordon|Alison Gordon]]\n* [[Michael Emerson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Zep Hindle|Zep Hindle]]\n* [[Ken Leung]] as [[List of Saw characters#Steven Sing|Detective Steven Sing]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* Mike Butters as [[List of Saw characters#Paul Leahy|Paul]]\n* [[Paul Gutrecht]] as [[List of Saw characters#Mark Wilson|Mark]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Makenzie Vega]] as [[List of Saw characters#Alison and Diana Gordon|Diana Gordon]]\n* [[Ned Bellamy]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Ridenhour|Jeff Ridenhour]]\n* [[Alexandra Bokyun Chun]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carla Song|Carla]]\n* [[Oren Koules]] as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n* [[Benito Martinez (actor)|Benito Martinez]] as Brett\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[File:James Wan and Leigh Whannell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|left|Wan (left) and Whannell (right).]]\nAfter finishing film school, Australian director [[James Wan]] and Australian writer [[Leigh Whannell]] wanted to write and fund a film.<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/ |title=Saw creators Leigh Whannell and James Wan |last=Tobias |first=Scott |work=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion]] |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912091303/http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/ |archivedate=September 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The inspiration that they needed came after watching the low-budget independent film ''[[The Blair Witch Project]]''.  Another film that inspired them to finance the film themselves was [[Darren Aronofsky]]'s ''[[Pi (film)|Pi]]''.<ref name=\"FangoriaPg50\">{{cite journal|last=Walker|first=Sarah|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw Cuts Deep|issn=0164-2111|number=236|date=September 2004|pages=50}}</ref> The two thought the cheapest script to shoot would involve two actors in one room.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> Whannell said, \"So I actually think the restrictions we had on our bank accounts at the time, the fact that we wanted to keep the film contained, helped us come up with the ideas in the film.\"<ref name=\"IGNpg1\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p1.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |page=1 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101107181331/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p1.html |archivedate=November 7, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> One idea was to have the entire film set with two actors stuck in an elevator and being shot in the point of view of security cameras.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" />\n\nWan pitched the idea to Whannell of two men chained to opposite sides of a bathroom with a dead body in the middle of the floor and they are trying to figure out why and how they are there. By the end of the film they realize the person lying on the floor is not dead and he is the reason they are locked in the room. Whannell initially did not give Wan the reaction he was looking for. He said, \"I'll never forget that day. I remember hanging up the phone and started just going over it in my head, and without any sort of long period of pondering, I opened my diary that I had at the time and wrote the word 'Saw'.\"<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> Before instantaneously writing the word \"Saw\" in a blood-red, dripping font, the two had not come up with a title. \"It was one of those moments that made me aware that some things just really are meant to be. Some things are just waiting there to be discovered\", Whannell said.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" />\n\nThe character of [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] did not come until months later, when Whannell was working at a job he was unhappy with and began having migraines. Convinced it was a [[brain tumor]],<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\" /> he went to a [[neurology|neurologist]] to have an [[Magnetic resonance imaging|MRI]] and while sitting nervously in the waiting room he thought, \"What if you were given the news that you had a tumor and you were going to die soon? How would you react to that?\"<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> He imagined the character Jigsaw having been given one or two years to live and combined that with the idea of Jigsaw putting others in a literal version of the situation, but only giving them a few minutes to choose their fate.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\nWan did not intend to make a \"[[Splatter film|torture porn]]\" film as the script only had one short segment of torture. He said the film \"played out like a mystery thriller\". It was not until the [[Saw (franchise)|sequel]]s that the plot focused more on torture scenes.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\n===Funding===\nWhannell and Wan initially had $30,000 to spend on the film, but as the script developed it was clear that more funds would be needed.<ref name=\"FangoriaPg50\" /> The script was optioned by a producer in [[Sydney]] for a year but the deal eventually fell through.<ref name=\"SawRevisted\" /> After other failed attempts to get the script produced in Australia from 2001 to 2002,<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> literary agent Ken Greenblat read the script and suggested they travel to [[Los Angeles]], where their chances of finding an interested studio were greater.<ref name=\"SMH\">{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/23/1100972389306.html |title=They came, Saw, conquered |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |date=November 24, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105200654/http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2004/11/23/1100972389306.html |archivedate=November 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Wan and Whannell initially refused, due to lack of traveling funds but the pair's agent, Stacey Testro, convinced them to go.<ref name=\"SMH\" />  In order to help studios take interest in the script, Whannell provided A$5,000 (US$5,000) to make a seven-minute short film based on the script's jaw trap scene, which they thought would prove most effective. Whannell played David, the man wearing the Reverse Bear Trap. Working at the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]], Whannell and Wan knew cameramen who were willing to provide technical assistance for the short.<ref name=\"IGNpg2\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p2.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=2 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126003505/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p2.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Quote box|quote=I guess the term 'torture-porn' doesn't affect me one way or the other. I don't love the term, nor do I really hate it. For me, it's kind of hard to have any bad feelings about the term, because I guess torture-porn has given me a lot of good things, like being able to work in the film industry and work as a screenwriter. I guess I'm just thankful to be part of a film that made it, and anything after that is just a champagne problem.|source=\u2014Leigh Whannell (screenwriter) on his feelings of the film being labeled \"torture porn\".<ref name=\"AVClub\"/>|align=right|width=27%|style=padding:10px;}}\nWan shot the short with a [[16 mm film|16mm]] camera<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview131.htm |title=The Arrow Interviews Leigh Whannell |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101065652/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview131.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> in over two days and transferred the footage to DVDs to ship along with the script. Whannell wanted to play the lead character in the feature film. The short helped show that Wan and Whannell were a \"director-actor team\" rather than just wanting to sell the script. Wan said, \"Leigh and I just loved the project so much and we wanted a career in filmmaking so we stuck to our guns and said, 'Look, guys, if you want this project, we're coming on board \u2014 Leigh has to act in it and I have to direct it.\"<ref name=\"SMH\" />\n\nIn early 2003,<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/21/us-saw-idUSTRE49K00J20081021 |title=\"Saw\" horror franchise faces test with 5th movie |last=A. Fernandez |first=Jay |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=October 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023142633/http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/10/21/us-saw-idUSTRE49K00J20081021 |archivedate=October 23, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  while in Los Angeles and before they met with producer [[Gregg Hoffman]], Hoffman's friend pulled him into his office and showed him the short. Hoffman said, \"About two or three minutes into it, my jaw hit the floor.\"<ref name=\"SawProdNotes\">{{cite web |url=http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw/docs/pro_notes.doc |title=Saw Production Notes |publisher=[[Lionsgate]] |year=2004 |format=1.18MB [[Doc (computing)|.DOC]] file download |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930182202/http://lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw/docs/pro_notes.doc |archivedate=September 30, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He quickly showed the short and script to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] of [[Evolution Entertainment]].<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> They later formed [[Twisted Pictures]] as a horror genre production label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117918836 |title=Twisted, LG find way into 'Catacombs' |last=Harris |first=Dana |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=March 2, 2005 |accessdate=September 28, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120918202856/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117918836 |archivedate=September 18, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> The producers read the screenplay that night and two days later offered Wan and Whannell [[Artistic control|creative control]] and 25% of the net profits.<ref name=\"Virginian\">{{cite news|title=As the ' Saw ' turns |last=Lidz|first=Franz|work=[[The Virginian-Pilot]]|publisher=[[Landmark Media Enterprises]]|location=[[Norfolk, Virginia]]|date=October 25, 2009}}</ref> Even though Wan and Whannell received \"better offers\" from studios like [[DreamWorks Pictures|DreamWorks]] and [[Gold Circle Films]], they were not willing to chance Wan's directing and Whannell acting in the lead role.<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> In order to finance the film, Hoffman, Burg, and Koules put up a second mortgage on their [[Highland Avenue (Los Angeles)|Highland Avenue]] headquarters.<ref name=\"Variety2004\">{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117898181 |title='Saw' comes, conquers |last=Fleming |first=Mike |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=January 11, 2004 |accessdate=September 21, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130205092742/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117898181 |archivedate=February 5, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw'' was given a [[production budget]] of between $1 million and $1.2 million.{{#tag:ref|Sources for the budget figure vary. Some put the budget at $1 million,<ref name=\"TorontoStar\"/> $1.15 million<ref name=\"NYTimes2009\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html |title=Limbs Pile Up, and Money, Too |last=Lidz |first=Franz |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506040501/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html |archivedate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> and $1.2 million.<ref name=\"SMH\"/>  |group=note}}\n\n===Casting===\nCary Elwes was sent the short film on DVD and immediately became interested in the film. He read the script in one sitting and was drawn in by the \"uniqueness and originality\" of the story.<ref name=\"ElwesIGN\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p1.html|title=IGN Interviews Cary Elwes|last=Otto|first=Jeff|work=IGN|publisher=News Corporation|page=1|date=October 26, 2004|accessdate=August 18, 2011}}</ref> To prepare for his role as an [[Oncology|oncologist]], he met with a doctor at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]'s Department of [[Neurosurgery]].<ref name=\"ElwesIGN2\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p2.html |title=IGN Interviews Cary Elwes |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=2 |date=October 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126051813/http://movies.ign.com/articles/560/560508p2.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nShawnee Smith, who is not a horror fan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |title=Shawnee Smith: \"I Can't Watch Horror Movies\" |last=Wieselman |first=Jarett |work=[[New York Post]] |date=July 13, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111128193200/http://www.nypost.com/p/blogs/popwrap/item_ecYv5CaMbUmTLncDi0q6lK |archivedate=November 28, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> initially refused the role, describing the script as \"horrific\". However, after watching the short, she agreed to the role, which was the part that Whannell portrayed in the short.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/interviews/glover-danny-smith-shawnee-saw |title=Glover, Danny & Smith, Shawnee (Saw) |last=Condit |first=Jon |work=DreadCentral |publisher=[[CraveOnline]] |date=December 2, 2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021152701/http://www.dreadcentral.com/interviews/glover-danny-smith-shawnee-saw |archivedate=October 21, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn taking the role of Jigsaw, Tobin Bell said, \"I did ''Saw'' because I thought it was a fascinating location for a film to be made. These guys locked in a room, to me, was fresh. I did not anticipate the ending when I read the script, so I was quite caught by surprise and it was clear to me that if the filmmakers shot the scene well, the audience would be caught by surprise as well. The film was worth doing for that moment alone.\"<ref name=\"SawRevisted\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/22185 |title=Special Feature: 'Saw Revisited: Jigsaw's Long Journey' |last=Albin |first=Andrea |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=October 26, 2010 |accessdate=September 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101029202452/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/22185 |archivedate=October 29, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Filming and post-production===\nWith a shooting budget of $700,000,<ref name=\"AVClub\" /><ref name=\"Collider2011\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/james-wan-leigh-whannell-interview-insidious/83806/ |title=James Wan & Leigh Whannell Insidious Interview; The Saw Creators Also Discuss Their Untitled Sci-Fi Project, Nihtfall, and Recent Horror Remakes |last=Messer |first=Ron |publisher=Collider.com |date=April 4, 2011 |accessdate=April 4, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110806131151/http://collider.com/james-wan-leigh-whannell-interview-insidious/83806/ |archivedate=August 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''Saw'' began [[principal photography]] on {{nowrap|September 22, 2003}}<ref name=\"Variety2004\" /> at Lacy Street Production Facility in Los Angeles<ref name=\"SawProdNotes\" /> for 18 days.<ref name=\"Collider2011\" /> The bathroom was the only set that had to be built.<ref name=\"TheArrowMG_GH_OK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview137.htm |title=The Arrow interviews Gregg Hoffman, Oren Koules & Mark Burg |last=Fallon |first=John |publisher=JoBlo.com |year=2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141101054056/http://www.joblo.com/arrow/interview137.htm |archivedate=November 1, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Danny Glover]] completed his scenes in two days.<ref name=\"IGNpg3\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p3.html |title=Interview: James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=IGN |publisher=News Corporation |page=3 |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130126090136/http://movies.ign.com/articles/561/561009p3.html |archivedate=January 26, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Due to the tight [[shooting schedule]], Wan could not afford to shoot more than a couple of [[take]]s per actor.<ref name=\"BDInterview1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/42 |title=Saw: Director James Wan & Writer/Star Leigh Whannell |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |accessdate=August 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222220149/http://bloody-disgusting.com/interview/42 |archivedate=December 22, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> \"It was a really tough struggle for me. Every day, it was me fighting to get the shots I did not get. I had high aspirations, but there's only so much you can do. I wanted to make it in a very [[Hitchcockian]] style of filmmaking, but that style of filmmaking takes time to set up and so on\", Wan said about the very short shooting schedule.<ref name=\"AVClub\" /> He said the style instead ended up being \"more gritty and rough around the edges due to the lack of time and money that we had to shoot the movie with\" and it ultimately became the aesthetic of the film.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\nIn post-production, Wan found he did not have enough shots or takes to work with as he was basically shooting rehearsals. Having a lot of missing gaps in the final product, he and editor [[Kevin Greutert]] created shots to mend together during editing; such as making a shot look like a surveillance camera feed and using still photographs. \"We did a lot of things to fill in gaps throughout the film. Whatever we cut to newspaper clippings and stuff like that, or we cut to surveillance cameras, or we cut to [[Unit still photographer|still photography]] within the film, which now people say, 'Wow, that's such a cool experimental style of filmmaking', we really did that out of necessity to fill in gaps we did not get during the filming\", he explained.<ref name=\"AVClub\" />\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|Hello Zepp}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 5, 2004\n| recorded   = 2004\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]]<br />[[electro-industrial]]\n| length     = 57:29\n| label      = [[Entertainment One Music|Koch]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Saw II#Soundtrack|Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2005\n}}\nThe soundtrack was mainly composed by [[Charlie Clouser]], which took six weeks to complete.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://music.ign.com/articles/562/562509p3.html |title=Charlie Clouser Interview |author=Spence D. |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |page=3 |date=November 1, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120319115742/http://music.ign.com/articles/562/562509p3.html |archivedate=March 19, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other songs were performed by [[Front Line Assembly]], [[Fear Factory]], [[Enemy (American band)|Enemy]], Pitbull Daycare and Psycho Pumps. [[Megadeth]]'s song \"Die Dead Enough\" was originally set to be featured in the film, but was not used for undisclosed reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25140 |title=MEGADETH: 'Die Dead Enough' Single To Be Featured In Upcoming Horror Film |publisher=[[Blabbermouth.net]] |date=July 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050312232449/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25140 |archivedate=March 12, 2005 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25203 |title=Producer: MEGADETH's 'Die Dead Enough' Not Featured In 'Saw' Movie |publisher=Blabbermouth.net |date=July 28, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080921223302/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=25203 |archivedate=September 21, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe soundtrack was released on {{nowrap|October 5, 2004}} by [[Entertainment One Music|Koch Records]]. Johnny Loftus of [[AllMusic]] gave it three out of five stars. He said that Clouser \"really nails it with his creaky, clammy score\" and that he \"understands that ''Saw''{{'s}} horror only works with a heady amount of camp, and he draws from industrial music in the same way\". He particularly liked, \"Cigarette\"; \"Hello, Adam\"; and \"F**k This S*!t\", commenting that they \"blend chilling sounds with harsh percussion and deep-wound keyboard stabs\".<ref name=\"AllMusicReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r710182|title=Saw (Original) Motion Picture Soundtrack|last= Loftus|first=Johnny|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{tracklist\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline         = ''Saw Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n| extra_column = Artist\n| total_length = 57:29\n| title1 = Sturm\n| writer1         = [[Rhys Fulber]]<br />[[Bill Leeb]]\n| extra1 = [[Front Line Assembly]]\n| length1 = 6:07\n| title2 = Hello, Adam\n| writer2         = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| extra2 = Clouser\n| length2 = 3:57\n| title3 = Bite the Hand That Bleeds\n| writer3         =  [[Burton C. Bell]]<br />Fear Factory<br />[[Raymond Herrera]]<br />Olde Wolbers\n| extra3 = [[Fear Factory]]\n| length3 = 4:01\n| title4 = Last I Heard ... \n| writer4         = Clouser\n| extra4 = Clouser\n| length4 = 4:40\n| title5 = Action\n| writer5         = [[Jason Slater]]<br />[[Troy Van Leeuwen]]\n| extra5 = [[Enemy (American band)|Enemy]]\n| length5 = 3:43\n| title6 =  Reverse Beartrap\n| writer6         = Clouser\n| extra6 = Clouser\n| length6 = 4:47\n| title7 = You Make Me Feel So Dead\n| writer7         = Stephen Ladd Bishop<br />Charles Todd Conally<br />Don Van Stavern\n| extra7 = Pitbull Daycare\n| length7 =  3:49\n| title8 =  X Marks the Spot\n| writer8         = Clouser\n| extra8 = Clouser\n| length8 = 4:34\n| title9 = Wonderful World\n| writer9         = Flemming Norre Larsen<br />Jesper Schmidt\n| extra9 = Psycho Pumps\n| length9 = 5:00\n| title10 =  Cigarette\n| writer10         = Clouser\n| extra10 = Clouser\n| length10 = 3:07\n| title11 = We're Out of Time\n| writer11         = Clouser\n| extra11 = Clouser\n| length11 =  3:48\n| title12 = F**k This S*!t\n| writer12         = Clouser\n| extra12 = Clouser\n| length12 = 4:09\n| title13 = [[Hello Zepp]]\n| writer13         = Clouser\n| extra13 =  Clouser\n| length13 = 3:00\n| title14 =  Zepp Overture\n| writer14         = Clouser\n| extra14 = Clouser\n| length14 = 2:38\n}}\n\n==Release==\n[[Lions Gate Films]] picked up ''Saw''{{'s}} worldwide distribution rights at the [[Sundance Film Festival]] days before the film premiered on {{nowrap|January 19, 2004}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/lions_gate_gets_world_rights_to_sundance_midnight_film_saw/ |title=Lions Gate Gets World Rights To Sundance Midnight Film \"Saw\" |work=[[indieWire]] |date=January 13, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309222928/http://www.indiewire.com/article/lions_gate_gets_world_rights_to_sundance_midnight_film_saw |archivedate=March 9, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> There it played to a packed theater for three nights to a very positive reaction.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> It was the closing film at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on {{nowrap|September 18, 2004}}.<ref name=\"TorontoStar\">{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> Lions Gate initially planned to release the film [[direct-to-video]], but due to the positive reaction at Sundance, they chose to release it theatrically by Halloween.<ref name=\"Virginian\" /> It was released on {{nowrap|October 1, 2004}} in the United Kingdom, {{nowrap|October 29, 2004}} in the United States and {{nowrap|December 2, 2004}} in Australia. The film was originally rated [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|NC-17]] (No children under 17 permitted) by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] for strong graphic violence, though after being re-edited, it was released with an [[Motion picture content rating system|R rating]].<ref name=\"TheArrowMG_GH_OK\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/28/news/wk-movies28\\ |title=An outsider mentality |last=Abele |first=Robert |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 28, 2004 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016080337/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/28/news/wk-movies28 |archivedate=October 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lions Gate held the inaugural \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] and collected 4,249 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive |publisher=[[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] |date=August 6, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106140610/http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |archivedate=November 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109034821/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |archivedate=November 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Tenth anniversary re-release===\nOn October 31, 2014, in honor of the film's 10th anniversary, ''Saw'' was re-released to select theatres for one week.\n\nThe release earned only $650,051 in its opening weekend, and is the third lowest-grossing wide opening.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/worstopenings.htm?page=WRSTOPN20&p=.htm | title=Worst Openings at the Box Office for 2,000+ | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref> At the end of its run, the release had grossed $815,324, bringing the film's overall domestic gross to $56,000,369.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw10th.htm | title=Saw 10th Anniversary (2014) | work=Box Office Mojo | publisher=Internet Movie Database | date=November 6, 2014 | accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe theatrical version of the film was released on [[VHS]] and [[DVD]] on {{nowrap|February 15, 2005}} in the United States. After its first week, it made {{nowrap|$9.4 million}} in DVD rentals and {{nowrap|$1.7 million}} in VHS rentals, making it the top rental of the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1117 |title=Seeing Saw |work=The Numbers |publisher=Nash Information Services |date=February 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613174753/http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1117 |archivedate=June 13, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> For the second week it remained as the number one DVD rental with {{nowrap|$6.8 million}}, for a {{nowrap|$16.27 million}} two-week total. It dropped to third place in VHS rentals with {{nowrap|$1.09 million}}, for a {{nowrap|$2.83 million}} two-week total.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/interactive/newsStory.php?newsID=1137|title=Saw Remains on Top of Belated Rental Charts|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Services|date=March 5, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>  The film went on to sell more than $70 million worth of video and DVDs.<ref name=\"Reuters\" /> A two-disc \"Uncut Edition\" was released on {{nowrap|October 18, 2005}} to tie in with the release of ''[[Saw II]]''. The short film, also entitled ''Saw'', was included on the DVD.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtown.com/moviedatabase/release-details/saw/dvd/16836 |title=Details and specifications for Saw (Special Edition, Uncut) on DVD |publisher=DVD Town |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807094922/http://www.dvdtown.com/moviedatabase/release-details/saw/dvd/16836 |archivedate=August 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film was subsequently included in a boxed set with all six sequels entitled ''Saw: The Complete Movie Collection'', which was released in September 2014 for the film's tenth anniversary.  The set contained the unrated editions of all seven films, though it lacked any of the special features from previous releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Saw-Complete-Movie-Collection-Blu-ray/dp/B00MFCPVO6/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1436562992&sr=8-1&keywords=saw+the+complete+movie+collection|title=Saw 1 - 7 Movie Collection|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=February 3, 2018|website=Amazon.com}}</ref>\n\n====''Full Disclosure Report''====\n''Full Disclosure Report'' is a 2005 [[mockumentary]], pseudo-documentary set in the ''[[Saw (franchise)|Saw]]'' franchise, taking place between the events of ''Saw'' and ''[[Saw II]]'', around one year after the beginning of the Jigsaw murders, following television host Rich Skidmore as he commentates on the murders and the police work in the yet-unresolved case. [[Donnie Wahlberg]] appears as Detective Eric Matthews, prior to his appearance in ''Saw II''.\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw'' opened at #3 on [[Halloween]] weekend 2004 in 2,315 theaters and grossed {{nowrap|$18.2 million}}, behind ''[[Ray (film)|Ray]]'' ($20 million) and ''[[The Grudge]]'' ($21.8 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2004&wknd=44&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 29\u201331, 2004|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[Amazon.com]]|date=November 1, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> According to Lionsgate's exit poll, 60% of the mostly male audience was under 25 years of age. ''Saw'' had also become Lions Gate's second best opening, after ''[[Fahrenheit 9/11]]''{{'s}} {{nowrap|$23.9 million}} (2004).<ref name=\"BOMOpening\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1540&p=.htm|title='Ray,' 'Saw' See Robust Bows|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 1, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> On its second weekend, an additional 152 theaters were added, bringing the theater count to 2,467. It dropped to number four, making $11 million, a 39% drop from the opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2004&wknd=45&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for October 5\u20137, 2004|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 8, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n''Saw'' opened in the United Kingdom to {{nowrap|$2.2 million}} in 301 theaters, grossing a {{nowrap|$12.3 million}} total in seven weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=UK&id=saw.htm|title=United Kingdom and Ireland and Malta Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=November 14, 2004|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Australia, it opened in 161 theaters with {{nowrap|$1.2 million}} and totaled out to {{nowrap|$3.1 million}} in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=AU&id=saw.htm|title=Australia Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=March 10, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> In Italy, the film opened on {{nowrap|January 14, 2005}} in 267 theaters to {{nowrap|$1.7 million}} and grossed {{nowrap|$6.4 million}} in six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=IT&id=saw.htm|title=Italy Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=February 20, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Saw'' opened to {{nowrap|$1.5 million}} 187 theaters in France on {{nowrap|March 16, 2005}} and made {{nowrap|$3.1 million}} by the end of its four-week run.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=intl&country=FR&id=saw.htm|title=France and Algeria, Monaco, Morocco and Tunisia Weekend Box Office|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|date=April 12, 2005|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> ''Saw'' came to gross {{nowrap|$55.1 million}} in the United States and Canada and {{nowrap|$47.9 million}} in other markets for a worldwide total of {{nowrap|$103 million}}.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> It is the second lowest-grossing film in the series after ''[[Saw VI]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' vs 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> At the time, it became the most profitable horror film after ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' (1996).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/61775/ |title=Splattered: An Interview with James Wan Talking torture, politics and not-so-sweet revenge |last=Foundas |first=Scott |work=[[LA Weekly]] |date=August 30, 2011 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309195342/http://www.laweekly.com/content/printVersion/61775/ |archivedate=March 9, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)\n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)\n! colspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" | '''Box office gross'''<ref name=\"BOM\" />\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''North America'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other territories'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 29, 2004\n|align=\"center\" |$1,200,000\n|$55,185,045\n|$47,911,300\n|$103,096,345\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nCritical reception to ''Saw'' was mixed. On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has a rating of 49% based on 184 reviews, with an average rating of 5.53/10. The site's consensus reads, \"''Saw'' ensnares audiences with a deceptively clever plot and a myriad of memorable, nasty set pieces, but its lofty ambitions are undercut by a nihilistic streak that feels more mean than profound.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/| title=''Saw'' (2004)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = June 29, 2019}}</ref> Metacritic gave the film a score of 46 out of 100, based on 32 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw| title= Saw Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = October 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDennis Harvey of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a negative review after its Sundance premiere. He called it a \"crude concoction sewn together from the severed parts of prior horror/serial killer pics\".  He called the screenplay \"convoluted\", criticizing the use of \"flashbacks within flashbacks\" and [[red herring]]s. He described the film as being \"too hyperbolic to be genuinely disturbing\".<ref name=\"VarietyReview\">{{cite news|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117922951.html |title=Sundance Review |last=Harvey |first=Dennis |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=January 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 16, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008033538/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117922951/ |archivedate=October 8, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carla Meyer of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film a positive review saying the film \"combined B-movie acting with a twisted mind-set and visual tricks designed to camouflage cheap effects\" and that it was \"terrifying at some moments and insinuatingly creepy at many others\". She called the killing scenes \"amazingly evocative for such a low-budget movie\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/10/29/DDGRB9HIGS1.DTL |title=Cheap Thrills Sharpen Grisly 'Saw' |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |publisher=[[Hearst Corporation]] |date=October 29, 2004 |first=Carla |last=Meyer |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629045222/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2004/10/29/DDGRB9HIGS1.DTL&type=movies |archivedate=June 29, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'s}} [[Kim Newman]] gave the film four out of five stars. He said ''Saw'' is styled like early [[David Fincher]] films and \"boasts an intricate structure \u2014 complex flashbacks-within-flashbacks explain how the characters have come to this crisis \u2014 and a satisfying mystery to go with its ghastly claustrophobia.\" He ended his review saying, \"As good an all-out, non-camp horror movie as we've had lately.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10234 |title=Saw |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=April 1, 2006 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113224054/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=10234 |archivedate=November 13, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B minus, calling it \"derivative and messy and too nonsensical for its own good\".  He described Jigsaw's intent as \"to show you the serial killer lurking inside yourself\". Gleiberman criticized Elwes' performance by saying, \"[Elwes] ought to be featured in a seminar on the perils of [[overacting]].\"<ref name=\"EWReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,734839,00.html |title=Saw Review |last=Gleiberman |first=Owen |authorlink=Owen Gleiberman |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 27, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100105124526/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,734839,00.html |archivedate=January 5, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Daniel M. Kimmel]] of the ''[[Telegram & Gazette]]'' called it \"one of the most loathsome films this critic has seen in more than 20 years on the job\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Many will wish they'd never seen 'Saw'|last=M. Kimmel|first=Daniel|authorlink=Daniel M. Kimmel|work=[[Telegram & Gazette]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|date=October 30, 2004}}</ref>\n\n''[[The New York Times]]''{{'s}} [[Stephen Holden]] gave a mixed review saying the film \"does a better-than-average job of conveying the panic and helplessness of men terrorized by a sadist in a degrading environment, but it is still not especially scary. What sets its demon apart from run-of-the-mill movie serial killers is his impulse to humiliate and torture his victims and justify it with some twisted morality.\" He said the film is \"seriously undermined by the half-baked, formulaic detective story in which the horror is framed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2004/10/29/movies/29saw.html |title=A Gore Fest, With Overtones of Iraq and TV |last=Holden |first=Stephen |work=[[The New York Times]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |date=October 29, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120710144903/http://movies.nytimes.com/2004/10/29/movies/29saw.html |archivedate=July 10, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carina Chocano of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' also gave the film a mixed review saying, \"''Saw'' is so full of twists it ends up getting snarled. For all of his flashy engineering and inventive torture scenarios, the Jigsaw Killer comes across as an amateur. [[Hannibal Lecter]] would have him for lunch.\" She said the film \"carelessly underscores its own shaky narrative at every turn with its mid-budget hokiness\". She also noted that Elwes and Whannell had trouble keeping an American accent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/29/entertainment/et-saw29 |title='Saw' would work better if sharpened |last=Chocano |first=Carina |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 29, 2004 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016080331/http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/29/entertainment/et-saw29 |archivedate=October 16, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Another mixed review came from [[Roger Ebert]], who gave the film 2 out of 4 stars and lamented the gimmicks and plot contrivances but nonetheless described ''Saw'' as \"well made and acted, and does what it does about as well as it could be expected to\".<ref>[[Roger Ebert]] (2004) \"[http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/saw-2004 Saw]\", accessed 10 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Comparisons to ''Seven'' (1995)===\nWhen asked if the 1995 thriller film ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]'' was an inspiration to ''Saw'', Whannell said \"For me as the writer, definitely. I mean, ''Seven'' is just a very well constructed film, and if you're writing a thriller, it can't hurt to study it. In terms of the story though, James and I never really felt ''Seven'' was that close to our film. I guess if you stand back, you have two detectives chasing a psychopath, who uses vile methods to teach people lessons, and those points echo ''Seven''. What we always liked about ''Saw'', though, was the fact that the story is told from the point of view of two of the psychopath's victims, instead of the police chasing after him, as you so often see.\"<ref name=\"TheArrowWhannell\" /> ''Entertainment Weekly''{{'s}} Owen Gleiberman compared the plot to ''Seven'' saying, \"In a blatant imitation of ''Seven'', ''Saw'' features a lunatic sadist whose ghoulish crimes are meant, in each case, to mirror the sins of his victims. The twist here is that the psycho doesn't do the killing.\"<ref name=\"EWReview\" /> Richard J. Leskosky of [[Champaign\u2013Urbana metropolitan area|Champaign-Urbana]]'s ''The News-Gazette'' said \"''Saw'' wants to be taken as another ''Seven''. Though it features perverse gross-out scenes and a villain with a superficially pedantic motive behind his crimes (his victims, if they survive, have learned to appreciate life more), it lacks the finesse and polish of the David Fincher film.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Improbable ' Saw ' surprises, but still not worth a see |last=J. Leskosky|first=Richard|work=The News-Gazette|location=[[Champaign-Urbana Metropolitan Area|Champaign-Urbana]], [[Illinois|IL]]|date=November 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n[[Bloody Disgusting]] ranked the film tenth in its list of the Top 20 Horror Films of the Decade, with the article calling ''Saw'' \"perhaps the most influential horror film of the decade, which kick-started a franchise. ... In light of its measly $1.2 million price tag the film's quality relative to bigger-budget horror films is striking. It also takes itself seriously, which came as a breath of fresh air following the trend of wimpy tongue-in-cheek horror that had dominated the multiplexes post-''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]''. More than anything, this twisted morality tale is a film made by horror fans, for horror fans; it's gory, it's depraved, and best of all it introduced a new horror icon in Jigsaw.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18425 |title=00's Retrospect: Bloody Disgusting's Top 20 Films of the Decade ... Part 3 |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |date=December 17, 2009 |accessdate=January 3, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810151317/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/18425 |archivedate=August 10, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' listed the film number 14 on their Top 100 list that defined the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6501160/Top-100-movies-defining-the-noughties-00s-in-film.html |title=The films that defined the noughties |last=Gritten |first=David |last2=Robey |first2=Tim |last3=Sandhu |first3=Sukhdev |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=November 6, 2009 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825145737/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/6501160/Top-100-movies-defining-the-noughties-00s-in-film.html |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Brussels International Fantastic Film Festival]]\n| Pegasus Audience Award\n|rowspan=2| [[James Wan]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Fantasporto]]\n| International Fantasy Film Award- Best Film\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Golden Trailer Awards]]\n| Best Horror\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Festival international du film fantastique de G\u00e9rardmer]]\n| Special Jury Prize\n|rowspan=2| James Wan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Youth Jury Grand Prize\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Frightened Performance\n| [[Cary Elwes]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[San Sebasti\u00e1n International Film Festival]]\n| Audience Award- Best Feature\n| James Wan\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Satellite Awards]]\n| Outstanding DVD Extras (Uncut Edition)\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Release|Best DVD Special Edition Release]]\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]]\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Scream Scene\n| [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Thriller\n| align=\"center\" |\u2014\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=note/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0387564|Saw}}\n* {{metacritic film|saw|Saw}}\n* {{mojo title|saw|Saw}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|saw|Saw}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{James Wan}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw (Film)}}\n[[Category:Saw films|1]]\n[[Category:2004 films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2004 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:English-