{"title_page": "Saw II", "text_new": "{{about|the film|the video game|Saw II: Flesh & Blood}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw II\n| image = Saw II poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Leigh Whannell]]\n* Darren Lynn Bousman\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]\n* [[Erik Knudsen]]\n* [[Franky G]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]]\n* [[Beverly Mitchell]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n}}\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Lions Gate Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|2005|10|28|United States}}\n| runtime = 93 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 92:40--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-ii-2005 | title=''SAW II'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 21, 2005 | accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = United States<br/>Canada<ref>https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8b62c042</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $4 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web|title=Saw II|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2005/SAW2.php}}</ref> \n| gross = $147.7 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Saw II''''' is a 2005 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] and written by [[Leigh Whannell]] and Bousman. It is the second installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Donnie Wahlberg]], [[Tobin Bell]], [[Shawnee Smith]], [[Erik Knudsen]], [[Franky G]], [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]], [[Glenn Plummer]], [[Beverly Mitchell]], and [[Dina Meyer]].\n\nThe film features [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] being apprehended by the police, but trapping the arresting officer in one of his own games while showing another game of eight people \u2014 including the officer's son \u2014 in progress on TV monitors at another location. It also explores some of John Kramer's backstory, providing a partial explanation of his reason for becoming Jigsaw.\n\nAfter the financial success of 2004's ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', a sequel was immediately green-lit. Leigh Whannell and [[James Wan]] were busy preparing for their next film and were unable to write or direct. Bousman wrote a script called ''The Desperate'' before ''Saw'' was released and was looking for a producer but many studios rejected it. [[Gregg Hoffman]] received the script and showed it to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]]. It was decided that, with some changes, it could be made into ''Saw II''. Whannell became available to provide rewrites of the script. The film was given a larger budget and was shot from May to June 2005 in Toronto.\n\n''Saw II'' was released in the United States on October 28, 2005, by [[Lions Gate Films]]. Despite mixed reviews from critics, the film was a financial success. It opened with $31.9 million and grossed $88 million in the United States and Canada. It has remained the highest grossing ''Saw'' film in those countries. Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2006 MTV Movie Awards]] for his role as Jigsaw in the film. ''Saw II'' was released to [[DVD]] on February 14, 2006, and topped charts its first week, selling more than 3 million units. At the time, it was the fastest-selling theatrical DVD in Lions Gate's history. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw III]]'', was released in 2006.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Long plot|date=July 2019}}\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 to 700 words. -->\nInformant Michael Marks awakens in a room with a spike-filled mask locked around his neck. A videotape informs him that in order to unlock the device, he must cut into his eye to obtain the key. He sets off the timer and finds the scalpel, but cannot bring himself to retrieve the key and is killed after sixty seconds when the mask closes.\n\nAt the scene of Michael's game, Detective Allison Kerry finds a message for her former partner, [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]], and calls him in. Despite not wanting to be involved in the case, Eric reluctantly joins Kerry and Officer Daniel Rigg in leading a [[SWAT]] team to the factory, which produced the lock from Michael's trap. There they find and apprehend John Kramer, the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]], who is weak from cancer. He indicates several computer monitors showing eight people trapped in a house; including his only known survivor [[Amanda Young]], and Eric's estranged son Daniel. The other victims are Xavier, Gus, Jonas, Laura, Addison, and Obi. A nerve agent filling the house will kill them all within two hours, but John assures Eric that if he follows the rules of his own game, by simply talking with John, he will see Daniel again. At Kerry's urging, Eric agrees in order to buy time for the tech team to arrive and trace the video signal.\n\nThe victims are informed by a microcassette recorder that antidotes are hidden throughout the house; one is in the room's safe, and they have the combination with the \"numbers in the back of their mind\". Xavier ignores a warning note and uses the key provided with the cassette on the door, which fires a bullet through the peephole as Gus looks through it, killing him. They search the house for more antidotes after the door opens, but with no success. After discovering a door, the group travel to the basement where Obi, who is revealed to have helped with the abductions, is forced into a crematory oven to obtain two antidotes. He inadvertently activates the trap and is burned to death before the others can save him, destroying the antidotes as well. In another room, Xavier's test is to go into a pit full of needles and retrieve the key to the door in two minutes, but he instead throws Amanda into the pit and forces her to do it. Pressured, she searches through the needle pit until finally retrieving the key, which she gives to Xavier, but he runs out of time to unlock the door containing the antidote. Throughout the game, the victims discuss connections between them and determine that each has been incarcerated before, excluding Daniel.\n\nMeanwhile, John passes the time with both idle and cryptic chat, eventually telling Eric that his survival of a suicide attempt after his diagnosis is the true reason for his games. Then, he destroys several of John's documents and sketches at Kerry's suggestion, but fails to provoke John. As the tech team arrives, John reveals the connection between the victims: Eric has framed all of them for various crimes.\n\nHaving left the others, Xavier returns to the safe room and finds a colored number on the back of Gus' neck. After realizing the answer to the clue, he kills Jonas with a spiked bat for his number after a brief fight and begins hunting the others. Laura succumbs to the nerve agent and dies; after finding the clue revealing Daniel's identity, Addison and Amanda abandon him, but Amanda returns after finding Jonas' body. Addison finds a glass box containing an antidote, but her arms become trapped in the arm holes which are lined with hidden blades. Xavier enters the room, reads Addison\u2019s number, and leaves her to die. Amanda and Daniel find a tunnel in the safe room, which leads to the bathroom from [[Saw (2004 film)|the first film]]. Daniel collapses inside just before Xavier finds them. Amanda notes that he cannot read his own number, so he cuts a piece of the back of his neck off. As he approaches Amanda as an attempt to kill her, Daniel, who feigned his collapse, jumps in the way and slashes his throat with a hacksaw, killing him.\n\nHaving seen Xavier chasing his son, Eric brutally assaults John and forces him to lead him to the house. John's sitting area is revealed to be an elevator, which they use to leave the factory. The tech team tracks the video's source and Rigg leads his team to a house, where they find VCRs playing previously recorded images. As Kerry realizes the game took place \"before\" they found John, the timer expires and a large safe opens, revealing Daniel bound and breathing into an oxygen mask. Eric enters the house alone and eventually locates the bathroom, where he is attacked by a pig-masked figure. He awakens shackled at the ankle to a pipe, and a tape recorder left by Amanda reveals that she is John's accomplice and intends to continue his work after he dies. Amanda suddenly appears in the doorway, and yells \"Game Over\" before sealing the door, leaving Eric to die.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Erik Knudsen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Matthews|Daniel Matthews]]\n* [[Franky G]] as [[List of Saw characters#Xavier Chavez|Xavier]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jonas Singer|Jonas]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]] as [[List of Saw characters#Addison Corday|Addison]]\n* [[Beverley Mitchell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Laura Hunter|Laura]]\n* Timothy Burd as [[List of Saw characters#Obi Tate|Obi]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Officer Daniel Rigg]]\n* Noam Jenkins as [[List of Saw characters#Michael Marks|Michael Marks]]\n* Tony Nappo as [[List of Saw characters#Gus Colyard|Gus]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[File:Saw two banned poster.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The original teaser poster showing two bloody severed fingers that was banned by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]].]]\n''Saw II'' was immediately [[Green-light|green-lit]] after ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''{{'}}s successful opening weekend a year earlier.<ref name=\"IGNFeb2005\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/586/586613p1.html |title=IGN Interviews James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=February 9, 2005 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212164031/http://movies.ign.com/articles/586/586613p1.html |archivedate=February 12, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> Producers needed a script for a sequel <ref name=\"FilmMonthly\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/LeighWhannell/LeighWhannell.html \n |title=Leigh Returns to the Saw \n |last=Fischer \n |first=Paul \n |work=Film Monthly \n |date=October 26, 2005 \n |accessdate=August 22, 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617eiopaX \n |archivedate=August 22, 2011 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> but [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], director and writer of ''Saw'', were working on [[Universal Pictures]]'s ''[[Dead Silence]]''. Music video director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] had just completed a script for his first film ''The Desperate'', and was trying to sell it to studios but was getting reactions that the script was very similar to ''Saw''. A German studio eventually approached him with an offer to produce the film for $1 million. Just as they were looking for a cinematographer, the American cinematographer David A. Armstrong, who had worked on ''Saw'', arrived on the scene and suggested showing the script to ''Saw'' producer [[Gregg Hoffman]].<ref name=\"BDDarren2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/155 |title=Saw II: Director Darren Bousman & Writer Leigh Whannell |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |year=2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617eli0Lg |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Hoffman read the script and called Bousman wanting to produce ''The Desperate''. After Hoffman showed the script to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]],<ref name=\"BousmanOfficial\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darrenlynnbousman.com/films-dlb/saw2/ |title=Saw II |publisher=Darren Lynn Bousman Official Site |last=Bousman |first=Darren Lynn |authorlink=Darren Lynn Bousman |year=2010 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AVQapvJ |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> the two decided that ''The Desperate'' was the starting script they needed for ''Saw II'' and two months later, Bousman was flown to [[Toronto]] to direct.<ref name=\"BousmanOfficial\"/>\n\nWhannell polished the script, with input from Wan,<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/> in order to bring it into the ''Saw'' universe,<ref name=\"FilmMonthly\"/> but kept the characters, traps and deaths from ''The Desperate'' script.<ref name=\"BDFeb2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/215 |title=Saw II DVD: Director Darren Lynn Bousman |last=Lamkin |first=Elaine |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=February 2006 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CC6Ly0l |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Bousman said, \"But you could read the script for ''The Desperate'' and watch ''Saw II'', and you would not be able to draw a comparison\".<ref name=\"BDDarren2005\"/>  Wan and Whannell also served as executive producers. All the previous film's crew members returned: editor [[Kevin Greutert]], cinematographer Armstrong, and composer [[Charlie Clouser]].  This was to be Hoffman's last film. He died unexpectedly on December 4, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/dec/15/guardianobituaries.film |title=Obituary: Gregg Hoffman |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=December 15, 2005 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CCxWwLH |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOnly those key cast and crew members who were involved in the film's ending were given the full script; the rest received only the first 88 pages. If a particular page was rewritten, the old page was shredded. Members were also required to sign [[Non-disclosure agreement|confidentiality agreements]] requiring them not to release any plot details.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-3 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #3 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |authorlink=Gregg Hoffman |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |page=3 |date=May 20, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AcxQiJx |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Reportedly, \"four or five\" alternate endings were shot in order to keep the ending a surprise.<ref name=\"SawIINotes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw2/docs/pro_notes.doc |title=Saw II Production Notes |publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]] |format=1.40MB [[Doc (computing)|.DOC]] file |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61zDPmBZM |archivedate=September 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Bousman gave the actors freedom to change dialogue in the script. He said that 95% of the time, the actors went by the script, with about 5% being [[Ad libitum|adlib]]s, which he said \"made all of the difference in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/od/saw2/a/saw2db021406_3.htm |title=One on One with \"Saw II\" Writer/Director Darren Lynn Bousman |last=Murray |first=Rebecca |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |page=3 |date=February 14, 2006 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AWraMCm |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hoffman said in an interview with ''[[Fangoria]]'' that they listened to fans' suggestions. For instance, instead of only showing the aftermath of a character violently dying in a flashback, they would allow it to unfold as it happened. This was in contrast to ''Saw'', in which most of the violence was implied off-screen.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw II: Building a Better Human Trap|issn=0164-2111|number=248|date=November 2005|page=30}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and post-production===\n''Saw II'' was given a larger production budget of $4 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1 |title=Evolution of Scary Movies |last=Rooney |first=Brian |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=October 27, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617rX6x73 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> compared to ''Saw''{{'}}s budget of a little over $1 million.<ref name=\"TorontoStar\">{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> The marketing budget was an additional $2 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117942674 |title=Lionsgate: The hidden enigma |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=May 7, 2006 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62Ra0fOTm |archivedate=October 15, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first shot, which involved shooting police cars and a SWAT van driving around the industrial docklands outside the soundstage,<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/?id=7379 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #1 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=1 |date=May 6, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ab1u2jk |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> was filmed on {{nowrap|April 29, 2005}} in Toronto. After two months of pre-production,<ref name=\"BDFeb2006\"/> [[principal photography]] took place over 25 days at Toronto's [[Cinespace Film Studios]] from {{nowrap|May 2, 2005}} to {{nowrap|June 6, 2005}}.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt1\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw II: Building a Better Human Trap|issn=0164-2111|number=248|date=November 2005|page=29}}</ref><ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-5 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #5 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=5 |date=June 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AfJfhNH |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The ending was filmed on May 25 and 26.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-4 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #4 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=4 |date=May 27, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AeGrOI6 |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The music and sound was recorded in July and ''Saw II'' was [[Picture lock|locked]] on {{nowrap|July 16}}. It was completely finished by {{nowrap|September 9}}.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt5\"/> Visual effects were performed by [[C.O.R.E.|C.O.R.E. Digital Pictures]] and post-production services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]].<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/>\n\n===Trap designs===\n[[David Hackl]], the film's production designer, took three weeks to construct 27 sets on a single sound stage.<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/> The puppet [[Billy the Puppet|Billy]], used in the series to give instructions to Jigsaw's victims, was originally created by Wan out of paper towel rolls and [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]]. Given the larger budget for the sequel, Billy was upgraded with remote-controlled eyes and a [[Servomechanism|servo]]-driven mouth.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-2 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #2 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=2 |date=May 13, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AcAwHaK |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> In one trap, \"The Needle Room\", Smith's character Amanda is thrown into a pit of needles to find a key. In order for this to be done safely, four people, over a period of four days, removed the needle tips from syringes and replaced them with fiber optic tips. They modified a total of 120,000 fake needles. However, this number was insufficient and the pit had to be filled with styrofoam and other materials to make it appear to have more needles. The needles that were apparently stuck into Smith were actually blunted syringes stuck into padding under her clothing. For certain shots, a fake arm was used.<ref>{{cite video |people=[[David Hackl]] (production designer), Jim Murray (property master), Darren Lynn Bousman (writer/director) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Needle Pit |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Darren Lynn Bousman CC.JPG|thumb|right|''Saw II'' was Bousman's first feature film.]]\nBousman came up with an idea whereby a character's hands would get stuck in some sort of vessel and this resulted in the \"Hand Trap\". It proved to be a challenge but after much discussion, Hackl, property master Jim Murray and art director Michele Brady came up with a suitable design. They arranged a glass box suspended by chains from the ceiling which contained a hypodermic needle with the antidote and which had two hand-holes on the underside. As soon as Vaugier's character Addison put her hands into the holes razor blades would close in on her hands and any attempt to withdraw from the trap would cause her to bleed to death. In order for the trap to be used safely, the prop builders made the handcuffs move inside the box and fake blades that would retract from the actress's hands, thus allowing her to slide her hands out. Hackl subsequently commented that the character did not have to put her hands into the trap as there was a lock with a key on the other side box that would have opened the contraption.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://machinedesign.com/article/how-to-engineer-a-nightmare-1023 |title=How to Engineer a Nightmare |last=Shapiro |first=Jessica |journal=[[Machine Design]] |volume=80 |issue=20 |pages=22\u201323 |date=October 23, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62GdveX3S |archivedate=October 7, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite video |people=David Hackl (production designer) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Hand Trap |medium=DVD |publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe original idea for the \"Furnace Trap\" came from the house having been a [[Crematory|crematorium]] at some point, but this would have involved turning the house into a funeral parlor, so it was instead decided that the furnace would be part of the house's boiler system. The furnace was visualized in the form of a computer model so that Bousman could better understand how shots could be filmed. Using the computer model as a guide, the furnace was constructed in three days using cement board and tin with removable sides and top so Timothy Burd (Obi) could be filmed crawling inside. The furnace produced real flames and, in place of Burd, a stunt man using a fire retardant gel crawled into the fire.<ref>{{cite video |people=David Hackl (production designer) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Furnace |medium=DVD |publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name         = Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Various Artists\n| cover        =\n| caption      ={{deletable image-caption|Wednesday, 13 November 2019|PROD}}\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2005|10|25}}\n| recorded     = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Industrial metal]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]|[[alternative metal]]|[[nu metal]]}}\n| length       = {{Duration|m=54|s=46}}\n| label        = [[Image Entertainment]]\n| producer     = {{hlist|[[Mark Burg]] <small>([[Executive producer|{{abbr|exec.|executive producer}}]])</small>|[[Gregg Hoffman]] <small>(exec.)</small>|[[Oren Koules]] <small>(exec.)</small>|Jonathan Platt|Jonathan Scott Miller|Martin Shore|Stu Song}}\n| prev_title   = [[Saw (soundtrack)|Saw: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year    = 2004\n| next_title   = [[Saw III (soundtrack)|Saw III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year    = 2006\n| misc         = \n}}\nThe ''Saw II'' soundtrack was released on October 25, 2005 by [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> The video for \"[[Forget to Remember]]\" was also directed by Bousman.<ref>{{cite video|title=Saw II Commentary|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]]|people=Darren Lynn Bousman, Donnie Wahlberg and Beverly Mitchell|date=2006 | accessdate=August 26, 2011|time=1:29:11\u2013 1:29:13}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| extra_column = Artist\n| title1 = Irresponsible Hate Anthem (Venus Head Trap Mix)\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Scott Putesky|Daisy Berkowitz]]|[[Madonna Wayne Gacy]]|[[Marilyn Manson]]|[[Twiggy Ramirez]]}}\n| extra1 = [[Marilyn Manson]]\n| length1 = 3:39\n| title2 = Sound Effects and Overdramatics\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[Quinn Allman]]|[[The Used|Jeph Howard]]|[[Bert McCracken]]|[[Branden Steineckert]]}}\n| extra2 = [[The Used]]\n| length2 = 3:28\n| title3 = [[Forget to Remember]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|[[Chad Gray]]|[[Ryan Martinie]]|[[Matthew McDonough]]|[[Greg Tribbett]]}}\n| extra3 = [[Mudvayne]]\n| length3 = 3:33\n| title4 = September\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Chris Hamilton|Mike Kennedy|Nick Rowe|[[Hellyeah|Kyle Sanders]]|Tim Williams}}\n| extra4 = [[Bloodsimple]]\n| length4 = 3:38\n| title5 = Blood (Empty Promises)\n| writer5 = {{hlist|[[Papa Roach|Dave Buckner]]|[[Papa Roach|Tobin Esperance]]|[[Jerry Horton]]|[[Jacoby Shaddix]]}}\n| extra5 = [[Papa Roach]]\n| length5 = 2:56\n| title6 = REV 22:20 (REV 4:20 Mix)\n| writer6 = {{hlist|[[Maynard James Keenan]]|[[Danny Lohner]]}}\n| extra6 = [[Puscifer]]\n| length6 = 4:47\n| title7 = [[Next (Sevendust album)|Pieces]]\n| writer7 = [[Sevendust]]\n| extra7 = [[Sevendust]]\n| length7 = 3:06\n| title8 = Rodent (Ken \"Hiwatt\" Marshall/DDT Mix)\n| writer8 = {{hlist|[[Al Jourgensen]]|[[Skinny Puppy]]}}\n| extra8 = [[Skinny Puppy]]\n| length8 = 5:00\n| title9 = [[Burn the Witch (Queens of the Stone Age song)|Burn the Witch]] ([[Unkle|UNKLE]] Variation)\n| writer9 = {{hlist|[[Joey Castillo]]|[[Josh Homme]]|[[Troy Van Leeuwen]]}}\n| extra9 = [[Queens of the Stone Age]]\n| length9 = 3:04\n| title10 = Holy\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Shaun Bivens|Tony Providence|Allen Richardson}}\n| extra10 = [[A Band Called Pain]]\n| length10 = 3:43\n| title11 = [[Enter the Chicken#Three Fingers|Three Fingers]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Buckethead|[[Dan Monti]]|[[Saul Williams]]}}\n| extra11 = [[Buckethead|Buckethead and Friends]] & [[Saul Williams]]\n| length11 = 3:00\n| title12 = Home Invasion Robbery\n| writer12 = [[The Legion of Doom (mash up group)|The Legion of Doom]]\n| extra12 = [[The Legion of Doom (mash up group)|The Legion of Doom]]\n| length12 = 4:10\n| title13 = Caliente (Dark Entries)\n| writer13 = {{hlist|[[Daniel Ash]]|[[Kevin Haskins]]|[[David J]]|[[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]]}}\n| extra13 = [[Revolting Cocks]], [[Gibby Haynes]] & [[Al Jourgensen]]\n| length13 = 4:28\n| title14 = Step Up\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Andrew Gerold|[[Jim Kaufman]]|[[John Travis (producer)|John Travis]]|[[Ron Underwood (musician)|Ron Underwood]]}}\n| extra14 = [[Opiate for the Masses]]\n| length14 = 3:24\n| title15 = Don't Forget the Rules\n| writer15 = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| extra15 = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| length15 = 5:00\n| total_length = 54:46\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Saw II'' was released in New Zealand, the United States, and the United Kingdom on {{nowrap|October 28, 2005}}; and {{nowrap|November 17, 2005}} in Australia. The original teaser poster showing two bloody, severed fingers, representing the Roman numeral, II, was rejected by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2005/08/22/saw-ii-sees-ads-yanked |title=Saw II Sees Ads Yanked |last=David |first=Erik |work=[[Moviefone]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=August 22, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AZlBCgp |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since the poster was already released and managed to \"slip by\" the MPAA, they issued a release stating the poster was not approved and was unacceptable; [[Lions Gate Films]] removed the poster from their websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/index.php?id=8380 |title=Saw 2 Poster Banned |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |accessdate=August 22, 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617es9xD4 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The image was used instead for the film's soundtrack cover.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/saw-2-r794014|title=Saw 2 - Original Soundtrack|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> Lionsgate held the second annual \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[Red Cross]] and collected 10,154 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive |publisher=[[Red Cross]] |date=August 6, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61eiTSBkv |archivedate=September 13, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61edOe9qM |archivedate=September 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Saw II'' was released on [[DVD]], [[VHS]], and [[Universal Media Disc]] on February 14, 2006 through [[Lions Gate Home Entertainment]]. The DVD debuted as number one selling 2.5 million units in its first day. It went on to sell 3.9 million units its first week, becoming the fastest selling theatrical DVD in Lions Gate's history.<ref name=\"CNWGroup2\">{{cite news|title=Jigsaw Is Back With a Vengeance as Lionsgate's SAW II Has Teeth in Debut on Home Entertainment Charts |agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=February 22, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2006, an Unrated Special Edition was released, while an Unrated [[Blu-ray]] edition was also released with various special features on January 23, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/561/sawii.html |title=Saw II (Bluray) |publisher=High-Def Digest |date=January 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fB0GAE |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://homevideo.about.com/od/horror/p/saw2dvdsawiidvd.htm |title=Saw II DVD Unrated Special Edition Release Date |publisher=[[About.com]] |date=October 24, 2006 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fJr7Sk |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw II'' opened with $31.7 million on 3,879 screens across 2,949 theaters.<ref name=\"BOMWeekend\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1930&p=.htm |title='Saw II' Gores 'Zorro' on Halloween Weekend |last=Gray |first=Brandon |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=October 31, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AgXubSc |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The three-day [[Halloween]] opening weekend set a Lions Gate record. It became at the time, the widest release for Lionsgate and one of the best opening weekends for a horror sequel.<ref name=\"CNWGroup\">{{cite news|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures Announce SAW III for Halloween 2006|agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=March 3, 2006}}</ref> For its second weekend it fell 47% making $16.9 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1935&p=.htm |title=Welcome to the Cluck: 'Chicken Little,' 'Jarhead' Top Weekend |last=Gray |first=Brandon |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 7, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AiStFVm |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film was closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|January 5, 2006}} after 70 days of release.\n\n''Saw II'' opened in the United Kingdom with $3.8 million on 305 screens, 70% larger than the first instalment. It opened in Japan on 67 screens with $750,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1932&p=.htm |title=Around the World Roundup: 'Zorro' Leaves Modest Mark in Mass Foreign Bow |last=Bresnan |first=Conor |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 1, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AhvJadN |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Opening to $1.3 million on 173 screens it was the number one film in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1948&p=.htm |title=Around the World Roundup: 'Harry Potter' on Fire in Foreign Bow |last=Bresnan |first=Conor |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AisQFwc |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film grossed $87 million in the United States and Canada and $60.7 million in other markets for a worldwide total of $147.7 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2.htm|title=Saw II (2005)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> The film is the 2nd highest-grossing film of the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' series]], only behind ''Saw III'' and Lionsgate's fourth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref> According to [[CinemaScore]] polls, 53% of the audience were males under 25 years of age. The poll also indicated that 65% of the audience were familiar with the first film.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001393198 |title='Saw II' cuts through b.o. with $31.7 mil debut |last=Fuson |first=Brian |work=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]] |date=November 1, 2005 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/619CK762U |archivedate=August 23, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Release date'''<br />(United States)\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''United States/Canada'''\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Other markets'''\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 28, 2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $4,000,000\n|$87,039,965\n|$60,708,540\n|$147,748,505\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received generally mixed reviews from critics, who praised the acting, particularly the performances of Bell and Wahlberg, while criticizing the gruesome nature of the story. Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 37% of 122 critics have given the film a positive review, with a rating average of 4.59/10. The site's consensus was, \"Saw II is likely to please the gore-happy fans of the original, though it may be too gruesome for those not familiar with first film's premise.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/| title=Saw II (2005)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = March 20, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which assigns a weighted average score out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, gives the film a score of 40 based on 28 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews| title= Saw II Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRobert Koehler of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a negative review, saying \"cooking up new Rube Goldberg torture contraptions isn't enough to get ''Saw II'' out of the shadow of its unnerving predecessor\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117928622?categoryid=31&cs=1 |title=Saw II Review |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |accessdate=October 20, 2005 |first=Robert |last=Koehler |date=October 20, 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fegEfp |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gregory Kirschling of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B minus, saying \"''Saw II'' is just barely a better [[B movie|B flick]] than ''Saw''\" and that both films are \"more clever and revolting than they are actually chilling\". He praised Bell's performance as Jigsaw, saying \"As the droopy-lidded maniac in the flesh, Tobin Bell is, for all the film's gewgaws, ''Saw II''{{'s}} sturdiest horror, a [[Terence Stamp]] look-alike who calls to mind a seedy [[General Zod]] lazily overseeing the universe from his evildoer's lair\".  He ended his review: \"Where ''Saw II'' lags behind in Saw's novelty, it takes the lead with its smoother landing, which is again primed to blow the movie wide open, but manages a more compelling job of it than the original's cheat finish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1123047,00.html |title=Movie Review Saw II (2005) |last=Kirschling |first=Gregory |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 26, 2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617hi5y12 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKevin Crust of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, calling ''Saw II'' a \"worthy follow-up to its grisly predecessor\". He said the story was \"much more focused on an endgame than the original film. There are fewer credibility gaps and there are plenty of reversals to satisfy fans\". He criticized the use of numerous flashbacks, saying that it \"rob[s] us of the pleasure of actually remembering for ourselves\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/28/entertainment/et-saw28 |title=Grisly 'Saw II' makes the cut |last=Crust |first=Kevin |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 29, 2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617jXtG4P |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laura Kern, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', gave it a mixed review, saying that Bousman \"delivers similar hard-core, practically humorless frights and hair-raising tension, but only after getting past a shaky beginning that plays more like a forensics-themed television show than a scary movie\" and called Greutert's editing \"crafty\". She called the sequel \"more trick than treat\" and that it \"doesn't really compare to its fine predecessor - though it still manages to be eye-opening (and sometimes positively nauseating) in itself\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2005/10/28/movies/28saw.html |title=Round 2 in a House of Horror |last=Kern |first=Laura |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714032226/http://movies.nytimes.com/2005/10/28/movies/28saw.html |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Kim Newman]] gave the film three out of five stars. He said that the film improves upon ''Saw''{{'s}} \"perverse fascination with ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]''-style murders and brutally violent puzzles\" and that Jigsaw's intellectual games make \"[[Hannibal Lecter]] look like the compiler of ''The Sun''{{'}}s quick crossword\". He ended his reviews saying, \"Morally dubious it may be, but this gory melange of torture, terror and darkly humorous depravity appeals to the sick puppy within us all\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=132340 |title=Saw II Movie Review |last=Newman |first=Kim |authorlink=Kim Newman |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=October 2005 |accessdate=September 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61oExb0Km |archivedate=September 19, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nTobin Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2006 MTV Movie Awards]] for his role as Jigsaw,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wedding_crashers/news/1646716/get_your_goofy_mtv_movie_awards_noms_right_here |title=Get Your Goofy MTV Movie Awards Noms Right Here |last=Weinberg |first=Scott |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Flixster |date=April 26, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208110313/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wedding_crashers/news/1646716/get_your_goofy_mtv_movie_awards_noms_right_here |archivedate=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> though the award went to [[Hayden Christensen]] for his role as [[Darth Vader]] in ''[[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2006/ |title=2006 Movie Awards Summary |publisher=[[MTV.com]] |date=June 8, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617g11whd |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Directors Guild of Canada]]\n| Outstanding Sound Editing - Feature Film\n| Rob Bertola; Tom Bjelic; Allan Fung; Mark Gingras; John Laing; Paul Shikata; [[John Douglas Smith]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Fangoria Chainsaw Awards\n| Best Villain\n| [[Tobin Bell]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Movie Acards]]\n| Best Villain\n| [[Tobin Bell]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Special Edition Release|Best DVD Special Edition Release]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie: Scream\n| [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Thriller\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0432348}}\n*{{metacritic film|saw-ii|Saw II}}\n*{{mojo title|saw2|Saw II}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|saw_ii|Saw II}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 2}}\n[[Category:Saw films|2]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2005 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:2005 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the film|the video game|Saw II: Flesh & Blood}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw II\n| image = Saw II poster.jpg\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Leigh Whannell]]\n* Darren Lynn Bousman\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]\n* [[Erik Knudsen]]\n* [[Franky G]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]]\n* [[Beverly Mitchell]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n}}\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Lions Gate Films]]\n| released = {{Film date|2005|10|28|United States}}\n| runtime = 93 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 92:40--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-ii-2005 | title=''SAW II'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 21, 2005 | accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = United States<br/>Canada<ref>https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8b62c042</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $4 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web|title=Saw II|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2005/SAW2.php}}</ref> \n| gross = $147.7 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Saw II''''' is a 2005 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] and written by [[Leigh Whannell]] and Bousman. It is the second installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Donnie Wahlberg]], [[Tobin Bell]], [[Shawnee Smith]], [[Erik Knudsen]], [[Franky G]], [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]], [[Glenn Plummer]], [[Beverly Mitchell]], and [[Dina Meyer]].\n\nThe film features [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] being apprehended by the police, but trapping the arresting officer in one of his own games while showing another game of eight people \u2014 including the officer's son \u2014 in progress on TV monitors at another location. It also explores some of John Kramer's backstory, providing a partial explanation of his reason for becoming Jigsaw.\n\nAfter the financial success of 2004's ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', a sequel was immediately green-lit. Leigh Whannell and [[James Wan]] were busy preparing for their next film and were unable to write or direct. Bousman wrote a script called ''The Desperate'' before ''Saw'' was released and was looking for a producer but many studios rejected it. [[Gregg Hoffman]] received the script and showed it to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]]. It was decided that, with some changes, it could be made into ''Saw II''. Whannell became available to provide rewrites of the script. The film was given a larger budget and was shot from May to June 2005 in Toronto.\n\n''Saw II'' was released in the United States on October 28, 2005, by [[Lions Gate Films]]. Despite mixed reviews from critics, the film was a financial success. It opened with $31.9 million and grossed $88 million in the United States and Canada. It has remained the highest grossing ''Saw'' film in those countries. Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2006 MTV Movie Awards]] for his role as Jigsaw in the film. ''Saw II'' was released to [[DVD]] on February 14, 2006, and topped charts its first week, selling more than 3 million units. At the time, it was the fastest-selling theatrical DVD in Lions Gate's history. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw III]]'', was released in 2006.\n\n==Plot==\n{{Long plot|date=July 2019}}\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 to 700 words. -->\nInformant Michael Marks awakens in a room with a spike-filled mask locked around his neck. A videotape informs him that in order to unlock the device, he must cut into his eye to obtain the key. He sets off the timer and finds the scalpel, but cannot bring himself to retrieve the key and is killed after sixty seconds when the mask closes.\n\nAt the scene of Michael's game, Detective Allison Kerry finds a message for her former partner, [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]], and calls him in. Despite not wanting to be involved in the case, Eric reluctantly joins Kerry and Officer Daniel Rigg in leading a [[SWAT]] team to the factory, which produced the lock from Michael's trap. There they find and apprehend John Kramer, the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]], who is weak from cancer. He indicates several computer monitors showing eight people trapped in a house; including his only known survivor [[Amanda Young]], and Eric's estranged son Daniel. The other victims are Xavier, Gus, Jonas, Laura, Addison, and Obi. A nerve agent filling the house will kill them all within two hours, but John assures Eric that if he follows the rules of his own game, by simply talking with John, he will see Daniel again. At Kerry's urging, Eric agrees in order to buy time for the tech team to arrive and trace the video signal.\n\nThe victims are informed by a microcassette recorder that antidotes are hidden throughout the house; one is in the room's safe, and they have the combination with the \"numbers in the back of their mind\". Xavier ignores a warning note and uses the key provided with the cassette on the door, which fires a bullet through the peephole as Gus looks through it, killing him. They search the house for more antidotes after the door opens, but with no success. After discovering a door, the group travel to the basement where Obi, who is revealed to have helped with the abductions, is forced into a crematory oven to obtain two antidotes. He inadvertently activates the trap and is burned to death before the others can save him, destroying the antidotes as well. In another room, Xavier's test is to go into a pit full of needles and retrieve the key to the door in two minutes, but he instead throws Amanda into the pit and forces her to do it. Pressured, she searches through the needle pit until finally retrieving the key, which she gives to Xavier, but he runs out of time to unlock the door containing the antidote. Throughout the game, the victims discuss connections between them and determine that each has been incarcerated before, excluding Daniel.\n\nMeanwhile, John passes the time with both idle and cryptic chat, eventually telling Eric that his survival of a suicide attempt after his diagnosis is the true reason for his games. Then, he destroys several of John's documents and sketches at Kerry's suggestion, but fails to provoke John. As the tech team arrives, John reveals the connection between the victims: Eric has framed all of them for various crimes.\n\nHaving left the others, Xavier returns to the safe room and finds a colored number on the back of Gus' neck. After realizing the answer to the clue, he kills Jonas with a spiked bat for his number after a brief fight and begins hunting the others. Laura succumbs to the nerve agent and dies; after finding the clue revealing Daniel's identity, Addison and Amanda abandon him, but Amanda returns after finding Jonas' body. Addison finds a glass box containing an antidote, but her arms become trapped in the arm holes which are lined with hidden blades. Xavier enters the room, reads Addison\u2019s number, and leaves her to die. Amanda and Daniel find a tunnel in the safe room, which leads to the bathroom from [[Saw (2004 film)|the first film]]. Daniel collapses inside just before Xavier finds them. Amanda notes that he cannot read his own number, so he cuts a piece of the back of his neck off. As he approaches Amanda as an attempt to kill her, Daniel, who feigned his collapse, jumps in the way and slashes his throat with a hacksaw, killing him.\n\nHaving seen Xavier chasing his son, Eric brutally assaults John and forces him to lead him to the house. John's sitting area is revealed to be an elevator, which they use to leave the factory. The tech team tracks the video's source and Rigg leads his team to a house, where they find VCRs playing previously recorded images. As Kerry realizes the game took place \"before\" they found John, the timer expires and a large safe opens, revealing Daniel bound and breathing into an oxygen mask. Eric enters the house alone and eventually locates the bathroom, where he is attacked by a pig-masked figure. He awakens shackled at the ankle to a pipe, and a tape recorder left by Amanda reveals that she is John's accomplice and intends to continue his work after he dies. Amanda suddenly appears in the doorway, and yells \"Game Over\" before sealing the door, leaving Eric to die.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Erik Knudsen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Matthews|Daniel Matthews]]\n* [[Franky G]] as [[List of Saw characters#Xavier Chavez|Xavier]]\n* [[Glenn Plummer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jonas Singer|Jonas]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]] as [[List of Saw characters#Addison Corday|Addison]]\n* [[Beverley Mitchell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Laura Hunter|Laura]]\n* Timothy Burd as [[List of Saw characters#Obi Tate|Obi]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Officer Daniel Rigg]]\n* Noam Jenkins as [[List of Saw characters#Michael Marks|Michael Marks]]\n* Tony Nappo as [[List of Saw characters#Gus Colyard|Gus]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[File:Saw two banned poster.jpg|thumb|left|150px|The original teaser poster showing two bloody severed fingers that was banned by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]].]]\n''Saw II'' was immediately [[Green-light|green-lit]] after ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''{{'}}s successful opening weekend a year earlier.<ref name=\"IGNFeb2005\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/586/586613p1.html |title=IGN Interviews James Wan and Leigh Whannell |last=Otto |first=Jeff |work=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]] |date=February 9, 2005 |accessdate=August 17, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212164031/http://movies.ign.com/articles/586/586613p1.html |archivedate=February 12, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> Producers needed a script for a sequel <ref name=\"FilmMonthly\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/Profiles/Articles/LeighWhannell/LeighWhannell.html \n |title=Leigh Returns to the Saw \n |last=Fischer \n |first=Paul \n |work=Film Monthly \n |date=October 26, 2005 \n |accessdate=August 22, 2011 \n |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617eiopaX \n |archivedate=August 22, 2011 \n |url-status=live \n}}</ref> but [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]], director and writer of ''Saw'', were working on [[Universal Pictures]]'s ''[[Dead Silence]]''. Music video director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] had just completed a script for his first film ''The Desperate'', and was trying to sell it to studios but was getting reactions that the script was very similar to ''Saw''. A German studio eventually approached him with an offer to produce the film for $1 million. Just as they were looking for a cinematographer, the American cinematographer David A. Armstrong, who had worked on ''Saw'', arrived on the scene and suggested showing the script to ''Saw'' producer [[Gregg Hoffman]].<ref name=\"BDDarren2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/155 |title=Saw II: Director Darren Bousman & Writer Leigh Whannell |work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] |publisher=The Collective |year=2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617eli0Lg |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Hoffman read the script and called Bousman wanting to produce ''The Desperate''. After Hoffman showed the script to his partners [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]],<ref name=\"BousmanOfficial\">{{cite web|url=http://www.darrenlynnbousman.com/films-dlb/saw2/ |title=Saw II |publisher=Darren Lynn Bousman Official Site |last=Bousman |first=Darren Lynn |authorlink=Darren Lynn Bousman |year=2010 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AVQapvJ |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> the two decided that ''The Desperate'' was the starting script they needed for ''Saw II'' and two months later, Bousman was flown to [[Toronto]] to direct.<ref name=\"BousmanOfficial\"/>\n\nWhannell polished the script, with input from Wan,<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/> in order to bring it into the ''Saw'' universe,<ref name=\"FilmMonthly\"/> but kept the characters, traps and deaths from ''The Desperate'' script.<ref name=\"BDFeb2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/interview/215 |title=Saw II DVD: Director Darren Lynn Bousman |last=Lamkin |first=Elaine |work=Bloody Disgusting |publisher=The Collective |date=February 2006 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CC6Ly0l |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Bousman said, \"But you could read the script for ''The Desperate'' and watch ''Saw II'', and you would not be able to draw a comparison\".<ref name=\"BDDarren2005\"/>  Wan and Whannell also served as executive producers. All the previous film's crew members returned: editor [[Kevin Greutert]], cinematographer Armstrong, and composer [[Charlie Clouser]].  This was to be Hoffman's last film. He died unexpectedly on December 4, 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2005/dec/15/guardianobituaries.film |title=Obituary: Gregg Hoffman |last=Newman |first=Kim |work=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=December 15, 2005 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61CCxWwLH |archivedate=August 25, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOnly those key cast and crew members who were involved in the film's ending were given the full script; the rest received only the first 88 pages. If a particular page was rewritten, the old page was shredded. Members were also required to sign [[Non-disclosure agreement|confidentiality agreements]] requiring them not to release any plot details.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-3 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #3 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |authorlink=Gregg Hoffman |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |page=3 |date=May 20, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AcxQiJx |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Reportedly, \"four or five\" alternate endings were shot in order to keep the ending a surprise.<ref name=\"SawIINotes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lionsgatepublicity.com/epk/saw2/docs/pro_notes.doc |title=Saw II Production Notes |publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]] |format=1.40MB [[Doc (computing)|.DOC]] file |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61zDPmBZM |archivedate=September 26, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Bousman gave the actors freedom to change dialogue in the script. He said that 95% of the time, the actors went by the script, with about 5% being [[Ad libitum|adlib]]s, which he said \"made all of the difference in the world\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.about.com/od/saw2/a/saw2db021406_3.htm |title=One on One with \"Saw II\" Writer/Director Darren Lynn Bousman |last=Murray |first=Rebecca |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |page=3 |date=February 14, 2006 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AWraMCm |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hoffman said in an interview with ''[[Fangoria]]'' that they listened to fans' suggestions. For instance, instead of only showing the aftermath of a character violently dying in a flashback, they would allow it to unfold as it happened. This was in contrast to ''Saw'', in which most of the violence was implied off-screen.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw II: Building a Better Human Trap|issn=0164-2111|number=248|date=November 2005|page=30}}</ref>\n\n===Filming and post-production===\n''Saw II'' was given a larger production budget of $4 million,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1 |title=Evolution of Scary Movies |last=Rooney |first=Brian |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=October 27, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617rX6x73 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> compared to ''Saw''{{'}}s budget of a little over $1 million.<ref name=\"TorontoStar\">{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> The marketing budget was an additional $2 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117942674 |title=Lionsgate: The hidden enigma |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=May 7, 2006 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62Ra0fOTm |archivedate=October 15, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first shot, which involved shooting police cars and a SWAT van driving around the industrial docklands outside the soundstage,<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/?id=7379 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #1 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=1 |date=May 6, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61Ab1u2jk |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> was filmed on {{nowrap|April 29, 2005}} in Toronto. After two months of pre-production,<ref name=\"BDFeb2006\"/> [[principal photography]] took place over 25 days at Toronto's [[Cinespace Film Studios]] from {{nowrap|May 2, 2005}} to {{nowrap|June 6, 2005}}.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt1\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=Saw II: Building a Better Human Trap|issn=0164-2111|number=248|date=November 2005|page=29}}</ref><ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-5 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #5 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=5 |date=June 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AfJfhNH |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The ending was filmed on May 25 and 26.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-4 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #4 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=4 |date=May 27, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AeGrOI6 |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The music and sound was recorded in July and ''Saw II'' was [[Picture lock|locked]] on {{nowrap|July 16}}. It was completely finished by {{nowrap|September 9}}.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt5\"/> Visual effects were performed by [[C.O.R.E.|C.O.R.E. Digital Pictures]] and post-production services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group|Deluxe]].<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/>\n\n===Trap designs===\n[[David Hackl]], the film's production designer, took three weeks to construct 27 sets on a single sound stage.<ref name=\"SawIINotes\"/> The puppet [[Billy the Puppet|Billy]], used in the series to give instructions to Jigsaw's victims, was originally created by Wan out of paper towel rolls and [[papier-m\u00e2ch\u00e9]]. Given the larger budget for the sequel, Billy was upgraded with remote-controlled eyes and a [[Servomechanism|servo]]-driven mouth.<ref name=\"GreggJoBlopt2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/saw-2-diary-2 |title=Saw 2: Dairy #2 |last=Hoffman |first=Gregg |publisher=JoBlo.com |page=2 |date=May 13, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AcAwHaK |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> In one trap, \"The Needle Room\", Smith's character Amanda is thrown into a pit of needles to find a key. In order for this to be done safely, four people, over a period of four days, removed the needle tips from syringes and replaced them with fiber optic tips. They modified a total of 120,000 fake needles. However, this number was insufficient and the pit had to be filled with styrofoam and other materials to make it appear to have more needles. The needles that were apparently stuck into Smith were actually blunted syringes stuck into padding under her clothing. For certain shots, a fake arm was used.<ref>{{cite video |people=[[David Hackl]] (production designer), Jim Murray (property master), Darren Lynn Bousman (writer/director) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Needle Pit |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Darren Lynn Bousman CC.JPG|thumb|right|''Saw II'' was Bousman's first feature film.]]\nBousman came up with an idea whereby a character's hands would get stuck in some sort of vessel and this resulted in the \"Hand Trap\". It proved to be a challenge but after much discussion, Hackl, property master Jim Murray and art director Michele Brady came up with a suitable design. They arranged a glass box suspended by chains from the ceiling which contained a hypodermic needle with the antidote and which had two hand-holes on the underside. As soon as Vaugier's character Addison put her hands into the holes razor blades would close in on her hands and any attempt to withdraw from the trap would cause her to bleed to death. In order for the trap to be used safely, the prop builders made the handcuffs move inside the box and fake blades that would retract from the actress's hands, thus allowing her to slide her hands out. Hackl subsequently commented that the character did not have to put her hands into the trap as there was a lock with a key on the other side box that would have opened the contraption.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://machinedesign.com/article/how-to-engineer-a-nightmare-1023 |title=How to Engineer a Nightmare |last=Shapiro |first=Jessica |journal=[[Machine Design]] |volume=80 |issue=20 |pages=22\u201323 |date=October 23, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62GdveX3S |archivedate=October 7, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite video |people=David Hackl (production designer) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Hand Trap |medium=DVD |publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe original idea for the \"Furnace Trap\" came from the house having been a [[Crematory|crematorium]] at some point, but this would have involved turning the house into a funeral parlor, so it was instead decided that the furnace would be part of the house's boiler system. The furnace was visualized in the form of a computer model so that Bousman could better understand how shots could be filmed. Using the computer model as a guide, the furnace was constructed in three days using cement board and tin with removable sides and top so Timothy Burd (Obi) could be filmed crawling inside. The furnace produced real flames and, in place of Burd, a stunt man using a fire retardant gel crawled into the fire.<ref>{{cite video |people=David Hackl (production designer) |date=2005 |title=The Traps of Saw II: The Furnace |medium=DVD |publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment |accessdate=August 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Albums -->\n| name         = Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Various Artists\n| cover        =\n| caption      ={{deletable image-caption|Wednesday, 13 November 2019|PROD}}\n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2005|10|25}}\n| recorded     = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Industrial metal]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]|[[alternative metal]]|[[nu metal]]}}\n| length       = {{Duration|m=54|s=46}}\n| label        = [[Image Entertainment]]\n| producer     = {{hlist|[[Mark Burg]] <small>([[Executive producer|{{abbr|exec.|executive producer}}]])</small>|[[Gregg Hoffman]] <small>(exec.)</small>|[[Oren Koules]] <small>(exec.)</small>|Jonathan Platt|Jonathan Scott Miller|Martin Shore|Stu Song}}\n| prev_title   = [[Saw (soundtrack)|Saw: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year    = 2004\n| next_title   = [[Saw III (soundtrack)|Saw III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year    = 2006\n| misc         = \n}}\nThe ''Saw II'' soundtrack was released on October 25, 2005 by [[RLJE Films|Image Entertainment]].<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> The video for \"[[Forget to Remember]]\" was also directed by Bousman.<ref>{{cite video|title=Saw II Commentary|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]]|people=Darren Lynn Bousman, Donnie Wahlberg and Beverly Mitchell|date=2006 | accessdate=August 26, 2011|time=1:29:11\u2013 1:29:13}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| extra_column = Artist\n| title1 = Irresponsible Hate Anthem (Venus Head Trap Mix)\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Scott Putesky|Daisy Berkowitz]]|[[Madonna Wayne Gacy]]|[[Marilyn Manson]]|[[Twiggy Ramirez]]}}\n| extra1 = [[Marilyn Manson]]\n| length1 = 3:39\n| title2 = Sound Effects and Overdramatics\n| writer2 = {{hlist|[[Quinn Allman]]|[[The Used|Jeph Howard]]|[[Bert McCracken]]|[[Branden Steineckert]]}}\n| extra2 = [[The Used]]\n| length2 = 3:28\n| title3 = [[Forget to Remember]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|[[Chad Gray]]|[[Ryan Martinie]]|[[Matthew McDonough]]|[[Greg Tribbett]]}}\n| extra3 = [[Mudvayne]]\n| length3 = 3:33\n| title4 = September\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Chris Hamilton|Mike Kennedy|Nick Rowe|[[Hellyeah|Kyle Sanders]]|Tim Williams}}\n| extra4 = [[Bloodsimple]]\n| length4 = 3:38\n| title5 = Blood (Empty Promises)\n| writer5 = {{hlist|[[Papa Roach|Dave Buckner]]|[[Papa Roach|Tobin Esperance]]|[[Jerry Horton]]|[[Jacoby Shaddix]]}}\n| extra5 = [[Papa Roach]]\n| length5 = 2:56\n| title6 = REV 22:20 (REV 4:20 Mix)\n| writer6 = {{hlist|[[Maynard James Keenan]]|[[Danny Lohner]]}}\n| extra6 = [[Puscifer]]\n| length6 = 4:47\n| title7 = [[Next (Sevendust album)|Pieces]]\n| writer7 = [[Sevendust]]\n| extra7 = [[Sevendust]]\n| length7 = 3:06\n| title8 = Rodent (Ken \"Hiwatt\" Marshall/DDT Mix)\n| writer8 = {{hlist|[[Al Jourgensen]]|[[Skinny Puppy]]}}\n| extra8 = [[Skinny Puppy]]\n| length8 = 5:00\n| title9 = [[Burn the Witch (Queens of the Stone Age song)|Burn the Witch]] ([[Unkle|UNKLE]] Variation)\n| writer9 = {{hlist|[[Joey Castillo]]|[[Josh Homme]]|[[Troy Van Leeuwen]]}}\n| extra9 = [[Queens of the Stone Age]]\n| length9 = 3:04\n| title10 = Holy\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Shaun Bivens|Tony Providence|Allen Richardson}}\n| extra10 = [[A Band Called Pain]]\n| length10 = 3:43\n| title11 = [[Enter the Chicken#Three Fingers|Three Fingers]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Buckethead|[[Dan Monti]]|[[Saul Williams]]}}\n| extra11 = [[Buckethead|Buckethead and Friends]] & [[Saul Williams]]\n| length11 = 3:00\n| title12 = Home Invasion Robbery\n| writer12 = [[The Legion of Doom (mash up group)|The Legion of Doom]]\n| extra12 = [[The Legion of Doom (mash up group)|The Legion of Doom]]\n| length12 = 4:10\n| title13 = Caliente (Dark Entries)\n| writer13 = {{hlist|[[Daniel Ash]]|[[Kevin Haskins]]|[[David J]]|[[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]]}}\n| extra13 = [[Revolting Cocks]], [[Gibby Haynes]] & [[Al Jourgensen]]\n| length13 = 4:28\n| title14 = Step Up\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Andrew Gerold|[[Jim Kaufman]]|[[John Travis (producer)|John Travis]]|[[Ron Underwood (musician)|Ron Underwood]]}}\n| extra14 = [[Opiate for the Masses]]\n| length14 = 3:24\n| title15 = Don't Forget the Rules\n| writer15 = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| extra15 = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| length15 = 5:00\n| total_length = 54:46\n}}\n\n==Release==\n''Saw II'' was released in New Zealand, the United States, and the United Kingdom on {{nowrap|October 28, 2005}}; and {{nowrap|November 17, 2005}} in Australia. The original teaser poster showing two bloody, severed fingers, representing the Roman numeral, II, was rejected by the [[Motion Picture Association of America]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2005/08/22/saw-ii-sees-ads-yanked |title=Saw II Sees Ads Yanked |last=David |first=Erik |work=[[Moviefone]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=August 22, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AZlBCgp |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since the poster was already released and managed to \"slip by\" the MPAA, they issued a release stating the poster was not approved and was unacceptable; [[Lions Gate Films]] removed the poster from their websites.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/index.php?id=8380 |title=Saw 2 Poster Banned |publisher=[[JoBlo.com]] |accessdate=August 22, 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617es9xD4 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The image was used instead for the film's soundtrack cover.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/saw-2-r794014|title=Saw 2 - Original Soundtrack|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Guide]]|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> Lionsgate held the second annual \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[Red Cross]] and collected 10,154 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD |title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive |publisher=[[Red Cross]] |date=August 6, 2007 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61eiTSBkv |archivedate=September 13, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593 |title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=September 12, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61edOe9qM |archivedate=September 12, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Saw II'' was released on [[DVD]], [[VHS]], and [[Universal Media Disc]] on February 14, 2006 through [[Lions Gate Home Entertainment]]. The DVD debuted as number one selling 2.5 million units in its first day. It went on to sell 3.9 million units its first week, becoming the fastest selling theatrical DVD in Lions Gate's history.<ref name=\"CNWGroup2\">{{cite news|title=Jigsaw Is Back With a Vengeance as Lionsgate's SAW II Has Teeth in Debut on Home Entertainment Charts |agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=February 22, 2006}}</ref>\n\nOn October 24, 2006, an Unrated Special Edition was released, while an Unrated [[Blu-ray]] edition was also released with various special features on January 23, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bluray.highdefdigest.com/561/sawii.html |title=Saw II (Bluray) |publisher=High-Def Digest |date=January 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fB0GAE |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://homevideo.about.com/od/horror/p/saw2dvdsawiidvd.htm |title=Saw II DVD Unrated Special Edition Release Date |publisher=[[About.com]] |date=October 24, 2006 |accessdate=August 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fJr7Sk |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw II'' opened with $31.7 million on 3,879 screens across 2,949 theaters.<ref name=\"BOMWeekend\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1930&p=.htm |title='Saw II' Gores 'Zorro' on Halloween Weekend |last=Gray |first=Brandon |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |date=October 31, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AgXubSc |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The three-day [[Halloween]] opening weekend set a Lions Gate record. It became at the time, the widest release for Lionsgate and one of the best opening weekends for a horror sequel.<ref name=\"CNWGroup\">{{cite news|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures Announce SAW III for Halloween 2006|agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=March 3, 2006}}</ref> For its second weekend it fell 47% making $16.9 million.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1935&p=.htm |title=Welcome to the Cluck: 'Chicken Little,' 'Jarhead' Top Weekend |last=Gray |first=Brandon |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 7, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AiStFVm |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film was closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|January 5, 2006}} after 70 days of release.\n\n''Saw II'' opened in the United Kingdom with $3.8 million on 305 screens, 70% larger than the first instalment. It opened in Japan on 67 screens with $750,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1932&p=.htm |title=Around the World Roundup: 'Zorro' Leaves Modest Mark in Mass Foreign Bow |last=Bresnan |first=Conor |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 1, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AhvJadN |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Opening to $1.3 million on 173 screens it was the number one film in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=1948&p=.htm |title=Around the World Roundup: 'Harry Potter' on Fire in Foreign Bow |last=Bresnan |first=Conor |work=Box Office Mojo |date=November 24, 2005 |accessdate=August 24, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61AisQFwc |archivedate=August 24, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> The film grossed $87 million in the United States and Canada and $60.7 million in other markets for a worldwide total of $147.7 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2.htm|title=Saw II (2005)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> The film is the 2nd highest-grossing film of the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' series]], only behind ''Saw III'' and Lionsgate's fourth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref> According to [[CinemaScore]] polls, 53% of the audience were males under 25 years of age. The poll also indicated that 65% of the audience were familiar with the first film.<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1001393198 |title='Saw II' cuts through b.o. with $31.7 mil debut |last=Fuson |first=Brian |work=[[Backstage (magazine)|Backstage]] |date=November 1, 2005 |accessdate=August 23, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/619CK762U |archivedate=August 23, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Release date'''<br />(United States)\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n! colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''United States/Canada'''\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Other markets'''\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 28, 2005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| $4,000,000\n|$87,039,965\n|$60,708,540\n|$147,748,505\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film received generally mixed reviews from critics, who praised the acting, particularly the performances of Bell and Wahlberg, while criticizing the gruesome nature of the story. Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 37% of 122 critics have given the film a positive review, with a rating average of 4.59/10. The site's consensus was, \"Saw II is likely to please the gore-happy fans of the original, though it may be too gruesome for those not familiar with first film's premise.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/| title=Saw II (2005)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = March 20, 2020}}</ref> Metacritic, which assigns a weighted average score out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, gives the film a score of 40 based on 28 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews| title= Saw II Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = August 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRobert Koehler of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' gave the film a negative review, saying \"cooking up new Rube Goldberg torture contraptions isn't enough to get ''Saw II'' out of the shadow of its unnerving predecessor\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117928622?categoryid=31&cs=1 |title=Saw II Review |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] |accessdate=October 20, 2005 |first=Robert |last=Koehler |date=October 20, 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617fegEfp |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Gregory Kirschling of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a B minus, saying \"''Saw II'' is just barely a better [[B movie|B flick]] than ''Saw''\" and that both films are \"more clever and revolting than they are actually chilling\". He praised Bell's performance as Jigsaw, saying \"As the droopy-lidded maniac in the flesh, Tobin Bell is, for all the film's gewgaws, ''Saw II''{{'s}} sturdiest horror, a [[Terence Stamp]] look-alike who calls to mind a seedy [[General Zod]] lazily overseeing the universe from his evildoer's lair\".  He ended his review: \"Where ''Saw II'' lags behind in Saw's novelty, it takes the lead with its smoother landing, which is again primed to blow the movie wide open, but manages a more compelling job of it than the original's cheat finish\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1123047,00.html |title=Movie Review Saw II (2005) |last=Kirschling |first=Gregory |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=October 26, 2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617hi5y12 |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nKevin Crust of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, calling ''Saw II'' a \"worthy follow-up to its grisly predecessor\". He said the story was \"much more focused on an endgame than the original film. There are fewer credibility gaps and there are plenty of reversals to satisfy fans\". He criticized the use of numerous flashbacks, saying that it \"rob[s] us of the pleasure of actually remembering for ourselves\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/oct/28/entertainment/et-saw28 |title=Grisly 'Saw II' makes the cut |last=Crust |first=Kevin |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=[[Tribune Company]] |date=October 29, 2005 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617jXtG4P |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Laura Kern, writing for ''[[The New York Times]]'', gave it a mixed review, saying that Bousman \"delivers similar hard-core, practically humorless frights and hair-raising tension, but only after getting past a shaky beginning that plays more like a forensics-themed television show than a scary movie\" and called Greutert's editing \"crafty\". She called the sequel \"more trick than treat\" and that it \"doesn't really compare to its fine predecessor - though it still manages to be eye-opening (and sometimes positively nauseating) in itself\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/2005/10/28/movies/28saw.html |title=Round 2 in a House of Horror |last=Kern |first=Laura |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 28, 2011 |accessdate=August 25, 2011 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120714032226/http://movies.nytimes.com/2005/10/28/movies/28saw.html |archivedate=July 14, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>  ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Kim Newman]] gave the film three out of five stars. He said that the film improves upon ''Saw''{{'s}} \"perverse fascination with ''[[Seven (1995 film)|Seven]]''-style murders and brutally violent puzzles\" and that Jigsaw's intellectual games make \"[[Hannibal Lecter]] look like the compiler of ''The Sun''{{'}}s quick crossword\". He ended his reviews saying, \"Morally dubious it may be, but this gory melange of torture, terror and darkly humorous depravity appeals to the sick puppy within us all\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/reviewcomplete.asp?FID=132340 |title=Saw II Movie Review |last=Newman |first=Kim |authorlink=Kim Newman |work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]] |publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]] |date=October 2005 |accessdate=September 19, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61oExb0Km |archivedate=September 19, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nTobin Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2006 MTV Movie Awards]] for his role as Jigsaw,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wedding_crashers/news/1646716/get_your_goofy_mtv_movie_awards_noms_right_here |title=Get Your Goofy MTV Movie Awards Noms Right Here |last=Weinberg |first=Scott |work=Rotten Tomatoes |publisher=Flixster |date=April 26, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208110313/http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/wedding_crashers/news/1646716/get_your_goofy_mtv_movie_awards_noms_right_here |archivedate=December 8, 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> though the award went to [[Hayden Christensen]] for his role as [[Darth Vader]] in ''[[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2006/ |title=2006 Movie Awards Summary |publisher=[[MTV.com]] |date=June 8, 2006 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/617g11whd |archivedate=August 22, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Recipient(s)\n! Result\n|-\n| [[Directors Guild of Canada]]\n| Outstanding Sound Editing - Feature Film\n| Rob Bertola; Tom Bjelic; Allan Fung; Mark Gingras; John Laing; Paul Shikata; [[John Douglas Smith]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Fangoria Chainsaw Awards\n| Best Villain\n| [[Tobin Bell]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[MTV Movie & TV Awards|MTV Movie Acards]]\n| Best Villain\n| [[Tobin Bell]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best DVD or Blu-ray Special Edition Release|Best DVD Special Edition Release]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|[[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie: Scream\n| [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Thriller\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u2014\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb title|0432348}}\n*{{metacritic film|saw-ii|Saw II}}\n*{{mojo title|saw2|Saw II}}\n*{{rotten-tomatoes|saw_ii|Saw II}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 2}}\n[[Category:Saw films|2]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2005 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s psychological horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:2005 directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:7ef6:9800:c5b7:fd1f:d7c:7635", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_II"}
{"title_page": "Saw III", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw III\n| image = Saw3 cape10.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Leigh Whannell\n* [[James Wan]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n}}<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Saw III (2006)|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64013?sid=b6cc7440-eb1a-4fa9-8195-afc4b79376e0&sr=3.873525&cp=1&pos=0|website=American Film Institute Catalog|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Koehler|first1=Robert|title=Saw III - Review|website=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/saw-iii-1200512355/|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 3, 2017|date=October 28, 2006}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|2006|10|27|United States}}\n| runtime = 108 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 108:08--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-iii-2006-0 | title=''Saw III'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 11, 2006 | accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| country = Canada<ref name=\"bfi\"/><br>United States<ref name=\"bfi\">{{cite web|title=Saw III (2006)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8beb2d8e|website=British Film Institute|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $10 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web|title=Saw III|website=The Numbers| url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/SAW3.php}}</ref> \n| gross = $164.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Saw III''''' is a 2006 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] from a screenplay by [[Leigh Whannell]] and a story by Whannell and [[James Wan]]. It is the third installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Tobin Bell]], [[Shawnee Smith]], [[Angus Macfadyen]], [[Bahar Soomekh]], [[Dina Meyer]], [[Donnie Wahlberg]], and Whannell.\n\nThe story follows [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff]], a man who, after his son is killed by a drunk driver, is put through a series of tests by [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] in order to try to get him to let go of his vengeance for the man that killed his son. Meanwhile, a bed-ridden John Kramer has his apprentice [[Amanda Young]] kidnap [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Dr. Lynn Denlon]], who is tasked with keeping John alive for one final test before he dies.\n\nDevelopment began right after the successful opening weekend of ''[[Saw II]]''. Filming took place in [[Toronto]] from May to June 2006. Whannell aimed to make the story more emotional than previous installments, particularly with the Amanda and Jigsaw storyline. The film is dedicated to producer [[Gregg Hoffman]] who died on December 4, 2005.\n\n''Saw III'' was released in the United States on {{nowrap|October 27, 2006}}, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. It was a financial success, opening to $33.6 million and grossing $80.2 million in the United States and Canada. It is the highest-grossing film of the series in the international market with $84.6 million and the highest-grossing film in the series overall with $164.9 million worldwide. It received mixed to negative reviews from critics. Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2007 MTV Movie Awards]] and the film received nominations for a [[Saturn Award]] as \"Best Horror Film\". The film was released to [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on {{nowrap|January 23, 2007}}, and topped the charts selling 2.5 million units in its first week. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw IV]]'', was released in 2007.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Saw II|After being left in the bathroom to die]], [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]] breaks his foot with a toilet lid to escape his shackle. Six months later, the aftermath of a Jigsaw \"game\" is discovered by a [[SWAT]] team. The victim, Troy, had to rip chains from his body in order to escape from a bomb. Detective Allison Kerry arrives at the scene, and points out that the room's exit was welded shut, breaking [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]]'s [[modus operandi]] of giving his victims a chance to survive. While reviewing the videotape, she is abducted and awakens in a harness hooked into her ribs. Even though she retrieves the key from a beaker of acid and unlocks the harness, she is unable to remove it and is killed when time runs out.\n\nDr. Lynn Denlon is abducted from the hospital she works at, and brought to the bedridden John Kramer. His apprentice, Amanda Young, locks a shotgun collar around Lynn's neck that is connected to John's heart rate monitor, and will detonate if John dies or Lynn moves out of range. She is instructed by Amanda to keep him alive until another victim has completed his game. The other victim, Jeff, wakes up in a box and learns that he must undergo tests, which will lead him to the man who killed his son, Dylan, in a drunk driving accident. Jeff became unstable and vengeful as a result and now neglects his daughter, Corbett.\n\nJeff's first test leads him into a meat freezer. He finds Danica Scott, the only witness to the accident, who refused to testify in court; she is stripped naked and chained at the wrists between two poles, which begin spraying her with ice-cold water. Jeff attempts to reach the key, which is behind frozen bars after Danica persuades Jeff to help her, but she freezes to death before he can retrieve it.\n\nIn his next test, Judge Halden, who gave Dylan's killer six months in jail, is chained at the neck to the bottom of a pit. Rotted pig corpses are dropped into a rack of circular saws, slowly filling the vat, but Halden persuades Jeff to help him. Jeff sets fire to a furnace full of Dylan's toys in order to retrieve the key, and saves Halden before he drowns.\n\nHis third test involves Timothy Young, Dylan's killer, who is strapped to a machine called \"The Rack\" that will twist his limbs and neck until they break. The key is tied to the trigger of an enclosed shotgun. The shotgun goes off, after Jeff retrieves the key, killing Halden in the process. Jeff tries to stop the machine before Timothy's neck breaks, but fails.\n\nMeanwhile, Lynn is forced to perform an improvised surgery to relieve pressure on John's brain with a conventional drill. Amanda grows increasingly jealous of Lynn's interaction with John, who continues to reprimand her for being rude. It is only when John suffers a seizure that Amanda is willing to cooperate with Lynn. During the surgery, John hallucinates about [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|another woman]] and declares his love out loud. This upsets Amanda and when she leaves, she finds a letter which drives her to hysterics. Amanda returns with the news that Jeff has completed his tests, but refuses to remove Lynn's collar. She reveals that she no longer believes in John's philosophy, and has been creating inescapable traps. She also reveals that she fought with Detective Matthews after he escaped the bathroom, and left him for dead.\n\nRefusing to listen to John's warnings, Amanda shoots Lynn just as Jeff arrives. Jeff, who is revealed to be Lynn's husband, retaliates by shooting Amanda with a gun provided by John after his tests. As Amanda dies, John reveals that Lynn's test was actually hers: aware of her modus operandi, and unwilling to allow a murderer to continue his legacy, John decided to test her. John then addresses Jeff, offering to call an ambulance for Lynn if he accepts one last test: he can choose to kill John or forgive him. Jeff tells John he forgives him, but slashes his throat with a power saw. The door to the room seals as John plays a final tape, which tells Jeff that he has failed his final test by killing John, the only person who knows the whereabouts of his daughter. The tape ends as John dies, and Lynn's collar detonates, killing her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff Denlon]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Lynn Denlon]]\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* [[Leigh Whannell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Stanheight|Adam Stanheight]]\n* [[Mpho Koaho]] as [[List of Saw characters#Timothy Young|Timothy Young]]\n* [[Barry Flatman]] as [[List of Saw characters#Judge Halden|Judge Halden]]\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Lieutenant Daniel Rigg]]\n* [[J. Larose]] as [[List of Saw characters#Troy|Troy]]\n* Debra Lynne McCabe as [[List of Saw characters#Danica Scott|Danica Scott]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* Stefan Georgiou as [[List of Saw characters#Dylan Denlon|Dylan]]\n* [[Niamh Wilson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Corbett Denlon|Corbett]]\n* [[Alan van Sprang]] as Chris\n* Kim Roberts as Nurse Deborah\n* [[Franky G]] as [[List of Saw characters#Xavier Chavez|Xavier Chavez]]\n* Tim Burd as [[List of Saw characters#Obi Tate|Obi Tate]]\n* Oren Koules as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[Darren Lynn Bousman]], director and co-writer of ''[[Saw II]]'', [[James Wan]], director of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', and [[Leigh Whannell]], screenwriter on both, turned down the offer to make a third film in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]]. ''Saw II'' producer [[Gregg Hoffman]] died a few weeks after its release. Bousman, Wan and Whannell got together to have lunch the day they heard of Hoffman's passing and decided to make ''Saw III'' in dedication to Hoffman.<ref name=\"ComingSoonBousman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=17120|title=Exclusive: Saw III's Darren Lynn Bousman|last=Douglas|first=Edward|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=October 24, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013214127/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=17120|archivedate=October 13, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Whannell aimed to make ''Saw III'' more emotional, describing the plot as essentially a father-daughter \"love story\" between Jigsaw and Amanda.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/interview-bousman-whannell|title=Interview Bousman & Whannell|publisher=[[Joblo.com]]|last=Topel|first=Fred|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023170149/http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/interview-bousman-whannell|archivedate=October 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n[[File:James Wan and Leigh Whannell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|left|Wan (left) and Whannell (right) returned to write ''Saw III'' and also served as executive producers.]]\nBousman said they did not intend to have a twist ending, as distinctly as the previous films,  noting that \"I think most people will figure it out in the first 15 minutes of the film\". Whannell added, \"What Darren and I struck for ''Saw III'' was to have an emotionally impactful ending.\" As with the previous two films, the ending was only given to the actors who appeared in the final scene at the time it was filmed. At one point the script was stolen from Bousman's chair; however, it was returned before it was leaked online.<ref name=\"Lionsgate Home Entertainment\">{{cite video|title=The Details of Death: The Props of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]]|people=[[David Hackl]] (production designer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=4:15\u20134:23}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nSoomekh became close with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] after appearing in their film ''[[Crash (2004 film)|Crash]]'' (2004) and they wanted her in their next big film. Not a fan of horror films she found the role challenging. \"I had nightmares the first month I was on set\", she said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/742/742130p1.html|title=Interview: Bahar Soomekh and Angus Macfadyen|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|page=1|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929191934/http://movies.ign.com/articles/742/742130p1.html|archivedate=September 29, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n''Saw III'' was given a larger budget of $10 million,<ref>{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> compared to ''Saw II''{{'}}s $4 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1|title=Evolution of Scary Movies|last=Rooney|first=Brian|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=August 22, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917163419/http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1|archivedate=September 17, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] took place for 27 days<ref name=\"ComingSoonBousman\"/> at [[Toronto]]'s [[Cinespace Film Studios]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=SAW III: Deadlier Lessons|issn=0164-2111|number=257|date=October 2006|pages=30}}</ref> from {{nowrap|May 8, 2006}}, to late June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lionsgate-and-twisted-pictures-rip-into-saw-iii-as-latest-film-in-powerhouse-horror-franchise-starts-principal-photography-in-toronto-56092217.html|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures Rip Into SAW III as Latest Film in Powerhouse Horror Franchise Starts Principal Photography in Toronto|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|date=May 6, 2006|accessdate=August 19, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015063416/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lionsgate-and-twisted-pictures-rip-into-saw-iii-as-latest-film-in-powerhouse-horror-franchise-starts-principal-photography-in-toronto-56092217.html|archivedate=October 15, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>   Production borrowed the bathroom set used in ''[[Scary Movie 4]]'', which parodied the franchise.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\"/>  Almost all the transitions from one place to another were not made using digital effects; the transitions were shot on the spot. For example, when the camera moves from Troy's crime scene to Kerry being in the bathtub, Meyer had to run, take off all her clothes, and jump into the tub.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\"/> Visually the film is akin to the previous two with using quick cuts and fast-paced rhythms. Bousman said, \"We're using a lot of [[whip pan]]s and [[wiktionary:flash frame|flash frames]] to create a dynamic feel\". [[Post-production]] services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group Inc.|Deluxe]].<ref name=\"ProdNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/saw3/notes.pdf|title=Saw III Production Notes|publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517062303/http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/saw3/notes.pdf|archivedate=May 17, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Trap designs===\nBousman described the hardest scene to film was the \"Pig Scene\", explaining that they had to rush and it involved filming \"so many moving parts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-saw-iiis-director-darren-lynn-bousman|title=EXCLUSIVE: Saw III's Director Darren Lynn Bousman|publisher=MovieWeb|date=October 26, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001060509/http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-saw-iiis-director-darren-lynn-bousman|archivedate=October 1, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The pig carcasses were made out of foam, rubber, and latex.<ref name=\"Lionsgate Home Entertainment\"/> The pig props had live, disinfected [[maggot]]s attached with honey.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Details of Death: The Props of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=David Hackl (production designer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=6:40\u20137:35}}</ref>\n\nFor \"The Rack Trap\", Whannell originally conceived it as a trap that would fold a person into a box, though it eventually morphed into the twisting of body parts.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Leigh Whannell (writer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=1:27\u20131:51}}</ref> Bousman wanted to have a trap that involved freezing someone to death since the films had already covered burning to death, bleeding to death, and being cut to death. A body cast was made of Debra Lynn McCabe for \"The Freezer Room\" trap, but, because of safety regulations a person cannot be entombed, only a front or back body cast could be on the actress at any given time.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Darren Lynn Bousman (director), Leigh Whannell (writer), Debra Lynn McCabe (actor)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=4:50\u20135:40}}</ref> For the \"Classroom Trap\", J. Larose's character was originally going to be hanged from the ceiling by meat hooks, but it was decided against since he would not have been able to rip the chains out himself (as the script called for). It proved to be a challenge since it was done with [[Prosthetic makeup|prosthetics]] and [[practical effect]]s.<ref name=\"ProdNotes\"/><ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Darren Lynn Bousman (director), Leigh Whannell play  adam   |date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=6:23\u20136:59}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Saw III'' was released domestically and in the United Kingdom on {{nowrap|October 27, 2006}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Saw-III#tab=summary|title=Saw III (2006)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=saw3.htm|title=Saw III (2006) International Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> It was released in Australia on {{nowrap|November 2, 2006}}, and on {{nowrap|January 4, 2007}}, in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=saw3.htm|title=Saw III (2006) International Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> According to executive producer Daniel Heffner, the film was toned down seven times to obtain the [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|\"R\" rating]]. According to Bousman, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA) ratings board was less concerned with the film's graphic violence than it was with emotional torture, citing television shows like ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' for expanding the scope of what is acceptable.<ref name=\"JobloDarren\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-darren-bousman|title=Interview: Darren Bousman|work=[[Joblo.com]]|date=June 19, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023170429/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-darren-bousman|archivedate=October 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In Japan, ''Saw III'' received a [[Eirin|R18+ rating]] while the previous two films received an R15+ rating.<ref name=\"DarrenBD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7411|title=SAW III: The Darren Lynn Bousman Blog Only on B-D!|last=Bousman|first=Darren Lynn|authorlink=Darren Lynn Bousman|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=October 11, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002753/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7411|archivedate=February 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> At screenings in the United Kingdom, five people were reported to have fainted at separate cinemas with three at one cinema, resulting in ambulances being called.<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web | work=[[BBC News]] | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6101704.stm | title=Film fans faint at Saw III show | accessdate=October 21, 2006 | date=October 31, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407023257/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6101704.stm | archivedate=April 7, 2012 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe opening scene of Troy's trap was shown at [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic-Con International]] on July 21, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/720/720081p1.html|title=Comic-Con 2006: Saw III Cuts Loose|work=IGN|publisher=News Corperotion|date=July 21, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202033315/http://movies.ign.com/articles/720/720081p1.html|archivedate=February 2, 2008|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The same clip was planned to be shown before the opening of ''[[Crank (film)|Crank]]'' in theaters on {{nowrap|September 1, 2006}}. However, the MPAA would not allow it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20061012saw3|title=Banned SAW 3 clip Revealed|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=October 12, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110913054621/http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20061012saw3|archivedate=September 13, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  On {{nowrap|October 10, 2006}}, Bell, Smith and Bousman appeared at [[Paramount Network|Spike TV]]'s Scream Awards to promote the film and the clip of Troy's trap was shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/story/scream-for-spike-tvs-awards|title=Scream For Spike TV's Awards|last=Condit|first=Jon|work=DreadCentral|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=September 29, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021140056/http://www.dreadcentral.com/story/scream-for-spike-tvs-awards|archivedate=October 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Lionsgate]]'s president of theatrical marketing [[Tim Palen]] thought of the idea to make 1,000 posters with a small amount of Bell's blood, which was mixed with the printing ink. He said, \"I asked if it would be possible to use actual blood. There was silence. He said, 'We could try, but are you serious?' I said I was dead serious.\" The posters were sold for $20, with the first being auctioned off; all the proceeds from the auctioned poster were donated to the [[Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593|title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=October 9, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109034821/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593|archivedate=November 9, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Lionsgate also held the third annual \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the Red Cross and collected 23,493 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive|publisher=[[Red Cross]]|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106140610/http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|archivedate=November 6, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Main|Saw III (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack was released on {{nowrap|October 24, 2006}}. James Christopher Monger of [[AllMusic]] gave the soundtrack three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r930325|title=Saw 3 Original Soundtrack|last=Monger|first=James Christopher|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> Ed Thompson of [[IGN|IGN Music]] gave it a 7.2 out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/742/742276p1.html|title=An album teeming with solid cuts|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320174515/http://music.ign.com/articles/742/742276p1.html|archivedate=March 20, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n \n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 24, 2006\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 72:01\n| label      = Artists Addiction\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Saw II (soundtrack)|Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Saw IV (soundtrack)|Saw IV: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  