 title14 = The Wolf Is Loose\n| writer14 = [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]]\n| extra14 = Mastodon\n| length14 = 3:34\n\n| title15 = Killer Inside\n| writer15 = Hydrovibe\n| extra15 = Hydrovibe Featuring [[Shawnee Smith]]\n| length15 = 3:17\n\n| title16 = Sakkara\n| writer16 = Hourcast  \n| extra16 = Hourcast \n| length16 = 3:45\n\n| title17 = Shed\n| writer17 = [[Fredrik Thordendal]]<br />[[Shagrath]]<br />[[Galder]]\n| extra17 = [[Meshuggah]]\n| length17 = 3:35\n\n| title18 = Effigy\n| writer18 = [[The SmashUp]]\n| extra18 = The SmashUp\n| length18 = 4:36\n\n| title19 = Siesta Loca\n| writer19 =[[Ghost Machine]] \n| extra19 = Ghost Machine\n| length19 = 3:50\n\n| title20 = Sh*! hole Theme\n| writer20 = [[Charlie Clouser]] \n| extra20 =  Clouser\n| length20 = 3:15\n}}\n\n===Home media===\n''Saw III'' was released to [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] through [[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] on {{nowrap|January 23, 2007}}. It topped the home video charts in the United States and Canada with 1.6 million units sold its first day and finished the week with 2.5 million units sold.<ref name=\"DVDSales\">{{cite news|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures' SAW III 'Three-Peats' at Number One on DVD Charts While Also Claiming Most Successful Week One Blu-Ray Debut to Date|agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=February 1, 2007}}</ref> The \"Unrated DVD\" was also released that day and features a 113-minute cut of the film that includes more gore.<ref name=\"DVDSales\"/> A 120-minute-long [[Director's cut]] was released on {{nowrap|October 23, 2007}}, to coincide with the theatrical release of ''[[Saw IV]]'' on {{nowrap|October 26}}. It also included an [[alternate ending]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/9589|title=Uber-Bloody 'Saw III: Director's Cut' This October, Box Set!|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010080309/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/9589|archivedate=October 10, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The director's cut was released on Blu-ray in Region B on October 7, 2008, in France only.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Saw-III-Blu-ray/dp/B001EY0LDM|title=Saw 3 [Blu-ray] [Director's Cut Extreme]|accessdate=December 16, 2017|agency=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]}}</ref>\n\n===Deleted scenes===\nThe original cut of the film ran for slightly over two hours, and several scenes were cut out, including a scene which depicted an extended scene of Kerry and Rigg examining Troy's trap, where Kerry reveals to Rigg she has had nightmares about Eric, and she blames herself for what happened to him.<ref>{{cite video|title=Deleted Scenes|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment| accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Adam had more scenes in the original cut.<ref name=\"IGNDarren\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/741/741449p2.html|title=IGN: Interview: Darren Lynn Bousman|accessdate=October 26, 2007|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=October 26, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001015851/http://movies.ign.com/articles/741/741449p2.html|archivedate=October 1, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A scene that showed Jigsaw regretting his actions was also cut. Bell said, \"I'm glad they cut that scene. This guy knows exactly what he's doing. Does he start off with a model, then refine it? Yeah, he probably does. But there are certain things that are interesting and advance the story, and there are other things that are basically sort of backstory, and you don't really need to know\".<ref name=\"TobinBellAVClub\">{{cite web|title=Tobin Bell Random Roles|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/tobin-bell,2513/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|last=Heisler|first=Steve|date=October 29, 2008|accessdate=October 17, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118125625/http://www.avclub.com/articles/tobin-bell,2513/|archivedate=January 18, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw III'' opened at number one on 4,700 screens at 3,167 theaters grossing $33.6 million from its opening weekend, a two percent increase from ''Saw II''{{'s}} $31.7 million. It held the biggest [[Halloween]] weekend debut for five years until it was beaten in 2011 by ''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]'' ($34 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/pop2it/2011/10/puss-in-boots-sets-halloween-box-office-record-for-now.html|title='Puss in Boots' sets Halloween box-office record (for now)|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=[[Zap2it]]|date=October 30, 2011|accessdate=October 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031170710/http://blog.zap2it.com/pop2it/2011/10/puss-in-boots-sets-halloween-box-office-record-for-now.html|archivedate=October 31, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  It was also Lionsgate's highest-opening weekend. Lionsgate's exit polling indicated that 69 percent of the audience was under 25 years old and 51 percent was male.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2191&p=.htm|title='Saw' Sharp in Third Outing|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011}}</ref>  In its second weekend it placed number four, dropping down 56% to $14.8 million, compared to ''Saw II''{{'s}} second weekend drop of 47% to $16.9 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2194&p=.htm|title='Borat' Bombards the Top Spot|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 6, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011}}</ref> The film was closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|December 14, 2006}}, after 49 days of release.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw3.htm |title= Saw III (2006) | work=Box Office Mojo| accessdate=October 29, 2006}}</ref>\n\n''Saw III'' opened at number five in the international market with an estimated $6 million. It opened at number one in the [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] to $4.7 million. In [[Cinema of Taiwan|Taiwan]] it placed third and opened to $320,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2192&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Prada' Still in Vogue|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> For its second weekend it opened to number two with an estimated $9.7 million. In [[Cinema of Spain|Spain]] it made $3.1 million, an improvement over the previous films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2199&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Borat' Doesn't Budge|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 13, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> For its third weekend, ''Saw III'' grossed $8 million, including [[Cinema of Japan|Japan]]'s opening on 86 screens with $1.1 million. [[Cinema of Australia|Australia]] made $4.3 million, Spain grossed $3.8 million and [[Cinema of Brazil|Brazil]] made $3.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2204&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Casino' Cashes In|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 20, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> In its fourth weekend it placed fourth place with an estimated $5.6 million from 24 territories. Its best market was a second-place start in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2209&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Royale' Flush in Second Weekend|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film took $80.2 million in the [[Cinema of the United States|United States]] and [[Cinema of Canada|Canada]] and $84.6 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $164.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>  ''Saw III'' has the highest-grossing weekend in the series, holds the records of highest-grossing in the international market and is the second highest-grossing film in the series worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> It is also Lionsgate's fifth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)  \n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n!colspan=\"3\"  align=\"center\" | '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''United States/Canada'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other markets'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 27, 2006\n|align=\"center\" | $10,000,000\n|$80,238,724 \t \t \n|$84,635,551\t\n|$164,874,275\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film was not screened in advance for critics.<ref name=\"AZcentral\">{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/ent/movies/articles/1103saw1103.html|title=Saw III|last=Cordova|first=Randy|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=November 3, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110914010022/http://www.azcentral.com/ent/movies/articles/1103saw1103.html|archivedate=September 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 28% based on 92 reviews, and a rating average of 4.23/10. The site's consensus states: \"''Saw III'' does little beyond repeating its predecessor's tropes on a gorier level.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/| title=Saw III (2006)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = June 29, 2019}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average score out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the film received an average score of 48 based on 16 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews| title= Saw III Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = September 12, 2011 }}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade moviegoers gave the film was a \"B\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1552067,00.html|title='Saw' Conquers|last=Rich|first=Joshua|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=October 29, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905020703/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1552067,00.html|archivedate=September 5, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Robert Koehler gave the film a mixed review.  He criticized the use of several flashbacks in the film, saying that it \"[...] hinder[ed] the movie, ratcheting down its tension and pace\". He explained, \"A bigger problem lies with Leigh Whannell's script, which utilizes so many flashbacks and explanatory inserts that the tension, a defining feature of the first ''Saw'', is lost\". He did, however praise the acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931983|title=Saw III Review|last=Koehler|first=Robert|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120918085329/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931983|archivedate=September 18, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Roger Moore of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave it two out of five stars, criticizing the plot and acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Saw%20III&Find+it%21=Submit+Query|title=Saw III (2 stars out of 5)|last=Moore|first=Roger|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122053221/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Saw%20III&Find+it%21=Submit+Query|archivedate=November 22, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''{{'}}s Peter Hartlaub gave the film a negative review, criticizing the plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/10/30/DDGE8M1H9R1.DTL&type=movies|title=Bedridden Jigsaw's minion carries on killing in 'Saw III'|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130093627/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2006%2F10%2F30%2FDDGE8M1H9R1.DTL&type=movies|archivedate=January 30, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Michael Ordo\u00f1a of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that \"More gore is really all ''Saw III'' has to offer\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-saw30oct30,0,3788651.story|title=This new horror sequel little more than a hack|last=Ordo\u00f1a|first=Michael|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004053147/http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-saw30oct30,0,3788651.story|archivedate=October 4, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1553340,00.html|title=Saw III Review|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|date=November 1, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001080322/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1553340,00.html|archivedate=October 1, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Randy Cordova of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' gave it a negative review saying, \"''Saw III'' is devoid of any suspense or terror\".<ref name=\"AZcentral\"/> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Kim Newman]] gave the film two out of five stars. He said the acting was \"surprisingly good\" but criticized the script and torture devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=133503|title=Saw III Movie Review|last=Newman|first=Kim|authorlink=Kim Newman|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=November 29, 2006|accessdate=September 19, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021080717/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=133503|archivedate=October 21, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Accolades====\n''Saw III'' was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]], but lost to ''[[The Descent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/News/b8235_The_33rd_Annual_Saturn_Awards_Nominations_Announced_.html|title=The 33rd Annual Saturn Awards Nominations Announced!|last=Brattelli|first=Adrian|work=[[Fearnet]]|date=February 21, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110920051712/http://www.fearnet.com/news/News/b8235_The_33rd_Annual_Saturn_Awards_Nominations_Announced_.html|archivedate=September 20, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8847|title=33rd Annual Saturn Awards Winners Announced!|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 11, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015075805/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/8847/|archivedate=October 15, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was also nominated as the \"Choice Movie: Horror/Thriller\" at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], but lost to ''[[Disturbia (film)|Disturbia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/08/27/2007-teen-choice-awards-the-shocking-results|title=2007 Teen Choice Awards: The Shocking Results|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|work=[[Moviefone]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=August 27, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616054023/http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/08/27/2007-teen-choice-awards-the-shocking-results|archivedate=June 16, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bell was nominated for a [[MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Award]] for [[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534188/man-behind-jigsaw-dishes-on-saw-iii.jhtml|title=Man Behind Jigsaw Swears 'Saw' Killer Is Back For Third Bloodbath|last=Carroll|first=Larry|publisher=[[MTV.com]]|date=June 14, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108015029/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534188/man-behind-jigsaw-dishes-on-saw-iii.jhtml|archivedate=November 8, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but lost to [[Jack Nicholson]] for his role in ''[[The Departed]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2007/|title=2007 Movie Awards Summary|publisher=MTV.com|date=June 3, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906033141/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2007/|archivedate=September 6, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0489270}}\n* {{Metacritic film|saw-iii|Saw III}}\n* {{Mojo title|saw3|Saw III}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|saw_3|Saw III}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n{{James Wan}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 3}}\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2006 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2000s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films|3]]\n[[Category:Self-harm in fiction]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in film]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw III\n| image = Saw3 cape10.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay = [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Leigh Whannell\n* [[James Wan]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]]\n}}<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Saw III (2006)|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/64013?sid=b6cc7440-eb1a-4fa9-8195-afc4b79376e0&sr=3.873525&cp=1&pos=0|website=American Film Institute Catalog|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| distributor = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Koehler|first1=Robert|title=Saw III - Review|website=Variety|url=https://variety.com/2006/film/markets-festivals/saw-iii-1200512355/|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=December 3, 2017|date=October 28, 2006}}</ref>\n| released = {{Film date|2006|10|27|United States}}\n| runtime = 108 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 108:08--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-iii-2006-0 | title=''Saw III'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 11, 2006 | accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref>\n| country = Canada<ref name=\"bfi\"/><br>United States<ref name=\"bfi\">{{cite web|title=Saw III (2006)|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b8beb2d8e|website=British Film Institute|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $10 million<ref name=\"the-numbers\">{{cite web|title=Saw III|website=The Numbers| url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2006/SAW3.php}}</ref> \n| gross = $164.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Saw III''''' is a 2006 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] from a screenplay by [[Leigh Whannell]] and a story by Whannell and [[James Wan]]. It is the third installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars [[Tobin Bell]], [[Shawnee Smith]], [[Angus Macfadyen]], [[Bahar Soomekh]], [[Dina Meyer]], [[Donnie Wahlberg]], and Whannell.\n\nThe story follows [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff]], a man who, after his son is killed by a drunk driver, is put through a series of tests by [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]] in order to try to get him to let go of his vengeance for the man that killed his son. Meanwhile, a bed-ridden John Kramer has his apprentice [[Amanda Young]] kidnap [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Dr. Lynn Denlon]], who is tasked with keeping John alive for one final test before he dies.\n\nDevelopment began right after the successful opening weekend of ''[[Saw II]]''. Filming took place in [[Toronto]] from May to June 2006. Whannell aimed to make the story more emotional than previous installments, particularly with the Amanda and Jigsaw storyline. The film is dedicated to producer [[Gregg Hoffman]] who died on December 4, 2005.\n\n''Saw III'' was released in the United States on {{nowrap|October 27, 2006}}, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. It was a financial success, opening to $33.6 million and grossing $80.2 million in the United States and Canada. It is the highest-grossing film of the series in the international market with $84.6 million and the highest-grossing film in the series overall with $164.9 million worldwide. It received mixed to negative reviews from critics. Bell was nominated for \"Best Villain\" at the [[2007 MTV Movie Awards]] and the film received nominations for a [[Saturn Award]] as \"Best Horror Film\". The film was released to [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on {{nowrap|January 23, 2007}}, and topped the charts selling 2.5 million units in its first week. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw IV]]'', was released in 2007.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Saw II|After being left in the bathroom to die]], [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]] breaks his foot with a toilet lid to escape his shackle. Six months later, the aftermath of a Jigsaw \"game\" is discovered by a [[SWAT]] team. The victim, Troy, had to rip chains from his body in order to escape from a bomb. Detective Allison Kerry arrives at the scene, and points out that the room's exit was welded shut, breaking [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw]]'s [[modus operandi]] of giving his victims a chance to survive. While reviewing the videotape, she is abducted and awakens in a harness hooked into her ribs. Even though she retrieves the key from a beaker of acid and unlocks the harness, she is unable to remove it and is killed when time runs out.\n\nDr. Lynn Denlon is abducted from the hospital she works at, and brought to the bedridden John Kramer. His apprentice, Amanda Young, locks a shotgun collar around Lynn's neck that is connected to John's heart rate monitor, and will detonate if John dies or Lynn moves out of range. She is instructed by Amanda to keep him alive until another victim has completed his game. The other victim, Jeff, wakes up in a box and learns that he must undergo tests, which will lead him to the man who killed his son, Dylan, in a drunk driving accident. Jeff became unstable and vengeful as a result and now neglects his daughter, Corbett.\n\nJeff's first test leads him into a meat freezer. He finds Danica Scott, the only witness to the accident, who refused to testify in court; she is stripped naked and chained at the wrists between two poles, which begin spraying her with ice-cold water. Jeff attempts to reach the key, which is behind frozen bars after Danica persuades Jeff to help her, but she freezes to death before he can retrieve it.\n\nIn his next test, Judge Halden, who gave Dylan's killer six months in jail, is chained at the neck to the bottom of a pit. Rotted pig corpses are dropped into a rack of circular saws, slowly filling the vat, but Halden persuades Jeff to help him. Jeff sets fire to a furnace full of Dylan's toys in order to retrieve the key, and saves Halden before he drowns.\n\nHis third test involves Timothy Young, Dylan's killer, who is strapped to a machine called \"The Rack\" that will twist his limbs and neck until they break. The key is tied to the trigger of an enclosed shotgun. The shotgun goes off, after Jeff retrieves the key, killing Halden in the process. Jeff tries to stop the machine before Timothy's neck breaks, but fails.\n\nMeanwhile, Lynn is forced to perform an improvised surgery to relieve pressure on John's brain with a conventional drill. Amanda grows increasingly jealous of Lynn's interaction with John, who continues to reprimand her for being rude. It is only when John suffers a seizure that Amanda is willing to cooperate with Lynn. During the surgery, John hallucinates about [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|another woman]] and declares his love out loud. This upsets Amanda and when she leaves, she finds a letter which drives her to hysterics. Amanda returns with the news that Jeff has completed his tests, but refuses to remove Lynn's collar. She reveals that she no longer believes in John's philosophy, and has been creating inescapable traps. She also reveals that she fought with Detective Matthews after he escaped the bathroom, and left him for dead.\n\nRefusing to listen to John's warnings, Amanda shoots Lynn just as Jeff arrives. Jeff, who is revealed to be Lynn's husband, retaliates by shooting Amanda with a gun provided by John after his tests. As Amanda dies, John reveals that Lynn's test was actually hers: aware of her modus operandi, and unwilling to allow a murderer to continue his legacy, John decided to test her. John then addresses Jeff, offering to call an ambulance for Lynn if he accepts one last test: he can choose to kill John or forgive him. Jeff tells John he forgives him, but slashes his throat with a power saw. The door to the room seals as John plays a final tape, which tells Jeff that he has failed his final test by killing John, the only person who knows the whereabouts of his daughter. The tape ends as John dies, and Lynn's collar detonates, killing her.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff Denlon]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Lynn Denlon]]\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Allison Kerry]]\n* [[Leigh Whannell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Stanheight|Adam Stanheight]]\n* [[Mpho Koaho]] as [[List of Saw characters#Timothy Young|Timothy Young]]\n* [[Barry Flatman]] as [[List of Saw characters#Judge Halden|Judge Halden]]\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Lieutenant Daniel Rigg]]\n* [[J. Larose]] as [[List of Saw characters#Troy|Troy]]\n* Debra Lynne McCabe as [[List of Saw characters#Danica Scott|Danica Scott]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* Stefan Georgiou as [[List of Saw characters#Dylan Denlon|Dylan]]\n* [[Niamh Wilson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Corbett Denlon|Corbett]]\n* [[Alan van Sprang]] as Chris\n* Kim Roberts as Nurse Deborah\n* [[Franky G]] as [[List of Saw characters#Xavier Chavez|Xavier Chavez]]\n* Tim Burd as [[List of Saw characters#Obi Tate|Obi Tate]]\n* Oren Koules as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development and writing===\n[[Darren Lynn Bousman]], director and co-writer of ''[[Saw II]]'', [[James Wan]], director of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', and [[Leigh Whannell]], screenwriter on both, turned down the offer to make a third film in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]]. ''Saw II'' producer [[Gregg Hoffman]] died a few weeks after its release. Bousman, Wan and Whannell got together to have lunch the day they heard of Hoffman's passing and decided to make ''Saw III'' in dedication to Hoffman.<ref name=\"ComingSoonBousman\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=17120|title=Exclusive: Saw III's Darren Lynn Bousman|last=Douglas|first=Edward|work=ComingSoon.net|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=October 24, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013214127/http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=17120|archivedate=October 13, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Whannell aimed to make ''Saw III'' more emotional, describing the plot as essentially a father-daughter \"love story\" between Jigsaw and Amanda.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/interview-bousman-whannell|title=Interview Bousman & Whannell|publisher=[[Joblo.com]]|last=Topel|first=Fred|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023170149/http://www.joblo.com/horror-movies/news/interview-bousman-whannell|archivedate=October 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n[[File:James Wan and Leigh Whannell Saw 3D premiere.jpg|thumb|left|Wan (left) and Whannell (right) returned to write ''Saw III'' and also served as executive producers.]]\nBousman said they did not intend to have a twist ending, as distinctly as the previous films,  noting that \"I think most people will figure it out in the first 15 minutes of the film\". Whannell added, \"What Darren and I struck for ''Saw III'' was to have an emotionally impactful ending.\" As with the previous two films, the ending was only given to the actors who appeared in the final scene at the time it was filmed. At one point the script was stolen from Bousman's chair; however, it was returned before it was leaked online.<ref name=\"Lionsgate Home Entertainment\">{{cite video|title=The Details of Death: The Props of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=[[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]]|people=[[David Hackl]] (production designer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=4:15\u20134:23}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nSoomekh became close with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] after appearing in their film ''[[Crash (2004 film)|Crash]]'' (2004) and they wanted her in their next big film. Not a fan of horror films she found the role challenging. \"I had nightmares the first month I was on set\", she said.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/742/742130p1.html|title=Interview: Bahar Soomekh and Angus Macfadyen|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|page=1|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929191934/http://movies.ign.com/articles/742/742130p1.html|archivedate=September 29, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n''Saw III'' was given a larger budget of $10 million,<ref>{{cite news|title=Saw's Unkindest Cutssaw's Unkindest Cuts|last=Alexander|first=Chris|work=[[Toronto Star]]|publisher=[[Torstar]]|date=June 11, 2006}}</ref> compared to ''Saw II''{{'}}s $4 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1|title=Evolution of Scary Movies|last=Rooney|first=Brian|publisher=[[ABC News]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=August 22, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130917163419/http://abcnews.go.com/WNT/story?id=2611799&page=1|archivedate=September 17, 2013|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] took place for 27 days<ref name=\"ComingSoonBousman\"/> at [[Toronto]]'s [[Cinespace Film Studios]]<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rowe|first=Michael|journal=[[Fangoria]]|title=SAW III: Deadlier Lessons|issn=0164-2111|number=257|date=October 2006|pages=30}}</ref> from {{nowrap|May 8, 2006}}, to late June.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lionsgate-and-twisted-pictures-rip-into-saw-iii-as-latest-film-in-powerhouse-horror-franchise-starts-principal-photography-in-toronto-56092217.html|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures Rip Into SAW III as Latest Film in Powerhouse Horror Franchise Starts Principal Photography in Toronto|agency=[[PR Newswire]]|date=May 6, 2006|accessdate=August 19, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015063416/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/lionsgate-and-twisted-pictures-rip-into-saw-iii-as-latest-film-in-powerhouse-horror-franchise-starts-principal-photography-in-toronto-56092217.html|archivedate=October 15, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>   Production borrowed the bathroom set used in ''[[Scary Movie 4]]'', which parodied the franchise.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\"/>  Almost all the transitions from one place to another were not made using digital effects; the transitions were shot on the spot. For example, when the camera moves from Troy's crime scene to Kerry being in the bathtub, Meyer had to run, take off all her clothes, and jump into the tub.<ref name=\"BousmanWhannellJoblo\"/> Visually the film is akin to the previous two with using quick cuts and fast-paced rhythms. Bousman said, \"We're using a lot of [[whip pan]]s and [[wiktionary:flash frame|flash frames]] to create a dynamic feel\". [[Post-production]] services were provided by [[Deluxe Entertainment Services Group Inc.|Deluxe]].<ref name=\"ProdNotes\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/saw3/notes.pdf|title=Saw III Production Notes|publisher=[[Lions Gate Entertainment|Lionsgate]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517062303/http://www.visualhollywood.com/movies/saw3/notes.pdf|archivedate=May 17, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Trap designs===\nBousman described the hardest scene to film was the \"Pig Scene\", explaining that they had to rush and it involved filming \"so many moving parts\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-saw-iiis-director-darren-lynn-bousman|title=EXCLUSIVE: Saw III's Director Darren Lynn Bousman|publisher=MovieWeb|date=October 26, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001060509/http://www.movieweb.com/news/exclusive-saw-iiis-director-darren-lynn-bousman|archivedate=October 1, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The pig carcasses were made out of foam, rubber, and latex.<ref name=\"Lionsgate Home Entertainment\"/> The pig props had live, disinfected [[maggot]]s attached with honey.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Details of Death: The Props of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=David Hackl (production designer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=6:40\u20137:35}}</ref>\n\nFor \"The Rack Trap\", Whannell originally conceived it as a trap that would fold a person into a box, though it eventually morphed into the twisting of body parts.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Leigh Whannell (writer)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=1:27\u20131:51}}</ref> Bousman wanted to have a trap that involved freezing someone to death since the films had already covered burning to death, bleeding to death, and being cut to death. A body cast was made of Debra Lynn McCabe for \"The Freezer Room\" trap, but, because of safety regulations a person cannot be entombed, only a front or back body cast could be on the actress at any given time.<ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Darren Lynn Bousman (director), Leigh Whannell (writer), Debra Lynn McCabe (actor)|date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=4:50\u20135:40}}</ref> For the \"Classroom Trap\", J. Larose's character was originally going to be hanged from the ceiling by meat hooks, but it was decided against since he would not have been able to rip the chains out himself (as the script called for). It proved to be a challenge since it was done with [[Prosthetic makeup|prosthetics]] and [[practical effect]]s.<ref name=\"ProdNotes\"/><ref>{{cite video|title=The Traps of Saw III|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment|people=Darren Lynn Bousman (director), Leigh Whannell play  adam   |date=2007 | accessdate=September 14, 2011|time=6:23\u20136:59}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''Saw III'' was released domestically and in the United Kingdom on {{nowrap|October 27, 2006}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Saw-III#tab=summary|title=Saw III (2006)|work=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|publisher=Nash Information Services, LLC|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=saw3.htm|title=Saw III (2006) International Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> It was released in Australia on {{nowrap|November 2, 2006}}, and on {{nowrap|January 4, 2007}}, in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=main&id=saw3.htm|title=Saw III (2006) International Box Office Results|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> According to executive producer Daniel Heffner, the film was toned down seven times to obtain the [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|\"R\" rating]]. According to Bousman, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] (MPAA) ratings board was less concerned with the film's graphic violence than it was with emotional torture, citing television shows like ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation|CSI]]'' for expanding the scope of what is acceptable.<ref name=\"JobloDarren\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-darren-bousman|title=Interview: Darren Bousman|work=[[Joblo.com]]|date=June 19, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023170429/http://www.joblo.com/movie-news/interview-darren-bousman|archivedate=October 23, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In Japan, ''Saw III'' received a [[Eirin|R18+ rating]] while the previous two films received an R15+ rating.<ref name=\"DarrenBD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7411|title=SAW III: The Darren Lynn Bousman Blog Only on B-D!|last=Bousman|first=Darren Lynn|authorlink=Darren Lynn Bousman|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=October 11, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214002753/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7411|archivedate=February 14, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> At screenings in the United Kingdom, five people were reported to have fainted at separate cinemas with three at one cinema, resulting in ambulances being called.<ref name=\"UK\">{{cite web | work=[[BBC News]] | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/6101704.stm | title=Film fans faint at Saw III show | accessdate=October 21, 2006 | date=October 31, 2006 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407023257/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6101704.stm | archivedate=April 7, 2012 | url-status=live | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nThe opening scene of Troy's trap was shown at [[San Diego Comic-Con|San Diego Comic-Con International]] on July 21, 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/720/720081p1.html|title=Comic-Con 2006: Saw III Cuts Loose|work=IGN|publisher=News Corperotion|date=July 21, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202033315/http://movies.ign.com/articles/720/720081p1.html|archivedate=February 2, 2008|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The same clip was planned to be shown before the opening of ''[[Crank (film)|Crank]]'' in theaters on {{nowrap|September 1, 2006}}. However, the MPAA would not allow it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20061012saw3|title=Banned SAW 3 clip Revealed|last=Sciretta|first=Peter|publisher=[[/Film]]|date=October 12, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110913054621/http://www.slashfilm.com/article.php/20061012saw3|archivedate=September 13, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  On {{nowrap|October 10, 2006}}, Bell, Smith and Bousman appeared at [[Paramount Network|Spike TV]]'s Scream Awards to promote the film and the clip of Troy's trap was shown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/story/scream-for-spike-tvs-awards|title=Scream For Spike TV's Awards|last=Condit|first=Jon|work=DreadCentral|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=September 29, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021140056/http://www.dreadcentral.com/story/scream-for-spike-tvs-awards|archivedate=October 21, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Lionsgate]]'s president of theatrical marketing [[Tim Palen]] thought of the idea to make 1,000 posters with a small amount of Bell's blood, which was mixed with the printing ink. He said, \"I asked if it would be possible to use actual blood. There was silence. He said, 'We could try, but are you serious?' I said I was dead serious.\" The posters were sold for $20, with the first being auctioned off; all the proceeds from the auctioned poster were donated to the [[Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593|title=Inside Move: 'Saw' gets into bloody vein for promo poster|last=McClintock|first=Pamela|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=October 9, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109034821/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117951593|archivedate=November 9, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Lionsgate also held the third annual \"Give Til It Hurts\" [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the Red Cross and collected 23,493 pints of blood.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive|publisher=[[Red Cross]]|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106140610/http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|archivedate=November 6, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Soundtrack===\n{{Main|Saw III (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack was released on {{nowrap|October 24, 2006}}. James Christopher Monger of [[AllMusic]] gave the soundtrack three out of five stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/r930325|title=Saw 3 Original Soundtrack|last=Monger|first=James Christopher|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> Ed Thompson of [[IGN|IGN Music]] gave it a 7.2 out of 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.ign.com/articles/742/742276p1.html|title=An album teeming with solid cuts|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 14, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320174515/http://music.ign.com/articles/742/742276p1.html|archivedate=March 20, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n \n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Saw III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack\n| type       = Soundtrack\n| artist     = Various Artists\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 24, 2006\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 72:01\n| label      = Artists Addiction\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[Saw II (soundtrack)|Saw II: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| prev_year  = 2005\n| next_title = [[Saw IV (soundtrack)|Saw IV: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n;Track listing\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed       = yes\n| headline         = ''Saw III: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack''\n| extra_column = Artist\n| total_length = 72:01\n\n| title1 =  This Calling\n| writer1         = Oliver Herbert<br />Phillip LaBonte<br />Michael MArtin<br />[[Jeanne Sagan]]\n| extra1 = [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]]\n| length1 = 3:38\n\n| title2 = No Submission\n| writer2         = [[Tony Campos]]<br />[[Wayne Static]]\n| extra2 = [[Static-X]]\n| length2 = 2:40\n\n| title3 = [[Eyes of the Insane]]\n| writer3         =  [[Tom Araya]]<br />[[Jeff Hanneman]]\n| extra3 = [[Slayer]]\n| length3 = 3:33\n\n| title4 = Walk with Me in Hell\n| writer4         = [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]]\n| extra4 = Lamb of God \n| length4 = 5:11\n\n| title5 =  Monochrome\n| writer5         = [[Page Hamilton]]\n| extra5 = [[Helmet (band)|Helmet]] \n| length5 = 3:47\n\n| title6 = [[Guarded]]\n| writer6         = [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]\n| extra6 = Disturbed\n| length6 =  3:21\n\n| title7 =  Drilled A Wire Through My Cheek\n| writer7         = [[Justin Furstenfeld]]<br />Patrick Sugg\n| extra7 = [[Blue October]]\n| length7 = 4:25\n\n| title8 = No More\n| writer8         = \n| extra8 =  [[Drowning Pool]]\n| length8 = 4:26\n\n| title9 =  Burn It Down\n| writer9         = [[Avenged Sevenfold]]\n| extra9 = Avenged Sevenfold\n| length9 = 4:59\n\n| title10 = Your Nightmare\n| writer10         = [[Eighteen Visions]]\n| extra10 = Eighteen Visions\n| length10 = 3:23\n\n| title11 = Dead Underground\n| writer11         = [[Jim Kaufman]]<br />[[Ron Underwood]]\n| extra11 =  [[Opiate For The Masses]]\n| length11 = 3:58\n\n| title12 = [[Suffocating Under Words of Sorrow (What Can I Do)]]\n| writer12         = [[Bullet for My Valentine]]\n| extra12 = Bullet for My Valentine\n| length12 = 3:36\n\n| title13 = Fear Is Big Business\n| writer13 = [[Al Jourgensen]]<br />Thomas Victor\n| extra13 = [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]]\n| length13 = 4:52\n\n| title14 = The Wolf Is Loose\n| writer14 = [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]]\n| extra14 = Mastodon\n| length14 = 3:34\n\n| title15 = Killer Inside\n| writer15 = Hydrovibe\n| extra15 = Hydrovibe Featuring [[Shawnee Smith]]\n| length15 = 3:17\n\n| title16 = Sakkara\n| writer16 = Hourcast  \n| extra16 = Hourcast \n| length16 = 3:45\n\n| title17 = Shed\n| writer17 = [[Fredrik Thordendal]]<br />[[Shagrath]]<br />[[Galder]]\n| extra17 = [[Meshuggah]]\n| length17 = 3:35\n\n| title18 = Effigy\n| writer18 = [[The SmashUp]]\n| extra18 = The SmashUp\n| length18 = 4:36\n\n| title19 = Siesta Loca\n| writer19 =[[Ghost Machine]] \n| extra19 = Ghost Machine\n| length19 = 3:50\n\n| title20 = Sh*! hole Theme\n| writer20 = [[Charlie Clouser]] \n| extra20 =  Clouser\n| length20 = 3:15\n}}\n\n===Home media===\n''Saw III'' was released to [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] through [[Lionsgate Home Entertainment]] on {{nowrap|January 23, 2007}}. It topped the home video charts in the United States and Canada with 1.6 million units sold its first day and finished the week with 2.5 million units sold.<ref name=\"DVDSales\">{{cite news|title=Lionsgate and Twisted Pictures' SAW III 'Three-Peats' at Number One on DVD Charts While Also Claiming Most Successful Week One Blu-Ray Debut to Date|agency=[[CNW Group]]|date=February 1, 2007}}</ref> The \"Unrated DVD\" was also released that day and features a 113-minute cut of the film that includes more gore.<ref name=\"DVDSales\"/> A 120-minute-long [[Director's cut]] was released on {{nowrap|October 23, 2007}}, to coincide with the theatrical release of ''[[Saw IV]]'' on {{nowrap|October 26}}. It also included an [[alternate ending]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/9589|title=Uber-Bloody 'Saw III: Director's Cut' This October, Box Set!|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|publisher=The Collective|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010080309/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/9589|archivedate=October 10, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The director's cut was released on Blu-ray in Region B on October 7, 2008, in France only.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.fr/Saw-III-Blu-ray/dp/B001EY0LDM|title=Saw 3 [Blu-ray] [Director's Cut Extreme]|accessdate=December 16, 2017|agency=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]}}</ref>\n\n===Deleted scenes===\nThe original cut of the film ran for slightly over two hours, and several scenes were cut out, including a scene which depicted an extended scene of Kerry and Rigg examining Troy's trap, where Kerry reveals to Rigg she has had nightmares about Eric, and she blames herself for what happened to him.<ref>{{cite video|title=Deleted Scenes|medium=DVD|publisher=Lionsgate Home Entertainment| accessdate=September 18, 2011}}</ref> Adam had more scenes in the original cut.<ref name=\"IGNDarren\">{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/741/741449p2.html|title=IGN: Interview: Darren Lynn Bousman|accessdate=October 26, 2007|work=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|date=October 26, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001015851/http://movies.ign.com/articles/741/741449p2.html|archivedate=October 1, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A scene that showed Jigsaw regretting his actions was also cut. Bell said, \"I'm glad they cut that scene. This guy knows exactly what he's doing. Does he start off with a model, then refine it? Yeah, he probably does. But there are certain things that are interesting and advance the story, and there are other things that are basically sort of backstory, and you don't really need to know\".<ref name=\"TobinBellAVClub\">{{cite web|title=Tobin Bell Random Roles|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/tobin-bell,2513/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|last=Heisler|first=Steve|date=October 29, 2008|accessdate=October 17, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118125625/http://www.avclub.com/articles/tobin-bell,2513/|archivedate=January 18, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Saw III'' opened at number one on 4,700 screens at 3,167 theaters grossing $33.6 million from its opening weekend, a two percent increase from ''Saw II''{{'s}} $31.7 million. It held the biggest [[Halloween]] weekend debut for five years until it was beaten in 2011 by ''[[Puss in Boots (2011 film)|Puss in Boots]]'' ($34 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/pop2it/2011/10/puss-in-boots-sets-halloween-box-office-record-for-now.html|title='Puss in Boots' sets Halloween box-office record (for now)|last=Porter|first=Rick|work=[[Zap2it]]|date=October 30, 2011|accessdate=October 30, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111031170710/http://blog.zap2it.com/pop2it/2011/10/puss-in-boots-sets-halloween-box-office-record-for-now.html|archivedate=October 31, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  It was also Lionsgate's highest-opening weekend. Lionsgate's exit polling indicated that 69 percent of the audience was under 25 years old and 51 percent was male.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2191&p=.htm|title='Saw' Sharp in Third Outing|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011}}</ref>  In its second weekend it placed number four, dropping down 56% to $14.8 million, compared to ''Saw II''{{'s}} second weekend drop of 47% to $16.9 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2194&p=.htm|title='Borat' Bombards the Top Spot|last=Gray|first=Brandon|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 6, 2006|accessdate=September 12, 2011}}</ref> The film was closed out of theaters on {{nowrap|December 14, 2006}}, after 49 days of release.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url= http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw3.htm |title= Saw III (2006) | work=Box Office Mojo| accessdate=October 29, 2006}}</ref>\n\n''Saw III'' opened at number five in the international market with an estimated $6 million. It opened at number one in the [[Cinema of the United Kingdom|United Kingdom]] to $4.7 million. In [[Cinema of Taiwan|Taiwan]] it placed third and opened to $320,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2192&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Prada' Still in Vogue|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> For its second weekend it opened to number two with an estimated $9.7 million. In [[Cinema of Spain|Spain]] it made $3.1 million, an improvement over the previous films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2199&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Borat' Doesn't Budge|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 13, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> For its third weekend, ''Saw III'' grossed $8 million, including [[Cinema of Japan|Japan]]'s opening on 86 screens with $1.1 million. [[Cinema of Australia|Australia]] made $4.3 million, Spain grossed $3.8 million and [[Cinema of Brazil|Brazil]] made $3.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2204&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Casino' Cashes In|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 20, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref> In its fourth weekend it placed fourth place with an estimated $5.6 million from 24 territories. Its best market was a second-place start in France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=2209&p=.htm|title=Around the World Roundup: 'Royale' Flush in Second Weekend|last=Bresnan|first=Conor|work=Box Office Mojo|date=November 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film took $80.2 million in the [[Cinema of the United States|United States]] and [[Cinema of Canada|Canada]] and $84.6 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $164.8 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>  ''Saw III'' has the highest-grossing weekend in the series, holds the records of highest-grossing in the international market and is the second highest-grossing film in the series worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/showdowns/chart/?id=sawvs.htm|title='Saw' Vs. 'Saw'|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=August 19, 2011}}</ref> It is also Lionsgate's fifth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n!rowspan=\"2\"  align=\"center\" | '''Release date'''<br />(United States)  \n!rowspan=\"2\"   align=\"center\" | '''Budget'''<br />(estimated)<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n!colspan=\"3\"  align=\"center\" | '''Box office revenue'''<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n|-\n!align=\"center\"   | '''United States/Canada'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Other markets'''\n!align=\"center\"   | '''Worldwide'''\n|-\n|October 27, 2006\n|align=\"center\" | $10,000,000\n|$80,238,724 \t \t \n|$84,635,551\t\n|$164,874,275\n|-\n|}\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film was not screened in advance for critics.<ref name=\"AZcentral\">{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/ent/movies/articles/1103saw1103.html|title=Saw III|last=Cordova|first=Randy|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=November 3, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110914010022/http://www.azcentral.com/ent/movies/articles/1103saw1103.html|archivedate=September 14, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the film a score of 28% based on 92 reviews, and a rating average of 4.23/10. The site's consensus states: \"''Saw III'' does little beyond repeating its predecessor's tropes on a gorier level.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/| title=Saw III (2006)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher = [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] | accessdate = June 29, 2019}}</ref> At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a weighted average score out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the film received an average score of 48 based on 16 reviews, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews| title= Saw III Reviews | publisher = [[CBS Interactive]] | work = [[Metacritic]] | accessdate = September 12, 2011 }}</ref> [[CinemaScore]] polls reported that the average grade moviegoers gave the film was a \"B\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1552067,00.html|title='Saw' Conquers|last=Rich|first=Joshua|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|date=October 29, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905020703/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1552067,00.html|archivedate=September 5, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Robert Koehler gave the film a mixed review.  He criticized the use of several flashbacks in the film, saying that it \"[...] hinder[ed] the movie, ratcheting down its tension and pace\". He explained, \"A bigger problem lies with Leigh Whannell's script, which utilizes so many flashbacks and explanatory inserts that the tension, a defining feature of the first ''Saw'', is lost\". He did, however praise the acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931983|title=Saw III Review|last=Koehler|first=Robert|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Reed Business Information]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120918085329/http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117931983|archivedate=September 18, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  Roger Moore of the ''[[Orlando Sentinel]]'' gave it two out of five stars, criticizing the plot and acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Saw%20III&Find+it%21=Submit+Query|title=Saw III (2 stars out of 5)|last=Moore|first=Roger|work=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 27, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111122053221/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/entertainment/movies/orl-db-moviereviews-searchresults,0,3279701,results.formprofile?turbine_cdb_lib__cdb_01_txt=Saw%20III&Find+it%21=Submit+Query|archivedate=November 22, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]''{{'}}s Peter Hartlaub gave the film a negative review, criticizing the plot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2006/10/30/DDGE8M1H9R1.DTL&type=movies|title=Bedridden Jigsaw's minion carries on killing in 'Saw III'|last=Hartlaub|first=Peter|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130093627/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=%2Fc%2Fa%2F2006%2F10%2F30%2FDDGE8M1H9R1.DTL&type=movies|archivedate=January 30, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Michael Ordo\u00f1a of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' said that \"More gore is really all ''Saw III'' has to offer\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-saw30oct30,0,3788651.story|title=This new horror sequel little more than a hack|last=Ordo\u00f1a|first=Michael|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|date=October 30, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004053147/http://www.calendarlive.com/printedition/calendar/cl-et-saw30oct30,0,3788651.story|archivedate=October 4, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Owen Gleiberman]] of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1553340,00.html|title=Saw III Review|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|work=Entertainment Weekly|publisher=Time Inc.|date=November 1, 2006|accessdate=September 13, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001080322/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1553340,00.html|archivedate=October 1, 2011|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Randy Cordova of ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' gave it a negative review saying, \"''Saw III'' is devoid of any suspense or terror\".<ref name=\"AZcentral\"/> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Kim Newman]] gave the film two out of five stars. He said the acting was \"surprisingly good\" but criticized the script and torture devices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=133503|title=Saw III Movie Review|last=Newman|first=Kim|authorlink=Kim Newman|work=[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]|publisher=[[Bauer Media Group]]|date=November 29, 2006|accessdate=September 19, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021080717/http://www.empireonline.com/reviews/ReviewComplete.asp?FID=133503|archivedate=October 21, 2012|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Accolades====\n''Saw III'' was nominated for a [[Saturn Award]] for [[Saturn Award for Best Horror Film|Best Horror Film]], but lost to ''[[The Descent]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fearnet.com/news/News/b8235_The_33rd_Annual_Saturn_Awards_Nominations_Announced_.html|title=The 33rd Annual Saturn Awards Nominations Announced!|last=Brattelli|first=Adrian|work=[[Fearnet]]|date=February 21, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110920051712/http://www.fearnet.com/news/News/b8235_The_33rd_Annual_Saturn_Awards_Nominations_Announced_.html|archivedate=September 20, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/8847|title=33rd Annual Saturn Awards Winners Announced!|last=Miska|first=Brad|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 11, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015075805/http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/8847/|archivedate=October 15, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It was also nominated as the \"Choice Movie: Horror/Thriller\" at the [[Teen Choice Awards]], but lost to ''[[Disturbia (film)|Disturbia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/08/27/2007-teen-choice-awards-the-shocking-results|title=2007 Teen Choice Awards: The Shocking Results|last=Weinberg|first=Scott|work=[[Moviefone]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|date=August 27, 2007|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616054023/http://blog.moviefone.com/2007/08/27/2007-teen-choice-awards-the-shocking-results|archivedate=June 16, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Bell was nominated for a [[MTV Movie Awards|MTV Movie Award]] for [[MTV Movie Award for Best Villain|Best Villain]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534188/man-behind-jigsaw-dishes-on-saw-iii.jhtml|title=Man Behind Jigsaw Swears 'Saw' Killer Is Back For Third Bloodbath|last=Carroll|first=Larry|publisher=[[MTV.com]]|date=June 14, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108015029/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534188/man-behind-jigsaw-dishes-on-saw-iii.jhtml|archivedate=November 8, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> but lost to [[Jack Nicholson]] for his role in ''[[The Departed]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2007/|title=2007 Movie Awards Summary|publisher=MTV.com|date=June 3, 2006|accessdate=September 20, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110906033141/http://www.mtv.com/ontv/movieawards/2007/|archivedate=September 6, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|0489270}}\n* {{Metacritic film|saw-iii|Saw III}}\n* {{Mojo title|saw3|Saw III}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|saw_3|Saw III}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Leigh Whannell}}\n{{James Wan}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 3}}\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2006 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2000s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Leigh Whannell]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films|3]]\n[[Category:Self-harm in fiction]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Obscenity controversies in film]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:7ef6:9800:c5b7:fd1f:d7c:7635", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_III"}
{"title_page": "Calvin Prasad", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n\n'''Calvin Prasad''' (born March 11, 1980) is an [[Indians in Fiji|Indo-Fijian]] [[chess]] player. He is the first male chess player to earn a [[Candidate Master]] (CM) title for the small chess community of [[Fiji]].<ref name=cvv>{{cite news|title=Prasad is Fiji's first CM |url=http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=113 |publisher=fijichess.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927184622/http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=113 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?si=main.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=sportsnational&cid=14180 Fiji chess player creates history] {{Dead link|date=March 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe has represented Fiji four times in international tournaments, in 2003 at the [[Fiji Invitational Chess Championships]], in 2004 at the Zonal Championships in [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]],<ref>[http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=131 Prasad is Fiji's National Athlete of the Year] at fijichess.com, accessed 2008-01-25  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017120456/http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=131 |date=October 17, 2007 }}</ref> and twice at the [[Chess Olympiad]], ([[36th Chess Olympiad|Mallorca 2004]] and [[37th Chess Olympiad|Turin 2006]]).<ref>[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/oggywk4e.html Prasad, Calvin] team chess record at olimpbase.org</ref>\n\nHe is also a Former [[Fijian Chess Championship|National Champion]] (2004) of Fiji and has had many tournament victories.<ref name=\"cvv\" /> He is the defending champion of the Kundan Singh Open Chess Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=166312|title=Fiji Chess Federation open championship|last=Kumar|first=Manoj|date=17 February 2011|work=Fiji Times|accessdate=5 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711001333/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=166312|archive-date=11 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFor the past 4 years, he has also served on the management board of the [[Fiji Chess Federation]], of which he is currently the Vice-President.\n\nPrasad was voted the National Male Athlete of 2006.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Karate kid wins for dad | url=http://www.fijitimes.com.fj/story.aspx?ref=archive&id=59925 | date=1 April 2007 | periodical=[[Fiji Times]] | access-date=24 April 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928024649/http://www.fijitimes.com.fj/story.aspx?ref=archive&id=59925 | archive-date=28 September 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Prasad won the Fiji National Chess Championships and became Fiji National Chess Champion. He last won this title in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Prasad bags chess title | url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=187957 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731162747/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=187957 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2012-07-31 }}</ref> Prasad was also awarded the '2011 Player of the Year Award'.[https://web.archive.org/web/20120203091900/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=192060 2011 Player of the Year award went to last year's national champion CM Calvin Prasad]\n\n2016 - Calvin Prasad removed as President of Fiji Chess Federation in an Extra- Ordinary General Meeting. \n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Fide}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prasad, Calvin}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian chess players]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-chess-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n\n'''Calvin Prasad''' (born March 11, 1980) is an [[Indians in Fiji|Indo-Fijian]] [[chess]] player. He is the first male chess player to earn a [[Candidate Master]] (CM) title for the small chess community of [[Fiji]].<ref name=cvv>{{cite news|title=Prasad is Fiji's first CM |url=http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=113 |publisher=fijichess.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927184622/http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=113 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.fijitv.com.fj/index.cfm?si=main.resources&cmd=forumview&cbegin=0&uid=sportsnational&cid=14180 Fiji chess player creates history] {{Dead link|date=March 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe has represented Fiji four times in international tournaments, 2003 at the [[Fiji Invitational Chess Championships]], 2004 at the Zonal Championships in [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]],<ref>[http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=131 Prasad is Fiji's National Athlete of the Year] at fijichess.com, accessed 2008-01-25  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017120456/http://www.fijichess.com/default2.asp?active_page_id=131 |date=October 17, 2007 }}</ref> and twice at the [[Chess Olympiad]], ([[36th Chess Olympiad|Mallorca 2004]] and [[37th Chess Olympiad|Turin 2006]]).<ref>[http://www.olimpbase.org/players/oggywk4e.html Prasad, Calvin] team chess record at olimpbase.org</ref>\n\nHe is also a Former [[Fijian Chess Championship|National Champion]] (2004) of Fiji and has had many tournament victories.<ref name=\"cvv\" /> He is the defending champion of the Kundan Singh Open Chess Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=166312|title=Fiji Chess Federation open championship|last=Kumar|first=Manoj|date=17 February 2011|work=Fiji Times|accessdate=5 March 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711001333/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=166312|archive-date=11 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFor the past 4 years, he has also served on the management board of the [[Fiji Chess Federation]], of which he is currently the Vice-President.\n\nPrasad was voted the National Male Athlete of 2006.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Karate kid wins for dad | url=http://www.fijitimes.com.fj/story.aspx?ref=archive&id=59925 | date=1 April 2007 | periodical=[[Fiji Times]] | access-date=24 April 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928024649/http://www.fijitimes.com.fj/story.aspx?ref=archive&id=59925 | archive-date=28 September 2007 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Prasad won the Fiji National Chess Championships and became Fiji National Chess Champion.  He last won this title in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news | title=Prasad bags chess title | url=http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=187957 | archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731162747/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=187957 | url-status=dead | archive-date=2012-07-31 }}</ref>  Prasad was also awarded the '2011 Player of the Year Award'.[https://web.archive.org/web/20120203091900/http://www.fijitimes.com/story.aspx?id=192060 2011 Player of the Year award went to last year's national champion CM Calvin Prasad]\n\n2016 - Calvin Prasad removed as President of Fiji Chess Federation in an Extra- Ordinary General Meeting. \n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Fide}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prasad, Calvin}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fijian people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Fijian chess players]]\n\n\n{{Fiji-chess-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "H elokeinu h 1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calvin_Prasad"}
{"title_page": "Saw IV", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw IV\n| image = Saw4final.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patrick Melton]]\n* [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n}}\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Patrick Melton\n* Marcus Dunstan\n* [[Thomas Fenton]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lyriq Bent]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]]\n* [[Justin Louis]] \n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n}}<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]</br>Brett Sullivan\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|26|United States}}\n| runtime = 92 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 92:26--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-iv-2 | title=''Saw IV'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 11, 2007 | accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Canada\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $10 million\n| gross = $139.4 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw4.htm|title=Saw IV (2007)|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Saw IV''''' is a 2007 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] from a screenplay by [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]], and a story by Melton, Dunstan, and [[Thomas Fenton]]. It is the fourth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]], the third directed by Bousman. The film stars [[Lyriq Bent]], [[Costas Mandylor]], [[Scott Patterson]], [[Tobin Bell]], [[Betsy Russell]], [[Athena Karkanis]], [[Justin Louis]], and [[Donnie Wahlberg]].\n\nThe film continues the story of the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]]'s obsession with teaching people the value of their lives and occurs roughly at the same time as the [[Saw III|previous installment]]. Despite Jigsaw's death, the film focuses on his ability to manipulate people into continuing his work. The story follows Officer Daniel Rigg being put through a series of tests in order to try to let go of his obsession with saving everyone, while at the same time attempting to save his partner.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on October 26, 2007, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics. Despite this, the film was a box office success, grossing $139 million worldwide. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw V]]'', was released in 2008.\n\n==Plot==\nA wax-coated [[microcassette]] is found in [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]'s stomach during his autopsy, and reveals to Detective [[Mark Hoffman]] that, despite his death, the games will continue and he will be tested. Elsewhere, two men \u2013 one with his eyes sewn shut, the other with his mouth sewn shut \u2013 awaken in a [[mausoleum]], chained at the neck to a winch. The blinded man panics and activates the winch before attacking the muted man, who kills him to get a key from his collar to free himself.\n\nFour days after [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Allison Kerry's]] death in the previous film, a [[SWAT]] team led by Hoffman and Officer [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Daniel Rigg]] find her body, and Hoffman warns Rigg against breaking through an unsecured door to reach her. The scene is also investigated by Agents [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]] and [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Lindsey Perez]], Kerry's FBI contacts, who received a message and key from her. Noting John and [[Amanda Young]]'s physical limitations, Strahm speculates that a third accomplice was involved and soon becomes suspicious of Rigg, who has developed an obsession with saving people in the six months since the disappearance of detective [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Eric Matthews]]. That night, Rigg is attacked in his home; he awakens and watches a video from Jigsaw, which is where he learns that Eric is still alive and has ninety minutes to save himself, with Hoffman's life at risk as well. Meanwhile, he must play his own game in order to face and overcome his obsession.\n\nRigg finds a pimp named Brenda bound to a chair in his living room, and accidentally activates the trap, which slowly tears her scalp off. He manages to free her, but kills her in self-defense when she attacks him with a knife in order to evade arrest. Rigg is then led to a motel and instructed to abduct the owner, Ivan Landsness, who Rigg learns is a serial rapist. He forces Ivan into a trap, which requires Ivan to blind both of his eyes as payment for photographing and videotaping his crimes, in order to escape. However, Ivan only blinds one of his eyes, and the trap dismembers him.\n\nNext, Rigg is led to a school where he once investigated the abuse of a young student, committed by her father but not proven. Rigg finds that the student\u2019s parents are impaled by metal spikes: Rex, who has already died from blood loss, and his also abused wife Morgan, who has remained alive at his expense by pulling the spikes from both of their bodies. The spikes were flesh wounds for Morgan but crucial arteries for Rex. Rigg gives her a key to free herself then turns on a fire alarm and goes to the location of his final test.\n\nWhile investigating Rigg's apartment, the agents find a clue that leads them to [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]], John's ex-wife. Jill reveals that John worked in civil engineering and property development, and she miscarried her son Gideon after seven months when Cecil Adams, a drug addict, slammed a door into her stomach while robbing her rehab clinic. The loss of their son destroyed their marriage and made John become insane and develop his life tests. At the motel, the agents learn that the room was rented out to a lawyer named Art Blank, John's partner from his previous work and the survivor of the mausoleum trap from the beginning of the film, who vanished two weeks prior. Art is revealed to be the man overseeing the current game when he hands Eric a gun. At the school, the agents learn that all three victims, along with Jill, were Art's clients. Strahm and Perez find a puppet and a tape recorder in another room, which plays a cryptic message for Perez and the forecast that Strahm will kill an innocent person. Its face explodes and sends shrapnel into Perez' face. After she is hospitalized, Strahm furiously questions Jill. He learns how John ended his work with Art after falling into his depression, and that Cecil became the first victim of John's \"games\". Strahm connects her story and a prior clue to the Gideon Meatpacking Plant, the location of Rigg's final test.\n\nStrahm arrives after Rigg, but ends up following [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff Denlon]], the protagonist in ''[[Saw III]]''. He finds him in the sickroom from the previous film, with the dead corpses of John, Amanda and others lying around, and is forced to kill Jeff in self-defense when he demands his daughter back. It now becomes clear that this happened only moments after Jeff had killed John and Amanda in ''Saw III''. Meanwhile, Art pulls out a device which will free him, Eric, and Hoffman once the timer expires; if used before then, a pair of pincers will sever his spine. Rigg finds them and is yelled at and ultimately shot by Eric to prevent him from entering the room too early, but as he breaks in with one second to spare, two overhead ice blocks are released that swing down and crush Eric's head, killing him. Rigg shoots and kills Art, believing he is responsible for the game, only to learn from Art's tape recorder that his interference and continued obsession to save people, while they should have saved themselves, caused Eric's death. Hoffman, the actual accomplice, releases himself from the chair, but leaves Rigg to die. He then seals Strahm in the sickroom, and leaves the plant. The scene then cuts to Hoffman at the morgue, revealing that John's autopsy took place ''after'' the events of the film.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Officer Daniel Rigg]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Agent Peter Strahm]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Agent Lindsey Perez]]\n* [[Louis Ferreira|Justin Louis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Art Blank|Art Blank]]\n* Simon Reynolds as Officer Lamanna\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Lynn Denlon]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Kerry]]\n* Mike Realba as [[List of Saw characters#Fisk|Detective Fisk]]\n* [[Marty Adams]] as [[List of Saw characters#Ivan Landsness|Ivan Landsness]]\n* Sarain Boylan as [[List of Saw characters#Brenda|Brenda]]\n* Billy Otis as [[List of Saw characters#Cecil Adams|Cecil Adams]]\n* James Van Patten as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]]\n* Kevin Rushton as [[List of Saw characters#Trevor|Trevor]]\n* [[Julian Richings]] as Vagrant\n* Ingrid Hart as [[List of Saw characters#Tracy Rigg|Tracy Rigg]]\n* [[Niamh Wilson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Corbett Denlon|Corbett Denlon]]\n* [[Janet Land]] as [[List of Saw characters#Morgan and Rex|Morgan]]\n* [[Ron Lea]] as [[List of Saw characters#Morgan and Rex|Rex]]\n* [[Tony Nappo]] as [[List of Saw characters#Gus Colyard|Gus]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]] as [[List of Saw characters#Addison Corday|Addison]]\n* [[Noam Jenkins]] as [[List of Saw characters#Michael Marks|Michael]]\n* Mike Butters as [[List of Saw characters#Paul Leahy|Paul]]\n* [[J. Larose]] as [[List of Saw characters#Troy|Troy]]\n* [[Oren Koules]] as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n* Alison Luther as Jane\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n''Saw IV\u2019''s writers were Thomas Fenton, Marcus Dunstan, and Patrick Melton.<ref>[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7904 Actual writer for ''Saw IV'' revealed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402181539/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7904 |date=April 2, 2007 }}</ref> There was also a hunt for a director before it was officially stated that [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], who had originally passed on it, would again direct the fourth installment, with creators and executive producers [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]] also returning.<ref>[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=18996 Bousman Returns to Direct Saw IV.] ComingSoon.net, 2007-02-20.</ref><ref name=\"MObousman\">[http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12255.html Darren Lynn Bousman Interview, SAW 4.] Movies Online. Retrieved 2007-06-22.</ref> [[Principal photography]] took from April 16, 2007<ref>[http://www.canmag.com/nw/6815-saw-iv-production Date set for filming]</ref> to May 3, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omdc.on.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=6269|title=Production in Ontario 2007|publisher=Ontario Media Development Corporation|format=pdf|accessdate=September 4, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVbGTLqR?url=http://www.omdc.on.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=6269|url-status=live|archivedate=September 5, 2010}}</ref> The filming location was [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]];<ref>[http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news?id=28315 Location set for the filming of ''Saw IV'']</ref> the same place where both ''[[Saw II]]''<ref>[http://www.movieweb.com/news/01/9701.php/ ''Saw II'' filming location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712101207/http://www.movieweb.com/news/01/9701.php |date=July 12, 2007 }} [[MovieWeb]] retrieved 2005-27-10.</ref> and ''[[Saw III]]''<ref>[http://www.movieweb.com/news/27/12127.php/ ''Saw III'' filming location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070623042041/http://www.movieweb.com/news/27/12127.php |date=June 23, 2007 }} [[MovieWeb]] retrieved 2006-04-17.</ref> were filmed. The post-production period began on 19 May.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0890870/combined IMDb post-production period]</ref>\n\nIn an interview with Bousman, he stated that the last work on ''Saw IV'' would happen in August to be able to have prints made.<ref name=\"MObousman\"/> At [[San Diego Comic-Con|Comic Con Intermeational]] 2007, it was revealed by Bousman and producer [[Mark Burg]] that the MPAA had given the film an NC-17 rating. They would have to figure out whether or not to cut the film to achieve an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|R rating]] or release it as an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|NC-17]] film,<ref>[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=22826 Saw IV Too Much for Comic-Con] Retrieved on 2007-08-07</ref> the former of which they accomplished.<ref>[http://www.filmratings.com/filmRatings_cara/reports/s10166925.htm]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] held its fourth annual \u201cGive Til It Hurts\u201d [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive|publisher=[[Red Cross]]|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61eiTSBkv?url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|url-status=live|archivedate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film grossed $63,300,095 in the United States and an additional $71,228,814 internationally, bringing the theatrical total to $134,528,909.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2007/SAW4.php |title=Saw IV (2007) - Box Office |accessdate=2009-11-02 |publisher=The Numbers}}</ref> It is Lionsgate's sixth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nCritical reception to ''Saw IV'' was negative. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports an approval rating of 20% based on 81 reviews, with an average score of 3.8/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV (2007)|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=2019-06-29}}</ref> The site's consensus states: \u201c''Saw IV'' is more disturbing than compelling, with material already seen in the prior installments.\u201d On [[Metacritic]], the film has an average score of 36 out of 100, based on 16 reviews, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/saw4 |title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews |accessdate=2007-11-06 |publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\nScott Schueller from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \u201ca film as edgy as a rubber knife\u201d and said that \u201cif the terrible craft of Bousman's film doesn\u2019t turn your stomach, the borderline pornographic violence will. It\u2019s disconcerting to imagine anyone enjoying the vile filth splashing the screen.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-saw-iv/243237/content |title=Movie review: 'Saw IV' |accessdate=2007-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127082238/http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-saw-iv/243237/content |archivedate=November 27, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Frank Scheck from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said \u201cthe famously inventive torture sequences here seem depleted of imagination\u201d, but added that \u201cit hasn\u2019t yet [[Jumping the shark|jumped the shark]] like such predecessors as the ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' and ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)|Friday the 13th]]'' movies eventually did.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film/reviews/article_display.jsp?&rid=10102 |title=Saw IV |accessdate=2007-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028145921/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film/reviews/article_display.jsp?&rid=10102 |archivedate=October 28, 2007 }}</ref> Peter Hartlaub from ''[[San Francisco Chronicle|The San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called it \u201cthe ''[[Syriana]]'' of slasher films, so complicated and circuitous that your only hope of understanding everything is to eat lots of fish the night before and then watch each of the previous films, in order, right before you enter the theater.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/10/29/DD4OT1N6U.DTL&type=movies |title=Review: The hunt for the Jigsaw Killer continues in 'Saw IV' |accessdate=2007-11-10 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Peter | last=Hartlaub | date=2007-10-29}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] wrote that \u201c''Saw IV'' functions as a drawn-out, tedious epilogue to a series that began with an energetic bang three years ago with ''Saw'', then progressively lost momentum, coherence, and intelligence with each successive annual installment.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/s/saw4.html|title=Saw IV|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref>\n\nA less negative review came from Jamie Russell from the [[BBC]], who called it \"deeply unsettling; just like a horror movie should be.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2007/10/22/saw_iv_2007_review.shtml |title=Saw IV (2007) |accessdate=November 10, 2007}}</ref> Linda Cook from ''[[Quad-City Times]]'' gave it a positive review and said \"The twists and turns are deadly, the 'lessons' are taught once again, and we have the perfect setup for ''[[Saw V]]''.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/articles/1685629/theres_more_gore_in_store_now_heres_saw_iv|title=Saw IV (2007)|accessdate=2007-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe Unrated Director's Cut was released on January 22, 2008 in America and March 3, 2008 in the UK, on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]]. An \"Extreme Edition\" was released in the United Kingdom only, before the release of ''[[Saw V]]'' in October 2008,<ref name= \"ukextreme\">[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/13715 Coolest DVD Packing Ever For UK 'Saw IV' Release]</ref><ref>{{YouTube|1mcZrL4u0xI|SAW IV DVD Extreme Limited Edition - WHAT DOES THE DVD DO? }}</ref> and features a 95-minute running time of the film. This version of the film matches the unrated version released in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdcompare.net/comparisons/film.php?fid=13812 |title=Rewind @ www.dvdcompare.net - Saw IV (2007)}}</ref> (since the BBFC have to classify every film by law, the term 'unrated' is not permitted on UK home video releases).\n\n===Extreme Limited Edition===\nThis edition was only released in the United Kingdom.<ref name= \"ukextreme\"/>\n* Exclusive automated spinning Saw with a sound clip packaging\n* A copy of the ''[[List of Saw media#Saw: Rebirth|Saw: Rebirth]]'' comic\n* Two [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]] (one with director Darren Lynn Bousman and actor Lyriq Bent; the other featuring the producers)\n* Video diary of Darren Lynn Bousman\n* Traps of ''Saw IV''\n* Props of ''Saw IV''\n* Music Video \"[[I.V. (X Japan song)|I.V.]]\" by [[X Japan]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Saw IV (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack was released on October 23, 2007 by [[Warner Records|WEA/Warner Bros. Records]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0890870}}\n* {{metacritic film|id=saw4}}\n* {{mojo title|id=saw4}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=saw_4}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 4}}\n[[Category:Saw films|4]]\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:2007 horror films]]\n[[Category:2000s sequel films]]\n[[Category:2000s serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Canadian splatter films]]\n[[Category:Canadian sequel films]]\n[[Category:Canadian serial killer films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Saw IV\n| image = Saw4final.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| producers = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Gregg Hoffman]]\n* [[Oren Koules]]\n* [[Mark Burg]]\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Patrick Melton]]\n* [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n}}\n| story = {{Plainlist|\n* Patrick Melton\n* Marcus Dunstan\n* [[Thomas Fenton]]\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Lyriq Bent]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]]\n* [[Justin Louis]] \n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]]\n}}<!--DO NOT CHANGE THIS CAST, THIS IS ACCORDING TO THE CREDIT BLOCK ON THE POSTER!-->\n| music = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = David A. Armstrong\n| editing = [[Kevin Greutert]]</br>Brett Sullivan\n| studio = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released = {{Film date|2007|10|26|United States}}\n| runtime = 92 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 92:26--><ref>{{cite web | url=http://bbfc.co.uk/releases/saw-iv-2 | title=''Saw IV'' (18) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=October 11, 2007 | accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| country = {{Plainlist|\n* United States\n* Canada\n}}\n| language = English\n| budget = $10 million\n| gross = $139.4 million<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw4.htm|title=Saw IV (2007)|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=2008-01-04}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Saw IV''''' is a 2007 [[horror film]] directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] from a screenplay by [[Patrick Melton]] and [[Marcus Dunstan]], and a story by Melton, Dunstan, and [[Thomas Fenton]]. It is the fourth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]], the third directed by Bousman. The film stars [[Lyriq Bent]], [[Costas Mandylor]], [[Scott Patterson]], [[Tobin Bell]], [[Betsy Russell]], [[Athena Karkanis]], [[Justin Louis]], and [[Donnie Wahlberg]].\n\nThe film continues the story of the [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw Killer]]'s obsession with teaching people the value of their lives and occurs roughly at the same time as the [[Saw III|previous installment]]. Despite Jigsaw's death, the film focuses on his ability to manipulate people into continuing his work. The story follows Officer Daniel Rigg being put through a series of tests in order to try to let go of his obsession with saving everyone, while at the same time attempting to save his partner.\n\nThe film was released in the United States on October 26, 2007, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. It received generally negative reviews from critics. Despite this, the film was a box office success, grossing $139 million worldwide. A sequel, titled ''[[Saw V]]'', was released in 2008.\n\n==Plot==\nA wax-coated [[microcassette]] is found in [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]'s stomach during his autopsy, and reveals to Detective [[Mark Hoffman]] that, despite his death, the games will continue and he will be tested. Elsewhere, two men \u2013 one with his eyes sewn shut, the other with his mouth sewn shut \u2013 awaken in a [[mausoleum]], chained at the neck to a winch. The blinded man panics and activates the winch before attacking the muted man, who kills him to get a key from his collar to free himself.\n\nFour days after [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Allison Kerry's]] death in the previous film, a [[SWAT]] team led by Hoffman and Officer [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Daniel Rigg]] find her body, and Hoffman warns Rigg against breaking through an unsecured door to reach her. The scene is also investigated by Agents [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Peter Strahm]] and [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Lindsey Perez]], Kerry's FBI contacts, who received a message and key from her. Noting John and [[Amanda Young]]'s physical limitations, Strahm speculates that a third accomplice was involved and soon becomes suspicious of Rigg, who has developed an obsession with saving people in the six months since the disappearance of detective [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Eric Matthews]]. That night, Rigg is attacked in his home; he awakens and watches a video from Jigsaw, which is where he learns that Eric is still alive and has ninety minutes to save himself, with Hoffman's life at risk as well. Meanwhile, he must play his own game in order to face and overcome his obsession.\n\nRigg finds a pimp named Brenda bound to a chair in his living room, and accidentally activates the trap, which slowly tears her scalp off. He manages to free her, but kills her in self-defense when she attacks him with a knife in order to evade arrest. Rigg is then led to a motel and instructed to abduct the owner, Ivan Landsness, who Rigg learns is a serial rapist. He forces Ivan into a trap, which requires Ivan to blind both of his eyes as payment for photographing and videotaping his crimes, in order to escape. However, Ivan only blinds one of his eyes, and the trap dismembers him.\n\nNext, Rigg is led to a school where he once investigated the abuse of a young student, committed by her father but not proven. Rigg finds that the student\u2019s parents are impaled by metal spikes: Rex, who has already died from blood loss, and his also abused wife Morgan, who has remained alive at his expense by pulling the spikes from both of their bodies. The spikes were flesh wounds for Morgan but crucial arteries for Rex. Rigg gives her a key to free herself then turns on a fire alarm and goes to the location of his final test.\n\nWhile investigating Rigg's apartment, the agents find a clue that leads them to [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]], John's ex-wife. Jill reveals that John worked in civil engineering and property development, and she miscarried her son Gideon after seven months when Cecil Adams, a drug addict, slammed a door into her stomach while robbing her rehab clinic. The loss of their son destroyed their marriage and made John become insane and develop his life tests. At the motel, the agents learn that the room was rented out to a lawyer named Art Blank, John's partner from his previous work and the survivor of the mausoleum trap from the beginning of the film, who vanished two weeks prior. Art is revealed to be the man overseeing the current game when he hands Eric a gun. At the school, the agents learn that all three victims, along with Jill, were Art's clients. Strahm and Perez find a puppet and a tape recorder in another room, which plays a cryptic message for Perez and the forecast that Strahm will kill an innocent person. Its face explodes and sends shrapnel into Perez' face. After she is hospitalized, Strahm furiously questions Jill. He learns how John ended his work with Art after falling into his depression, and that Cecil became the first victim of John's \"games\". Strahm connects her story and a prior clue to the Gideon Meatpacking Plant, the location of Rigg's final test.\n\nStrahm arrives after Rigg, but ends up following [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff Denlon]], the protagonist in ''[[Saw III]]''. He finds him in the sickroom from the previous film, with the dead corpses of John, Amanda and others lying around, and is forced to kill Jeff in self-defense when he demands his daughter back. It now becomes clear that this happened only moments after Jeff had killed John and Amanda in ''Saw III''. Meanwhile, Art pulls out a device which will free him, Eric, and Hoffman once the timer expires; if used before then, a pair of pincers will sever his spine. Rigg finds them and is yelled at and ultimately shot by Eric to prevent him from entering the room too early, but as he breaks in with one second to spare, two overhead ice blocks are released that swing down and crush Eric's head, killing him. Rigg shoots and kills Art, believing he is responsible for the game, only to learn from Art's tape recorder that his interference and continued obsession to save people, while they should have saved themselves, caused Eric's death. Hoffman, the actual accomplice, releases himself from the chair, but leaves Rigg to die. He then seals Strahm in the sickroom, and leaves the plant. The scene then cuts to Hoffman at the morgue, revealing that John's autopsy took place ''after'' the events of the film.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n{{div col begin}}\n* [[Lyriq Bent]] as [[List of Saw characters#Daniel Rigg|Officer Daniel Rigg]]\n* [[Scott Patterson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Peter Strahm|Agent Peter Strahm]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]]\n* [[Costas Mandylor]] as [[Mark Hoffman|Detective Mark Hoffman]]\n* [[Betsy Russell]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jill Tuck|Jill Tuck]]\n* [[Athena Karkanis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lindsey Perez|Agent Lindsey Perez]]\n* [[Louis Ferreira|Justin Louis]] as [[List of Saw characters#Art Blank|Art Blank]]\n* Simon Reynolds as Officer Lamanna\n* [[Donnie Wahlberg]] as [[Eric Matthews (Saw)|Detective Eric Matthews]]\n* [[Angus Macfadyen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jeff Denlon|Jeff]]\n* [[Shawnee Smith]] as [[Amanda Young]]\n* [[Bahar Soomekh]] as [[List of Saw characters#Lynn Denlon|Lynn Denlon]]\n* [[Dina Meyer]] as [[List of Saw characters#Allison Kerry|Detective Kerry]]\n* Mike Realba as [[List of Saw characters#Fisk|Detective Fisk]]\n* [[Marty Adams]] as [[List of Saw characters#Ivan Landsness|Ivan Landsness]]\n* Sarain Boylan as [[List of Saw characters#Brenda|Brenda]]\n* Billy Otis as [[List of Saw characters#Cecil Adams|Cecil Adams]]\n* James Van Patten as [[List of Saw characters#Adam Heffner|Dr. Heffner]]\n* Kevin Rushton as [[List of Saw characters#Trevor|Trevor]]\n* [[Julian Richings]] as Vagrant\n* Ingrid Hart as [[List of Saw characters#Tracy Rigg|Tracy Rigg]]\n* [[Niamh Wilson]] as [[List of Saw characters#Corbett Denlon|Corbett Denlon]]\n* [[Janet Land]] as [[List of Saw characters#Morgan and Rex|Morgan]]\n* [[Ron Lea]] as [[List of Saw characters#Morgan and Rex|Rex]]\n* [[Tony Nappo]] as [[List of Saw characters#Gus Colyard|Gus]]\n* [[Emmanuelle Vaugier]] as [[List of Saw characters#Addison Corday|Addison]]\n* [[Noam Jenkins]] as [[List of Saw characters#Michael Marks|Michael]]\n* Mike Butters as [[List of Saw characters#Paul Leahy|Paul]]\n* [[J. Larose]] as [[List of Saw characters#Troy|Troy]]\n* [[Oren Koules]] as [[List of Saw characters#Donnie Greco|Donnie Greco]]\n* Alison Luther as Jane\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n''Saw IV\u2019''s writers were Thomas Fenton, Marcus Dunstan, and Patrick Melton.<ref>[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7904 Actual writer for ''Saw IV'' revealed] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402181539/http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/7904 |date=April 2, 2007 }}</ref> There was also a hunt for a director before it was officially stated that [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], who had originally passed on it, would again direct the fourth installment, with creators and executive producers [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]] also returning.<ref>[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=18996 Bousman Returns to Direct Saw IV.] ComingSoon.net, 2007-02-20.</ref><ref name=\"MObousman\">[http://www.moviesonline.ca/movienews_12255.html Darren Lynn Bousman Interview, SAW 4.] Movies Online. Retrieved 2007-06-22.</ref> [[Principal photography]] took from April 16, 2007<ref>[http://www.canmag.com/nw/6815-saw-iv-production Date set for filming]</ref> to May 3, 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.omdc.on.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=6269|title=Production in Ontario 2007|publisher=Ontario Media Development Corporation|format=pdf|accessdate=September 4, 2010|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5sVbGTLqR?url=http://www.omdc.on.ca/AssetFactory.aspx?did=6269|url-status=live|archivedate=September 5, 2010}}</ref> The filming location was [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]];<ref>[http://www.entertainmentwise.com/news?id=28315 Location set for the filming of ''Saw IV'']</ref> the same place where both ''[[Saw II]]''<ref>[http://www.movieweb.com/news/01/9701.php/ ''Saw II'' filming location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070712101207/http://www.movieweb.com/news/01/9701.php |date=July 12, 2007 }} [[MovieWeb]] retrieved 2005-27-10.</ref> and ''[[Saw III]]''<ref>[http://www.movieweb.com/news/27/12127.php/ ''Saw III'' filming location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070623042041/http://www.movieweb.com/news/27/12127.php |date=June 23, 2007 }} [[MovieWeb]] retrieved 2006-04-17.</ref> were filmed. The post-production period began on 19 May.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0890870/combined IMDb post-production period]</ref>\n\nIn an interview with Bousman, he stated that the last work on ''Saw IV'' would happen in August to be able to have prints made.<ref name=\"MObousman\"/> At [[San Diego Comic-Con|Comic Con Intermeational]] 2007, it was revealed by Bousman and producer [[Mark Burg]] that the MPAA had given the film an NC-17 rating. They would have to figure out whether or not to cut the film to achieve an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|R rating]] or release it as an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|NC-17]] film,<ref>[http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=22826 Saw IV Too Much for Comic-Con] Retrieved on 2007-08-07</ref> the former of which they accomplished.<ref>[http://www.filmratings.com/filmRatings_cara/reports/s10166925.htm]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] held its fourth annual \u201cGive Til It Hurts\u201d [[Blood donation|blood drive]] for the [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|title=American Red Cross Partners With Lionsgate on SAW IV Blood Drive|publisher=[[Red Cross]]|date=August 6, 2007|accessdate=September 12, 2011|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61eiTSBkv?url=http://www.redcross.org/portal/site/en/menuitem.94aae335470e233f6cf911df43181aa0/?vgnextoid=d45cc92887b6b110VgnVCM10000089f0870aRCRD|url-status=live|archivedate=September 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\nThe film grossed $63,300,095 in the United States and an additional $71,228,814 internationally, bringing the theatrical total to $134,528,909.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/2007/SAW4.php |title=Saw IV (2007) - Box Office |accessdate=2009-11-02 |publisher=The Numbers}}</ref> It is Lionsgate's sixth highest-grossing film in the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/studio/chart/?studio=lionsgate.htm|title=Lionsgate All Time Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=September 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical reception===\nCritical reception to ''Saw IV'' was negative. [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports an approval rating of 20% based on 81 reviews, with an average score of 3.8/10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV (2007)|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=2019-06-29}}</ref> The site's consensus states: \u201c''Saw IV'' is more disturbing than compelling, with material already seen in the prior installments.\u201d On [[Metacritic]], the film has an average score of 36 out of 100, based on 16 reviews, indicating \"Generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/film/titles/saw4 |title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews |accessdate=2007-11-06 |publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n\nScott Schueller from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called it \u201ca film as edgy as a rubber knife\u201d and said that \u201cif the terrible craft of Bousman's film doesn\u2019t turn your stomach, the borderline pornographic violence will. It\u2019s disconcerting to imagine anyone enjoying the vile filth splashing the screen.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-saw-iv/243237/content |title=Movie review: 'Saw IV' |accessdate=2007-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127082238/http://chicago.metromix.com/movies/movie_review/movie-review-saw-iv/243237/content |archivedate=November 27, 2007 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Frank Scheck from ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said \u201cthe famously inventive torture sequences here seem depleted of imagination\u201d, but added that \u201cit hasn\u2019t yet [[Jumping the shark|jumped the shark]] like such predecessors as the ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' and ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)|Friday the 13th]]'' movies eventually did.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film/reviews/article_display.jsp?&rid=10102 |title=Saw IV |accessdate=2007-11-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028145921/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/hr/film/reviews/article_display.jsp?&rid=10102 |archivedate=October 28, 2007 }}</ref> Peter Hartlaub from ''[[San Francisco Chronicle|The San Francisco Chronicle]]'' called it \u201cthe ''[[Syriana]]'' of slasher films, so complicated and circuitous that your only hope of understanding everything is to eat lots of fish the night before and then watch each of the previous films, in order, right before you enter the theater.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/10/29/DD4OT1N6U.DTL&type=movies |title=Review: The hunt for the Jigsaw Killer continues in 'Saw IV' |accessdate=2007-11-10 | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | first=Peter | last=Hartlaub | date=2007-10-29}}</ref> [[James Berardinelli]] wrote that \u201c''Saw IV'' functions as a drawn-out, tedious epilogue to a series that began with an energetic bang three years ago with ''Saw'', then progressively lost momentum, coherence, and intelligence with each successive annual installment.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/movies/s/saw4.html|title=Saw IV|accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref>\n\nA less negative review came from Jamie Russell from the [[BBC]], who called it \"deeply unsettling; just like a horror movie should be.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2007/10/22/saw_iv_2007_review.shtml |title=Saw IV (2007) |accessdate=November 10, 2007}}</ref> Linda Cook from ''[[Quad-City Times]]'' gave it a positive review and said \"The twists and turns are deadly, the 'lessons' are taught once again, and we have the perfect setup for ''[[Saw V]]''.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/articles/1685629/theres_more_gore_in_store_now_heres_saw_iv|title=Saw IV (2007)|accessdate=2007-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe Unrated Director's Cut was released on January 22, 2008 in America and March 3, 2008 in the UK, on [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]]. An \"Extreme Edition\" was released in the United Kingdom only, before the release of ''[[Saw V]]'' in October 2008,<ref name= \"ukextreme\">[http://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/13715 Coolest DVD Packing Ever For UK 'Saw IV' Release]</ref><ref>{{YouTube|1mcZrL4u0xI|SAW IV DVD Extreme Limited Edition - WHAT DOES THE DVD DO? }}</ref> and features a 95-minute running time of the film. This version of the film matches the unrated version released in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dvdcompare.net/comparisons/film.php?fid=13812 |title=Rewind @ www.dvdcompare.net - Saw IV (2007)}}</ref> (since the BBFC have to classify every film by law, the term 'unrated' is not permitted on UK home video releases).\n\n===Extreme Limited Edition===\nThis edition was only released in the United Kingdom.<ref name= \"ukextreme\"/>\n* Exclusive automated spinning Saw with a sound clip packaging\n* A copy of the ''[[List of Saw media#Saw: Rebirth|Saw: Rebirth]]'' comic\n* Two [[Audio commentary|audio commentaries]] (one with director Darren Lynn Bousman and actor Lyriq Bent; the other featuring the producers)\n* Video diary of Darren Lynn Bousman\n* Traps of ''Saw IV''\n* Props of ''Saw IV''\n* Music Video \"[[I.V. (X Japan song)|I.V.]]\" by [[X Japan]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Saw IV (soundtrack)}}\nThe soundtrack was released on October 23, 2007 by [[Warner Records|WEA/Warner Bros. Records]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0890870}}\n* {{metacritic film|id=saw4}}\n* {{mojo title|id=saw4}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=saw_4}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Darren Lynn Bousman}}\n{{Marcus Dunstan & Patrick Melton}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saw 4}}\n[[Category:Saw films|4]]\n