{"title_page": "Jigsaw (2017 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 film by Spierig brothers}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}} \n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Jigsaw\n| image          = Jigsaw 2017 poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael Spierig<br>Peter Spierig]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Gregg Hoffman]]|[[Oren Koules]]|[[Mark Burg]]|}}\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Josh Stolberg]]|Peter Goldfinger}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Matt Passmore]]|[[Callum Keith Rennie]]|[[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]]|Hannah Emily Anderson}}|\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = Ben Nott<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Niel|title='JIGSAW' TRAILER: THE 'SAW' FRANCHISE LIVES ON|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/jigsaw-trailer/|website=[[Film School Rejects]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Kevin Greutert]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alexander|first1=Chris|title=Jackals Review|url=https://comingsoon.net/horror/reviews/881315-jackals-review|website=[[CraveOnline#Owned or associated websites|ComingSoon.net]]|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|10|27|United States|}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes<ref name=\"18cert\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jigsaw-film-0 | title=JIGSAW | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]}} Retrieved August 22, 2017</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n| gross          = $102.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Jigsaw''''' is a 2017 American [[horror film]] directed by [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]] and written by [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger. It is the eighth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars <!-- Casting is per the billing block. Do NOT change. -->[[Matt Passmore]], [[Callum Keith Rennie]], [[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]], and Hannah Emily Anderson. The film picks up over a decade after the death of the eponymous [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw killer]], during the police investigation of a new succession of murders that fit his ''[[modus operandi]]''.\n\n2010's ''[[Saw 3D]]'' was originally deemed the final installment of the series, before [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] commissioned the production of ''Jigsaw'' from a pitch by Stolberg and Goldfinger.\n\nFilming began in November 2016, with post-production following in January. The film was released in the United States on October 27, 2017, by Lionsgate. ''Jigsaw'' received mostly unfavorable reviews<!-- The Metacritic rating states \"unfavorable reviews\". There is no source for \"Mixed reviews\". --> from critics but was a commercial success, grossing $102.9 million worldwide against a $10 million budget.\n\n==Plot==\nTen years after [[Saw III|the death of John Kramer]], criminal Edgar Munsen is shot and apprehended by Detectives Hunt and Halloran after activating a [[Triggering device|remote trigger]]. Meanwhile, five people \u2013 Mitch, Anna, Ryan, Carly, and an unconscious man \u2013 are held captive in a barn with chains around their necks. A tape recording from John Kramer explains they must give a sacrifice of blood and confess their sins. The chains pull them towards a wall of buzzsaws. Most of the group survive by cutting themselves to offer blood, but the unconscious man awakens too late to escape.\n\nTheir next test reveals that Carly is a [[theft|purse snatcher]], who accidentally caused the death of an [[Asthma|asthmatic woman]]. To save the others from being [[Hanging|hanged]], she must inject herself with one of three needles \u2013 one containing an antidote to a [[poison]] in her system, one containing [[Saline (medicine)|saline]], and one containing [[acid]]. She refuses, so Ryan stabs her with all three to save himself, killing her.\n\nHalloran and Detective Hunt investigate the discovery of bodies that appear to be the unconscious man and Carly. Halloran becomes suspicious of [[pathology|pathologists]] Logan Nelson, who is a [[veteran]] and former doctor whose wife was killed two years prior, and Eleanor Bonneville. Later, Munsen goes missing from the hospital. His body is found inside John's grave when it is exhumed by the police.\n\nRyan attempts to escape through a door with the words \"No Exit\" on it, but his leg crashes through loose floorboards, and is ensnared by wires. A tape recorder found next to his leg reveal that he is being punished for breaking the rules and that he must pull a lever to sever his leg and be \"set free\". Exploring the room, Anna and Mitch walk inside a [[silo]] and are trapped inside. A recording reveals they will be killed unless Ryan pulls the lever. Ryan pulls the lever, severing his leg, while saving Anna and Mitch.\n\nEleanor reveals to Logan that she is a [[fandom|fangirl]] of the Jigsaw case, and has built replicas of many of his traps in her [[studio]]. She is worried this might incriminate her. Hunt follows them and informs Halloran.\n\nThe next test reveals Mitch sold a [[motorcycle]] with a faulty brake to John's nephew, resulting in his death. Mitch will be killed by a spiral-shaped blade unless he can reach a [[Parking brake|brake]]. Anna attempts to help him, but he is killed. Halloran finds a corpse appearing to be Mitch in Eleanor\u2019s studio and calls for Logan and Eleanor\u2019s arrest.\n\nLogan convinces Hunt to let them go, as both suspect Halloran. Eleanor deduces the game's location and she and Logan depart for the barn. Halloran pursues them. Meanwhile, Hunt finds pieces of flesh in Halloran's freezer, fitting Jigsaw's [[Modus operandi|M.O.]] and implicating Halloran as the killer.\n\nAnna is drugged while attempting to escape, and awakens to find herself and Ryan chained in a room with a still-living John Kramer. John reveals that Anna [[Infanticide|suffocated her baby]] and [[Frameup|framed her husband]] while Ryan caused the death of several friends in a car accident. John tells them they have gotten his message backwards. He places a shotgun between them and tells them it is the key to their survival. Anna attempts to shoot Ryan, but the gun [[Booby trap|backfires and kills her]]. Ryan realizes that the keys to his and Anna's chains were in the gun and were destroyed when Anna fired it, leaving him to die.\n\nLogan and Eleanor are ambushed by Halloran at the barn. Eleanor escapes, while Halloran is drugged by an unseen assailant. Logan and Halloran awaken in collars rigged with [[Laser cutting|laser cutters]]. They are told to confess their sins to survive and may choose who goes first. Halloran forces Logan to go first. Logan confesses that he mislabeled John's x-rays years prior, causing his [[cancer]] to go undiagnosed. Despite confessing, Logan is killed. Then, Halloran admits to allowing criminals to walk free for personal gain and his collar deactivates.\n\nLogan reveals that he is still alive and that the barn games occurred [[Nonlinear narrative|ten years prior]]. He was the man who appeared to die in the first game, but John, having decided Logan shouldn't die over an honest mistake, saved him and recruited him as his first [[Apprenticeship|apprentice]]. The bodies that were found were actually the bodies of criminals Halloran allowed to walk free, which Logan placed into the same tests that took place at Tuck's Pig Farm ten years ago. Logan also reveals that Munsen, one of the criminals Halloran let go, killed his wife. However, because Halloran broke the rules and forced Logan to go first, he will die and be framed as the killer. Logan reactivates the collar around Halloran's neck, killing him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Matt Passmore]] as [[List of Saw characters#Logan Nelson|Logan Nelson]]\n* [[Callum Keith Rennie]] as [[List of Saw characters#Detective Halloran|Detective Halloran]]\n* [[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]] as [[List of Saw characters#Detective Keith Hunt|Detective Keith Hunt]]\n* Hannah Emily Anderson as [[List of Saw characters#Eleanor Bonneville|Eleanor Bonneville]]\n* [[Laura Vandervoort]] as [[List of Saw characters#Anna|Anna]]\n* [[Paul Braunstein]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jigsaw|Ryan]]\n* [[Mandela Van Peebles]] as [[List of Saw characters#Mitch|Mitch]]\n* [[Brittany Allen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carly|Carly]]\n* Josiah Black as [[List of Saw characters#Edgar Munsen|Edgar Munsen]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer / Jigsaw]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n''[[Saw 3D]]'' was intended to be the final ''Saw'' film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-22-saw22_ST_N.htm|title='Saw 3D' will be the final cut for horror franchise|last1=Bowles|first1=Scott|date=July 22, 2010|website=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett]]|accessdate=February 18, 2016}}</ref> The film was set to be split into two parts, but [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] only allowed the filmmakers to make one more film after ''[[Saw VI]]'' under-performed at the box office. According to ''Saw 3D'' writers [[Marcus Dunstan]] and [[Patrick Melton]], because of the change, \"the big reveal of [[List of Saw characters#Lawrence Gordon|Dr. Gordon]] was a bit underserved&nbsp;... perhaps creating more questions than answers. There were several ideas [we] never quite figured out. But [I] don't want to say what they were, because you never know what might happen in the future.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404119/previous-saw-entry-supposed-split-two-exclusive/|title=The Previous 'SAW' Entry Was Supposed to Be Split in Two! (Exclusive)|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the intended conclusion, Lionsgate ceased making ''Saw'' films, while waiting to hear a pitch that they thought made it worthwhile to resurrect the series. ''Jigsaw'' was conceived when writers [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger, who had spent two years pursuing the opportunity to write a ''Saw'' entry, proposed their vision.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3379148/saw-lionsgate-begins-developing-next-sequel-legacy/|title='Saw': Lionsgate Begins Developing Next Sequel, 'Legacy'|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=February 8, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/904188250108993536|title=The studio was waiting to hear a pitch that they thought made it worth it to bring back the franchise.  Pete and I spent two years--|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=2 September 2017|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=3 September 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903184745/https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/904188250108993536|archivedate=September 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It became known in July 2016 that brothers [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]] would direct the film.<ref name=\"Release1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/07/ryan-reynolds-the-hitmans-bodyguard-saw-horror-movie-lionsgate-release-dates-1201786247/|title=Lionsgate Dates New 'Saw' Movie & Ryan Reynolds Action Comedy 'The Hitman's Bodyguard'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=July 13, 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/popculturenow/2016/07/14/saw-legacy-gets-a-release-date/|title=Saw: Legacy Gets A Release Date|last=Lovett|first=Jamie|date=July 14, 2016|work=ComicBook.com|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref> The producers [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] had also produced the previous entries in the ''Saw'' series.<ref name=\"cast2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/mandela-van-peebles-saw-legacy-frank-cassini-volition-1201897430/|title='Mandela Van Peebles cast in 'Saw: Legacy'|last1=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|date=January 30, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> Composer [[Charlie Clouser]] has described the film as a \"reinvention\" of the series, opining that \"the Spierig brothers can deliver a fresh take on the material that will establish a new story line and new characters that can carry the saga into the future\".<ref name=\"Composer\">{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/saw-legacy-be-scored-by-936030|title='Saw: Legacy' to Be Scored by Franchise Veteran Charlie Clouser (Exclusive)|last=Couch|first=Aaron|date=October 7, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 7, 2016}}</ref> The directors further detailed their approach as being \"''Saw'' for 2017\", and Michael Spierig explained, \"It's perhaps not quite as vicious, and more fun. But it's still full of gore, that's for sure. It's got a really great mystery, and there are very interesting twists\".<ref name=\"EW First look\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/07/13/jigsaw-first-look-saw/|title=Jigsaw first look: Directors tease next installment in Saw saga|last1=Collis|first1=Clark|date=July 13, 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn October 2016, production was confirmed to have commenced under the working title of ''Saw: Legacy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3408599/saw-legacy-production-beginning-exclusive/|title='Saw: Legacy': Production Beginning (Exclusive)|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=October 1, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> The film was shot in [[Toronto]] in November 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dailyhive.com/toronto/movies-tv-series-filming-toronto-2016 |title=7 major movies and TV series filming in Toronto right now |first=Lloyd |last=Braun |work=[[Daily Hive]] |date=November 16, 2016 |access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref> and entered post-production by January.<ref name=\"cast2\" /> On March 2, 2017, ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' revealed the first plot details and a full actor list, confirming that Tobin Bell would return in the role of [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]].<ref name=\"PlotTobin\">{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3426678/exclusive-weve-got-first-saw-legacy-plot-details-tobin-bell-returning/|title=[Exclusive] We've Got the First 'Saw: Legacy' Plot Details; Tobin Bell Returning!|last1=Squires|first1=John|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] listed the film under the official title of ''Jigsaw'', rating it R, for \"sequences of grisly bloody violence and torture, and for language\".<ref name=\"RatingTitle\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=jigsaw&x=0&y=0| title=Jigsaw (2017) | work=The Classification and Rating Adiministration | publisher=[[Motion Picture Association of America]] | accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref> On August 14, 2017, the film passed uncut in the United Kingdom with an [[18 (British Board of Film Classification)|18 Certificate]] by the BBFC.<ref name=\"RatingTitle\" /><ref name=\"18cert\" /> In regard to the new title, writer Josh Stolberg clarified that \"when a writer is writing a movie, they put something on the cover page to separate it from other films. So when we were writing this film, the title read ''Saw: Legacy'' but it was never official or 'decided'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/890407708003770369|title=So when we're were writing this film, the title read \"Saw: Legacy\" but it was never official or \"decided\". (3/3)|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=13 July 2017|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=27 July 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727065404/https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/890407708003770369|archivedate=July 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n\n===Poster releases===\nOn September 16, 2017, [[Lionsgate]] released five posters to promote ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.showbizjunkies.com/movies/jigsaw-character-posters/|title='Jigsaw' Unveils New Jigsaw's Army Character Posters|last=Murray|first=Rebecca|date=September 15, 2017|work=Showbiz Junkies|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The posters show off people in the traditional [[Billy the Puppet]] makeup, captioned \"He is Everything. He is Everywhere. He is Everyone\". The release of the posters was Lionsgate's way of reasserting the series' dominance over the Halloween season.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/09/15/jigsaw-will-open-in-imax-and-may-send-saw-over-the-1-billion-mark/#1a8687338a2d|title='Jigsaw' Will Open In IMAX And May Send 'Saw' Over The $1 Billion Mark|last=Meldelson|first=Scott|date=September 15, 2017|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Halloween Blood Drive===\nThe Annual Blood Drive is the series' tradition, where before the release of the films in October, mobile blood stations are set up around the United States, where fans who donate blood receive a free ticket to see the respective film of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/253468/jigsaws-nurses-back-saw-blood-drive/|title=Jigsaw's Nurses Are Back With the Saw Blood Drive|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Dread Central]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The tradition started in 2004, after the overwhelming success of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', and continued for each of the sequels until it stopped in 2009 before the release of ''[[Saw VI]]''. Due to the arrival of ''Jigsaw'' in October, the blood drive was revived for another year, promoting the film with eight posters released by [[Lionsgate]], featuring \"Nurses\" [[Grae Drake]], Dan Rockwell, [[Susanne Bartsch|Susanne Bartch]], [[Nyakim Gatwech]], [[Shaun Ross (model)|Shaun Ross]], [[Mosh (model)|Mosh]], Mykie, and [[Amanda Lepore|Amanda LePore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jigsaw-movie-posters-nurses-saw-8-blood-drive/|title=New Saw 8 Posters Unleash Jigsaw's Blood-Starved Nurses|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=September 25, 2017|website=[[MovieWeb]]|accessdate=September 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 25, 2017, 120,000 pints (57,000 L) of blood had been donated, which has led to over 360,000 lives being saved.<ref>https://movieweb.com/jigsaw-movie-posters-nurses-saw-8-blood-drive/</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[Charlie Clouser]], who provided the score for all previous entries in the ''Saw'' series, returned to score ''Jigsaw''. Clouser re-imagined the music of the ''Saw'' franchise, following the six year hiatus between ''Saw 3D'' and ''Jigsaw''. Clouser stated in 2016, \"this will be an opportunity [for me] to re-imagine how [I] approach the score, and [I] will be trying a more stark, bold, and stripped-down approach that will be more in line with the strong vision that the Spierig brothers are bringing to the table\".<ref name=\"Composer\" /> The soundtrack of the film was distributed digitally on October 27, 2017. Some tracks from the film can also be found on Volume 2 of the ''Saw'' Anthology Collection.\n\n==Release==\n''Jigsaw'' was released in the United Kingdom on October 26, 2017, and in the United States theatrically on October 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/saw-8-jigsaw-release-date-trailer-halloween-serial-killer-tobin-bell-a7801241.html|title='Saw 8' release date announced: Horror franchise to return with 'Jigsaw'|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|date=June 21, 2017|work=|accessdate=August 13, 2017|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> It was featured in [[IMAX]] screenings for the first week of its theatrical run.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Box office===\n''Jigsaw'' has grossed $38.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $64.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $102.9 million, against a production budget of $10 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2017.htm|title=Jigsaw (2017)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Jigsaw'' was released alongside ''[[Thank You for Your Service (2017 film)|Thank You for Your Service]]'' and ''[[Suburbicon]]'', and is projected to gross around $20 million from 2,941 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/jigsaw-boo2-a-madea-halloween-george-clooney-suburbicon-box-office-weekend-preview-1202194368/|title=Jigsaw' Looks To Keep 'Saw' Franchise Sharp During Pre-Halloween Weekend With $20M+ Opening|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=October 25, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> It made $1.6 million from Thursday night previews at 2,400 theaters, just below the $1.7 million ''Saw 3D'' made from midnight screenings seven years prior, and $7.2 million on its first day. It went on to open to $16.64 million, finishing first at the box office but marking the second lowest debut of the franchise.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/jigsaw-george-clooney-suburbicon-madea-halloween-thank-you-for-your-service-1202196050/|title=Horror Has Few Scares At B.O. As 'Jigsaw' Dulls To $16M+, 'Suburbicon' Condemned With D- CinemaScore|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=October 29, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> In its second weekend the film dropped 61% to $6.56 million, finishing third behind newcomers ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' and ''[[A Bad Moms Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-a-bad-moms-christmas-huge-box-office-weekend-1202200942/|title='Thor: Ragnarok\u2019 Flexes His Box Office Muscles To $120M-$122M Opening \u2013 Early Sunday AM Update|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=November 6, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> In its third weekend, the film dropped another 47% and made $3.43 million, finishing fifth.\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 33% based on 87 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 4.76/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Jigsaw'' definitely won't win many converts to the ''Saw'' franchise, but for longtime fans, it should prove a respectably revolting\u2014if rarely scary\u2014diversion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|title=''Jigsaw'' (2017)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |accessdate=October 26, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|title=''Jigsaw'' reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported women under 25 (21% of the film's audience) and older males (30%) gave it a 76% and 70% overall positive score, respectively.<ref name=opening/>\n\n''[[IGN]]'' gave the film a score of 4.5/10, writing \"The good news is, ''Jigsaw'' is not the worst horror movie of the year. The bad news is, it's still bad enough that that's the good news...[It] doesn't capture what made the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' franchise]] work in the first place.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2017/10/27/jigsaw-review|title=Jigsaw Review|last=Bibbiani|first=William|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> Darren French of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\", calling it disappointing and overly long.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/10/27/jigsaw-is-a-bloody-mess-ew-review/|title=Jigsaw is a bloody mess: EW review|last=Franich|first=Darren|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' gave the film two and a half out of five, saying the film \"while being a fun ride, fails to justify its existence with a story that is overly familiar and a twist that doesn't live up to most of its predecessors\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3466635/review-jigsaw/|title=[Review] The Overly Familiar 'Jigsaw' Still Manages to Be Fun|last=Thurman|first=Trace|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s [[Owen Gleiberman]] found the film \"garishly rote\" saying \"For 92 minutes, it more or less succeeds in sawing through your boredom, slicing and dicing with a glum explicitness that raises the occasional tingle of gross-out suspense but no longer carries any kick of true shock value.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/jigsaw-review-tobin-bell-1202600173/|title=Film Review: 'Jigsaw'|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> Germain Lussier of ''[[io9]]'' largely panned the film saying \"[it] is one of the better films in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]]. Unfortunately, that's not saying much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/jigsaw-is-pretty-bad-which-still-makes-it-one-of-the-b-1819913359|title=Jigsaw Is Pretty Bad, Which Still Makes It One of the Better Saw Movies|last=Lussier|first=Germain|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[io9]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Jigsaw'' was released digitally on January 9, 2018, and on 4K [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[DVD]] on January 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3474074/trap-set-jigsaw-returns-4k-hd-blu-ray-dvd-digital-hd-exclusive/|title=The Trap is Set! \u2018Jigsaw\u2019 Returns On 4K HD, Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital HD! [Exclusive]|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=December 12, 2017|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|Spiral (2020 film)}}\n\nThe ninth installment of the ''Saw'' franchise known as ''Spiral'' is an upcoming American horror film that is the sequel to ''Jigsaw''. The sequel film,  directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], stars [[Chris Rock]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]]. Production took place in [[Toronto]] from July to August 2019. [[Lionsgate Films]] planned to release ''Spiral'' in theaters on May 15, 2020, however the film was pulled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/lionsgate-takes-antebellum-run-spiral-off-release-calendar-for-the-time-being-1202886268/|title=Lionsgate Takes \u2018Antebellum\u2019, \u2018Run\u2019 & \u2018Spiral\u2019 Off Release Calendar For The Time Being|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[List of horror films of the 2010s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|jigsawsaves.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|3348730}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Michael and Peter Spierig}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 horror films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 film by Spierig brothers}}\n{{Use American English|date = March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}} \n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Jigsaw\n| image          = Jigsaw 2017 poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael Spierig<br>Peter Spierig]]\n| producer       = {{ubl|[[Gregg Hoffman]]|[[Oren Koules]]|[[Mark Burg]]|}}\n| writer         = {{ubl|[[Josh Stolberg]]|Peter Goldfinger}}\n| starring       = {{ubl|[[Matt Passmore]]|[[Callum Keith Rennie]]|[[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]]|Hannah Emily Anderson}}|\n| music          = [[Charlie Clouser]]\n| cinematography = Ben Nott<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miller|first1=Niel|title='JIGSAW' TRAILER: THE 'SAW' FRANCHISE LIVES ON|url=https://filmschoolrejects.com/jigsaw-trailer/|website=[[Film School Rejects]]|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref>\n| editing        = [[Kevin Greutert]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alexander|first1=Chris|title=Jackals Review|url=https://comingsoon.net/horror/reviews/881315-jackals-review|website=[[CraveOnline#Owned or associated websites|ComingSoon.net]]|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>\n| studio         = [[Twisted Pictures]]\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|10|27|United States|}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes<ref name=\"18cert\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/jigsaw-film-0 | title=JIGSAW | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]]}} Retrieved August 22, 2017</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $10 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n| gross          = $102.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n}}\n'''''Jigsaw''''' is a 2017 American [[horror film]] directed by [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]] and written by [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger. It is the eighth installment in the [[Saw (film series)|''Saw'' film series]]. The film stars <!-- Casting is per the billing block. Do NOT change. -->[[Matt Passmore]], [[Callum Keith Rennie]], [[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]], and Hannah Emily Anderson. The film picks up over a decade after the death of the eponymous [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|Jigsaw killer]], during the police investigation of a new succession of murders that fit his ''[[modus operandi]]''.\n\n2010's ''[[Saw 3D]]'' was originally deemed the final installment of the series, before [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] commissioned the production of ''Jigsaw'' from a pitch by Stolberg and Goldfinger.\n\nFilming began in November 2016, with post-production following in January. The film was released in the United States on October 27, 2017, by Lionsgate. ''Jigsaw'' received mostly unfavorable reviews<!-- The Metacritic rating states \"unfavorable reviews\". There is no source for \"Mixed reviews\". --> from critics but was a commercial success, grossing $102.9 million worldwide against a $10 million budget.\n\n==Plot==\nTen years after [[Saw III|the death of John Kramer]], criminal Edgar Munsen is shot and apprehended by Detectives Hunt and Halloran after activating a [[Triggering device|remote trigger]]. Meanwhile, five people \u2013 Mitch, Anna, Ryan, Carly, and an unconscious man \u2013 are held captive in a barn with chains around their necks. A tape recording from John Kramer explains they must give a sacrifice of blood and confess their sins. The chains pull them towards a wall of buzzsaws. Most of the group survive by cutting themselves to offer blood, but the unconscious man awakens too late to escape.\n\nTheir next test reveals that Carly is a [[theft|purse snatcher]], who accidentally caused the death of an [[Asthma|asthmatic woman]]. To save the others from being [[Hanging|hanged]], she must inject herself with one of three needles \u2013 one containing an antidote to a [[poison]] in her system, one containing [[Saline (medicine)|saline]], and one containing [[acid]]. She refuses, so Ryan stabs her with all three to save himself, killing her.\n\nHalloran and Detective Hunt investigate the discovery of bodies that appear to be the unconscious man and Carly. Halloran becomes suspicious of [[pathology|pathologists]] Logan Nelson, who is a [[veteran]] and former doctor whose wife was killed two years prior, and Eleanor Bonneville. Later, Munsen goes missing from the hospital. His body is found inside John's grave when it is exhumed by the police.\n\nRyan attempts to escape through a door with the words \"No Exit\" on it, but his leg crashes through loose floorboards, and is ensnared by wires. A tape recorder found next to his leg reveal that he is being punished for breaking the rules and that he must pull a lever to sever his leg and be \"set free\". Exploring the room, Anna and Mitch walk inside a [[silo]] and are trapped inside. A recording reveals they will be killed unless Ryan pulls the lever. Ryan pulls the lever, severing his leg, while saving Anna and Mitch.\n\nEleanor reveals to Logan that she is a [[fandom|fangirl]] of the Jigsaw case, and has built replicas of many of his traps in her [[studio]]. She is worried this might incriminate her. Hunt follows them and informs Halloran.\n\nThe next test reveals Mitch sold a [[motorcycle]] with a faulty brake to John's nephew, resulting in his death. Mitch will be killed by a spiral-shaped blade unless he can reach a [[Parking brake|brake]]. Anna attempts to help him, but he is killed. Halloran finds a corpse appearing to be Mitch in Eleanor\u2019s studio and calls for Logan and Eleanor\u2019s arrest.\n\nLogan convinces Hunt to let them go, as both suspect Halloran. Eleanor deduces the game's location and she and Logan depart for the barn. Halloran pursues them. Meanwhile, Hunt finds pieces of flesh in Halloran's freezer, fitting Jigsaw's [[Modus operandi|M.O.]] and implicating Halloran as the killer.\n\nAnna is drugged while attempting to escape, and awakens to find herself and Ryan chained in a room with a still-living John Kramer. John reveals that Anna [[Infanticide|suffocated her baby]] and [[Frameup|framed her husband]] while Ryan caused the death of several friends in a car accident. John tells them they have gotten his message backwards. He places a shotgun between them and tells them it is the key to their survival. Anna attempts to shoot Ryan, but the gun [[Booby trap|backfires and kills her]]. Ryan realizes that the keys to his and Anna's chains were in the gun and were destroyed when Anna fired it, leaving him to die.\n\nLogan and Eleanor are ambushed by Halloran at the barn. Eleanor escapes, while Halloran is drugged by an unseen assailant. Logan and Halloran awaken in collars rigged with [[Laser cutting|laser cutters]]. They are told to confess their sins to survive and may choose who goes first. Halloran forces Logan to go first. Logan confesses that he mislabeled John's x-rays years prior, causing his [[cancer]] to go undiagnosed. Despite confessing, Logan is killed. Then, Halloran admits to allowing criminals to walk free for personal gain and his collar deactivates.\n\nLogan reveals that he is still alive and that the barn games occurred [[Nonlinear narrative|ten years prior]]. He was the man who appeared to die in the first game, but John, having decided Logan shouldn't die over an honest mistake, saved him and recruited him as his first [[Apprenticeship|apprentice]]. The bodies that were found were actually the bodies of criminals Halloran allowed to walk free, which Logan placed into the same tests that took place at Tuck's Pig Farm ten years ago. Logan also reveals that Munsen, one of the criminals Halloran let go, killed his wife. However, because Halloran broke the rules and forced Logan to go first, he will die and be framed as the killer. Logan reactivates the collar around Halloran's neck, killing him.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Details|topic=the cast and characters|List of Saw cast members|List of Saw characters}}\n* [[Matt Passmore]] as [[List of Saw characters#Logan Nelson|Logan Nelson]]\n* [[Callum Keith Rennie]] as [[List of Saw characters#Detective Halloran|Detective Halloran]]\n* [[Cl\u00e9 Bennett]] as [[List of Saw characters#Detective Keith Hunt|Detective Keith Hunt]]\n* Hannah Emily Anderson as [[List of Saw characters#Eleanor Bonneville|Eleanor Bonneville]]\n* [[Laura Vandervoort]] as [[List of Saw characters#Anna|Anna]]\n* [[Paul Braunstein]] as [[List of Saw characters#Jigsaw|Ryan]]\n* [[Mandela Van Peebles]] as [[List of Saw characters#Mitch|Mitch]]\n* [[Brittany Allen]] as [[List of Saw characters#Carly|Carly]]\n* Josiah Black as [[List of Saw characters#Edgar Munsen|Edgar Munsen]]\n* [[Tobin Bell]] as [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer / Jigsaw]]\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\n''[[Saw 3D]]'' was intended to be the final ''Saw'' film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-22-saw22_ST_N.htm|title='Saw 3D' will be the final cut for horror franchise|last1=Bowles|first1=Scott|date=July 22, 2010|website=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett]]|accessdate=February 18, 2016}}</ref> The film was set to be split into two parts, but [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]] only allowed the filmmakers to make one more film after ''[[Saw VI]]'' under-performed at the box office. According to ''Saw 3D'' writers [[Marcus Dunstan]] and [[Patrick Melton]], because of the change, \"the big reveal of [[List of Saw characters#Lawrence Gordon|Dr. Gordon]] was a bit underserved&nbsp;... perhaps creating more questions than answers. There were several ideas [we] never quite figured out. But [I] don't want to say what they were, because you never know what might happen in the future.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/exclusives/3404119/previous-saw-entry-supposed-split-two-exclusive/|title=The Previous 'SAW' Entry Was Supposed to Be Split in Two! (Exclusive)|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=August 24, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter the intended conclusion, Lionsgate ceased making ''Saw'' films, while waiting to hear a pitch that they thought made it worthwhile to resurrect the series. ''Jigsaw'' was conceived when writers [[Josh Stolberg]] and Peter Goldfinger, who had spent two years pursuing the opportunity to write a ''Saw'' entry, proposed their vision.<ref name=\"Development\">{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3379148/saw-lionsgate-begins-developing-next-sequel-legacy/|title='Saw': Lionsgate Begins Developing Next Sequel, 'Legacy'|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=February 8, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/904188250108993536|title=The studio was waiting to hear a pitch that they thought made it worth it to bring back the franchise.  Pete and I spent two years--|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=2 September 2017|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=3 September 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170903184745/https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/904188250108993536|archivedate=September 3, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It became known in July 2016 that brothers [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]] would direct the film.<ref name=\"Release1\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/07/ryan-reynolds-the-hitmans-bodyguard-saw-horror-movie-lionsgate-release-dates-1201786247/|title=Lionsgate Dates New 'Saw' Movie & Ryan Reynolds Action Comedy 'The Hitman's Bodyguard'|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=July 13, 2016|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/popculturenow/2016/07/14/saw-legacy-gets-a-release-date/|title=Saw: Legacy Gets A Release Date|last=Lovett|first=Jamie|date=July 14, 2016|work=ComicBook.com|accessdate=September 4, 2016}}</ref> The producers [[Mark Burg]] and [[Oren Koules]] had also produced the previous entries in the ''Saw'' series.<ref name=\"cast2\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/mandela-van-peebles-saw-legacy-frank-cassini-volition-1201897430/|title='Mandela Van Peebles cast in 'Saw: Legacy'|last1=N'Duka|first1=Amanda|date=January 30, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> Composer [[Charlie Clouser]] has described the film as a \"reinvention\" of the series, opining that \"the Spierig brothers can deliver a fresh take on the material that will establish a new story line and new characters that can carry the saga into the future\".<ref name=\"Composer\">{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/saw-legacy-be-scored-by-936030|title='Saw: Legacy' to Be Scored by Franchise Veteran Charlie Clouser (Exclusive)|last=Couch|first=Aaron|date=October 7, 2016|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=October 7, 2016}}</ref> The directors further detailed their approach as being \"''Saw'' for 2017\", and Michael Spierig explained, \"It's perhaps not quite as vicious, and more fun. But it's still full of gore, that's for sure. It's got a really great mystery, and there are very interesting twists\".<ref name=\"EW First look\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/07/13/jigsaw-first-look-saw/|title=Jigsaw first look: Directors tease next installment in Saw saga|last1=Collis|first1=Clark|date=July 13, 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|accessdate=July 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nIn October 2016, production was confirmed to have commenced under the working title of ''Saw: Legacy''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3408599/saw-legacy-production-beginning-exclusive/|title='Saw: Legacy': Production Beginning (Exclusive)|last=Barkan|first=Jonathan|date=October 1, 2016|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=October 2, 2016}}</ref> The film was shot in [[Toronto]] in November 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://dailyhive.com/toronto/movies-tv-series-filming-toronto-2016 |title=7 major movies and TV series filming in Toronto right now |first=Lloyd |last=Braun |work=[[Daily Hive]] |date=November 16, 2016 |access-date=October 27, 2018}}</ref> and entered post-production by January.<ref name=\"cast2\" /> On March 2, 2017, ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' revealed the first plot details and a full actor list, confirming that Tobin Bell would return in the role of [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]].<ref name=\"PlotTobin\">{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3426678/exclusive-weve-got-first-saw-legacy-plot-details-tobin-bell-returning/|title=[Exclusive] We've Got the First 'Saw: Legacy' Plot Details; Tobin Bell Returning!|last1=Squires|first1=John|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> In June 2017, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] listed the film under the official title of ''Jigsaw'', rating it R, for \"sequences of grisly bloody violence and torture, and for language\".<ref name=\"RatingTitle\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filmratings.com/Search?filmTitle=jigsaw&x=0&y=0| title=Jigsaw (2017) | work=The Classification and Rating Adiministration | publisher=[[Motion Picture Association of America]] | accessdate=June 7, 2017}}</ref> On August 14, 2017, the film passed uncut in the United Kingdom with an [[18 (British Board of Film Classification)|18 Certificate]] by the BBFC.<ref name=\"RatingTitle\" /><ref name=\"18cert\" /> In regard to the new title, writer Josh Stolberg clarified that \"when a writer is writing a movie, they put something on the cover page to separate it from other films. So when we were writing this film, the title read ''Saw: Legacy'' but it was never official or 'decided'.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/890407708003770369|title=So when we're were writing this film, the title read \"Saw: Legacy\" but it was never official or \"decided\". (3/3)|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=13 July 2017|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=27 July 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727065404/https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/890407708003770369|archivedate=July 27, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n\n===Poster releases===\nOn September 16, 2017, [[Lionsgate]] released five posters to promote ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.showbizjunkies.com/movies/jigsaw-character-posters/|title='Jigsaw' Unveils New Jigsaw's Army Character Posters|last=Murray|first=Rebecca|date=September 15, 2017|work=Showbiz Junkies|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The posters show off people in the traditional [[Billy the Puppet]] makeup, captioned \"He is Everything. He is Everywhere. He is Everyone\". The release of the posters was Lionsgate's way of reasserting the series' dominance over the Halloween season.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/09/15/jigsaw-will-open-in-imax-and-may-send-saw-over-the-1-billion-mark/#1a8687338a2d|title='Jigsaw' Will Open In IMAX And May Send 'Saw' Over The $1 Billion Mark|last=Meldelson|first=Scott|date=September 15, 2017|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Halloween Blood Drive===\nThe Annual Blood Drive is the series' tradition, where before the release of the films in October, mobile blood stations are set up around the United States, where fans who donate blood receive a free ticket to see the respective film of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dreadcentral.com/news/253468/jigsaws-nurses-back-saw-blood-drive/|title=Jigsaw's Nurses Are Back With the Saw Blood Drive|last=Barton|first=Steve|date=September 25, 2017|work=[[Dread Central]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref> The tradition started in 2004, after the overwhelming success of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', and continued for each of the sequels until it stopped in 2009 before the release of ''[[Saw VI]]''. Due to the arrival of ''Jigsaw'' in October, the blood drive was revived for another year, promoting the film with eight posters released by [[Lionsgate]], featuring \"Nurses\" [[Grae Drake]], Dan Rockwell, [[Susanne Bartsch|Susanne Bartch]], [[Nyakim Gatwech]], [[Shaun Ross (model)|Shaun Ross]], [[Mosh (model)|Mosh]], Mykie, and [[Amanda Lepore|Amanda LePore]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movieweb.com/jigsaw-movie-posters-nurses-saw-8-blood-drive/|title=New Saw 8 Posters Unleash Jigsaw's Blood-Starved Nurses|last=Gallagher|first=Brian|date=September 25, 2017|website=[[MovieWeb]]|accessdate=September 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 25, 2017, 120,000 pints (57,000 L) of blood had been donated, which has led to over 360,000 lives being saved.<ref>https://movieweb.com/jigsaw-movie-posters-nurses-saw-8-blood-drive/</ref>\n\n==Music==\n[[Charlie Clouser]], who provided the score for all previous entries in the ''Saw'' series, returned to score ''Jigsaw''. Clouser re-imagined the music of the ''Saw'' franchise, following the six year hiatus between ''Saw 3D'' and ''Jigsaw''. Clouser stated in 2016, \"this will be an opportunity [for me] to re-imagine how [I] approach the score, and [I] will be trying a more stark, bold, and stripped-down approach that will be more in line with the strong vision that the Spierig brothers are bringing to the table\".<ref name=\"Composer\" /> The soundtrack of the film was distributed digitally on October 27, 2017. Some tracks from the film can also be found on Volume 2 of the ''Saw'' Anthology Collection.\n\n==Release==\n''Jigsaw'' was released in the United Kingdom on October 26, 2017, and in the United States theatrically on October 27, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/saw-8-jigsaw-release-date-trailer-halloween-serial-killer-tobin-bell-a7801241.html|title='Saw 8' release date announced: Horror franchise to return with 'Jigsaw'|last=Stolworthy|first=Jacob|date=June 21, 2017|work=|accessdate=August 13, 2017|website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> It was featured in [[IMAX]] screenings for the first week of its theatrical run.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Box office===\n''Jigsaw'' has grossed $38.1 million in the United States and Canada, and $64.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $102.9 million, against a production budget of $10 million.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=https://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2017.htm|title=Jigsaw (2017)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=December 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Jigsaw'' was released alongside ''[[Thank You for Your Service (2017 film)|Thank You for Your Service]]'' and ''[[Suburbicon]]'', and is projected to gross around $20 million from 2,941 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/jigsaw-boo2-a-madea-halloween-george-clooney-suburbicon-box-office-weekend-preview-1202194368/|title=Jigsaw' Looks To Keep 'Saw' Franchise Sharp During Pre-Halloween Weekend With $20M+ Opening|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=October 25, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref> It made $1.6 million from Thursday night previews at 2,400 theaters, just below the $1.7 million ''Saw 3D'' made from midnight screenings seven years prior, and $7.2 million on its first day. It went on to open to $16.64 million, finishing first at the box office but marking the second lowest debut of the franchise.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/jigsaw-george-clooney-suburbicon-madea-halloween-thank-you-for-your-service-1202196050/|title=Horror Has Few Scares At B.O. As 'Jigsaw' Dulls To $16M+, 'Suburbicon' Condemned With D- CinemaScore|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=October 29, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> In its second weekend the film dropped 61% to $6.56 million, finishing third behind newcomers ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'' and ''[[A Bad Moms Christmas]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-a-bad-moms-christmas-huge-box-office-weekend-1202200942/|title='Thor: Ragnarok\u2019 Flexes His Box Office Muscles To $120M-$122M Opening \u2013 Early Sunday AM Update|author=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=November 6, 2017|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> In its third weekend, the film dropped another 47% and made $3.43 million, finishing fifth.\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 33% based on 87 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 4.76/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Jigsaw'' definitely won't win many converts to the ''Saw'' franchise, but for longtime fans, it should prove a respectably revolting\u2014if rarely scary\u2014diversion.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|title=''Jigsaw'' (2017)|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media|Fandango]] |accessdate=October 26, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 39 out of 100, based on 18 critics, indicating \"generally unfavorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|title=''Jigsaw'' reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported women under 25 (21% of the film's audience) and older males (30%) gave it a 76% and 70% overall positive score, respectively.<ref name=opening/>\n\n''[[IGN]]'' gave the film a score of 4.5/10, writing \"The good news is, ''Jigsaw'' is not the worst horror movie of the year. The bad news is, it's still bad enough that that's the good news...[It] doesn't capture what made the [[Saw (franchise)|''Saw'' franchise]] work in the first place.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ign.com/articles/2017/10/27/jigsaw-review|title=Jigsaw Review|last=Bibbiani|first=William|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[IGN]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> Darren French of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a \"C\", calling it disappointing and overly long.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/10/27/jigsaw-is-a-bloody-mess-ew-review/|title=Jigsaw is a bloody mess: EW review|last=Franich|first=Darren|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> ''[[Bloody Disgusting]]'' gave the film two and a half out of five, saying the film \"while being a fun ride, fails to justify its existence with a story that is overly familiar and a twist that doesn't live up to most of its predecessors\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/reviews/3466635/review-jigsaw/|title=[Review] The Overly Familiar 'Jigsaw' Still Manages to Be Fun|last=Thurman|first=Trace|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s [[Owen Gleiberman]] found the film \"garishly rote\" saying \"For 92 minutes, it more or less succeeds in sawing through your boredom, slicing and dicing with a glum explicitness that raises the occasional tingle of gross-out suspense but no longer carries any kick of true shock value.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/jigsaw-review-tobin-bell-1202600173/|title=Film Review: 'Jigsaw'|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|authorlink=Owen Gleiberman|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> Germain Lussier of ''[[io9]]'' largely panned the film saying \"[it] is one of the better films in the [[Saw (franchise)|franchise]]. Unfortunately, that's not saying much.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://io9.gizmodo.com/jigsaw-is-pretty-bad-which-still-makes-it-one-of-the-b-1819913359|title=Jigsaw Is Pretty Bad, Which Still Makes It One of the Better Saw Movies|last=Lussier|first=Germain|date=October 27, 2017|website=[[io9]]|access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Jigsaw'' was released digitally on January 9, 2018, and on 4K [[Ultra HD Blu-ray]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[DVD]] on January 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/home-video/3474074/trap-set-jigsaw-returns-4k-hd-blu-ray-dvd-digital-hd-exclusive/|title=The Trap is Set! \u2018Jigsaw\u2019 Returns On 4K HD, Blu-ray, DVD, and Digital HD! [Exclusive]|last=Miska|first=Brad|date=December 12, 2017|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|access-date=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Sequel==\n{{Main|Spiral (2020 film)}}\n\nThe ninth installment of the ''Saw'' franchise known as ''Spiral'' is an upcoming American horror film that is the sequel to ''Jigsaw''. The sequel film,  directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], stars [[Chris Rock]], [[Samuel L. Jackson]], [[Max Minghella]], and [[Marisol Nichols]]. Production took place in [[Toronto]] from July to August 2019. [[Lionsgate Films]] planned to release ''Spiral'' in theaters on May 15, 2020, however the film was pulled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/lionsgate-takes-antebellum-run-spiral-off-release-calendar-for-the-time-being-1202886268/|title=Lionsgate Takes \u2018Antebellum\u2019, \u2018Run\u2019 & \u2018Spiral\u2019 Off Release Calendar For The Time Being|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[List of horror films of the 2010s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|jigsawsaves.com}}\n* {{IMDb title|3348730}}\n\n{{Saw}}\n{{Michael and Peter Spierig}}\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:2017 horror films]]\n[[Category:Crime horror films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American horror films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Charlie Clouser]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Saw films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:2010s sequel films]]\n[[Category:Torture in films]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:7ef6:9800:c5b7:fd1f:d7c:7635", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jigsaw_(2017_film)"}
